WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.120
[Amit Varma]: What is your instinctive reaction when you hear an outrageous idea that challenges conventional

00:00:10.120 --> 00:00:14.640
[Amit Varma]: wisdom? I think all of us recoil a little bit because it is tempting to stick to our

00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:19.300
[Amit Varma]: picture of how the world works, what is possible and what is not possible. It takes too much

00:00:19.300 --> 00:00:23.960
[Amit Varma]: mental energy to keep shifting our frameworks as it were. But over time, I've learned

00:00:23.960 --> 00:00:28.720
[Amit Varma]: to fight this reflexive reaction. Humanity progresses not because of those who follow

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:34.720
[Amit Varma]: the conventional path and build better mousetraps, but because of those who dream audacious dreams.

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:39.200
[Amit Varma]: That is why, for example, I don't join in the fashionable mockery of Elon Musk. Just

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:43.080
[Amit Varma]: look at the things he's done and is trying to do. Bloody hell, we need a hundred more

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:48.480
[Amit Varma]: Elon Musks. We need to celebrate moonshots and crazy ideas. We need to let dreamers keep

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:53.360
[Amit Varma]: chasing their dreams. And yes, they'll often fail. But when they succeed, they can change

00:00:53.360 --> 00:01:01.360
[Unknown]: the world. Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:11.440
[Unknown]: podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:15.560
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen. My guest today is Vinay Singhal, who was born in a

00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:20.400
[Amit Varma]: small village in Haryana and who was the first graduate in his family. His earliest ambition

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:24.200
[Amit Varma]: was to be the richest man in the world. When he read that Bill Gates was the richest man

00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:28.960
[Amit Varma]: in the world at that time, he decided to out-Gates Gates by building the best operating system

00:01:28.960 --> 00:01:33.480
[Amit Varma]: in the world. That didn't go far, but he did go on to build a site called WittyFeed that

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:38.480
[Amit Varma]: for a while was second in the world only to BuzzFeed for viral content. That journey ended

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:43.600
[Amit Varma]: suddenly and devastated Vinay. He spent time moaning and introspecting and then dreaming

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:49.420
[Amit Varma]: again. And now he runs Stage, which he describes as a Netflix for Bharat. Stage is more than

00:01:49.420 --> 00:01:54.720
[Amit Varma]: an OTT for regional languages. It is an OTT for regional dialects. As he tells me in this

00:01:54.720 --> 00:02:00.280
[Amit Varma]: remarkable conversation, cities have languages, towns and villages have dialects, and we don't

00:02:00.280 --> 00:02:06.000
[Amit Varma]: need to homogenize culture. Instead, we need to celebrate our diversity by enabling it.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.880
[Amit Varma]: So far, Stage creates content not in Hindi or Tamil or Bengali or such major languages,

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:15.700
[Amit Varma]: but dialects like Haryanvi and Rajasthani, and has led to almost a reverse migration

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:21.000
[Amit Varma]: from Bollywood as industries have sprung up around those dialects. People who speak them

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:26.480
[Amit Varma]: no longer feel like outcasts in big cities needing to lose themselves to fit in. I was

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:31.880
[Amit Varma]: blown away by my conversation with Vinay for two reasons. One, the depth of his self-reflection,

00:02:31.880 --> 00:02:36.780
[Amit Varma]: which made him learn from every setback and become a better person. And two, the audacity

00:02:36.780 --> 00:02:41.520
[Amit Varma]: of his dreams and the clarity of his thinking. I left our conversation as a believer, not

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:46.600
[Amit Varma]: just in this venture, but in Vinay himself. This man will do amazing things. Before you

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:53.120
[Amit Varma]: see for yourself why I felt that way, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:56.680
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer, but never quite gotten down to it? Well, I'd love

00:02:56.680 --> 00:03:01.360
[Amit Varma]: to help you. Since April 2020, I've taught 20 cohorts of my online course, The Art of

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:05.800
[Amit Varma]: Clear Writing. An online community has now sprung up of all my past students. We have

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:10.740
[Amit Varma]: workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students, and vibrant community interaction.

00:03:10.740 --> 00:03:15.240
[Amit Varma]: In the course itself, through 4 webinars spread over 4 weekends, I share all I know about

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:19.640
[Amit Varma]: the craft and practice of clear writing. There are many exercises, much interaction, a lovely

00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:25.200
[Amit Varma]: and lively community at the end of it. The course costs Rs 10,000 plus GST or about $150

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:29.680
[Amit Varma]: and is a monthly thing. So if you're interested, head on over to register at indiauncut.com

00:03:29.680 --> 00:03:35.320
[Amit Varma]: slash clear writing. That's indiauncut.com slash clear writing. Being a good writer doesn't

00:03:35.320 --> 00:03:40.400
[Amit Varma]: require God-given talent, just the willingness to work hard and a clear idea of what you

00:03:40.400 --> 00:03:43.320
[Amit Varma]: need to do to refine your skills. I can help you.

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:49.440
[Amit Varma]: Vinay, welcome to the scene and the unseen. Thank you, Amit. It's a pleasure. Absolute

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:53.440
[Amit Varma]: pleasure. Thank you. Ever since a couple of months back, you agreed to come on the show

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:57.480
[Amit Varma]: when I was in Delhi next. I've been looking forward to, you know, before we talk about

00:03:57.480 --> 00:04:01.960
[Amit Varma]: Witty Feed and before we talk about Stage.in, let's sort of talk about you and talk about

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:05.720
[Amit Varma]: your early life. You know, where did you grow up? What was your childhood like? Tell me

00:04:05.720 --> 00:04:14.720
[Guest]: about that. So I grew up in a very small village in Haryana, 50-60 old houses. So much so that

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:19.880
[Guest]: I was the first ever engineer from my village that way. And first ever graduate in my own

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:25.120
[Guest]: family basically. Nobody had gone to a college before me, essentially. So I grew up there.

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:32.120
[Guest]: It's a Hindi medium school. I went to a private school that way. And so grew up there mostly.

00:04:32.120 --> 00:04:39.760
[Guest]: My family, my father, my mom, both of them are, so to say, unperturbed, illiterates that

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:44.440
[Guest]: way, right? I don't know if that's the right way to address them, but they were very aware

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:51.280
[Guest]: about the fact that kids should be taught. And so they made a lot of focus on that. So

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:58.080
[Guest]: sent me to a private school, essentially. Grew up around that. After that, we shifted

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:04.960
[Guest]: to a town in English medium school for the first time. First time in 9th grade, I basically

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:16.240
[Guest]: reached English medium school. And before that, I was good at studies, basically. And

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:21.440
[Guest]: basically I used to be a class-topper, school-topper, that way. Very favorite of my teachers, so

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:25.440
[Guest]: to say, right? You do well in the village, anyways, like that. And I reached English

00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:29.760
[Guest]: medium school. And English medium school, I was basically at the bottom of the list

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:35.600
[Guest]: because I couldn't understand what was going on, basically, right? And I remember an anecdote

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:42.080
[Guest]: actually from my school that way. It was a chemistry class, 9th grade. And our teacher,

00:05:42.080 --> 00:05:47.920
[Guest]: she was a South Indian, so Pandey ma'am, and I over time grew very fond of her. But anyway,

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:53.000
[Guest]: initial days, she was South Indian, so a certain accent of English, her Hindi had a certain

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:57.840
[Guest]: accent, etc, right? So she was teaching. And I was sitting, I couldn't understand anything,

00:05:57.840 --> 00:06:02.800
[Guest]: basically. I was clueless. So I was sitting with a book upside down, basically. And, sorry,

00:06:02.800 --> 00:06:07.560
[Guest]: not upside down, actually I was sitting with a physics book in that class. And she was

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:14.360
[Guest]: like, Vinay, what happened? Which class are you in? Chemistry class. The book is of physics.

00:06:14.360 --> 00:06:18.360
[Guest]: And which is when I was like, what the hell? But anyways, yeah, so made my way through

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:28.760
[Guest]: it. It's a scene where you come in first in the class, favorite of your teacher, etc.

00:06:28.760 --> 00:06:33.660
[Guest]: And then you are basically nobody, nobody, you're at the bottom of the class, nobody

00:06:33.660 --> 00:06:38.200
[Guest]: cares about you. Nobody, basically, asks who are the backbenchers, who are not getting

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:44.080
[Guest]: good marks, right? So I kind of made a sort of a determination that in 10th class, when

00:06:44.080 --> 00:06:51.280
[Guest]: I pass out of CBSE, I will become a topper in the school, essentially, again, basically.

00:06:51.280 --> 00:06:56.240
[Guest]: And anybody I would have told would have basically laughed at it, right? I remember, I had a

00:06:56.240 --> 00:07:03.120
[Guest]: study table in my house. I sketched it with my own hands. And I said, 94%, basically,

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:08.920
[Guest]: my dream for 10th class. And in 9th class, I hardly passed, basically, I must have scored

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:17.000
[Guest]: some marks, essentially, and continue to work very hard. Again, preboards, rewards. At the

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:24.320
[Guest]: end of it, when I passed the class, I actually topped it. I scored 93.5% marks. So it was

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:30.920
[Guest]: probably one of the early achievements of life. And that way, I felt that if you put

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:35.680
[Guest]: your mind to something, if you, if I really, you know, go after something, I probably can

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:41.000
[Guest]: do anything. It kind of made me believe that, yeah, I can do anything. There's nothing that

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:46.800
[Guest]: I can't do, right? So I did that. After staying there for two years, again, after 10th class,

00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:52.320
[Guest]: it was time to decide what I wanted to do in life, basically, right? So, from my village,

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:55.520
[Guest]: from my school, basically, I didn't have any education at home, so who would have told

00:07:55.520 --> 00:08:03.560
[Guest]: me what I wanted to do in life, right? So, many of the students were going to Kota, essentially.

00:08:03.560 --> 00:08:07.640
[Guest]: And I asked them, what are you going to do there? What is the Kota scene, essentially?

00:08:07.640 --> 00:08:11.840
[Guest]: So they told me that there is such coaching, doctors will be made. Some of my good friends

00:08:11.840 --> 00:08:18.600
[Guest]: were Dr. Allen Institute, of the very famous Allen, of course. At that time, it was not

00:08:18.600 --> 00:08:24.640
[Guest]: a very known name, at least in my village. So we will go there and all. And I somehow

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:30.520
[Guest]: had this vague idea in my mind that my father wanted me to become a doctor. And so I said,

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:35.560
[Guest]: man, I will also go to Kota, I will become a doctor. So I landed in Kota, spent two years

00:08:35.560 --> 00:08:40.080
[Guest]: over there, quite interesting, quite an amazing journey. Going there, for the first time in

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:46.040
[Guest]: my life, I discovered medical, non-medical, different streams. I discovered that, IITs,

00:08:46.040 --> 00:08:51.440
[Guest]: NITs, and AIIMS, and all these institutes. For the first time in my life, I came to know

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:57.240
[Guest]: the meaning of MCQ. And in the process, I also ended up discovering that there is something

00:08:57.240 --> 00:09:01.800
[Guest]: called passion. People live and die for it. I actually discovered the word passion in

00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:06.560
[Guest]: Kota. Kota, actually, I did not become a doctor, but it was the turning point of my life, in

00:09:06.560 --> 00:09:13.480
[Guest]: a way. I really believe that those were the two most important years of my life. And I

00:09:13.480 --> 00:09:19.640
[Guest]: probably learned more about life in those two years than I learned in probably the rest

00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:24.560
[Guest]: of my life at that point in time. For the first time, you step out of the protection

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:34.640
[Guest]: and you realize that it's such a huge world, right? Kota was the definition of huge world

00:09:34.640 --> 00:09:39.400
[Guest]: to me, but it was such a huge world still, right? Big buildings, AIIMS, you know, and

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:46.000
[Guest]: all of that stuff, basically. So I spent two years in Kota, and there was a lot that happened

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:53.640
[Guest]: around that time. Just one more thing before I finish this part. I discovered, when I saw

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:59.040
[Guest]: a computer for the first time, when I was in 10th class, when I was in 10th class, I

00:09:59.040 --> 00:10:02.840
[Guest]: saw a computer for the first time in my life, in our lab. I saw it in the lab on the 9th.

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:09.040
[Guest]: On the 10th, I had a computer with a senior, basically, and classmates, some of our classmates

00:10:09.040 --> 00:10:13.720
[Guest]: would gather and say, we have to prepare a model test paper, a CBC exam paper, so let's

00:10:13.720 --> 00:10:20.040
[Guest]: get it from the internet. And we went and he did something, and all of a sudden he had

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:24.960
[Guest]: papers and he wrote. And basically, that was the time when I saw it with internet for the

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:28.800
[Guest]: first time. Computer plus internet, I saw for the first time. He wrote on Google, CBC

00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:32.920
[Guest]: model test papers, a website came, everything was there, he took it out. And to me, it was

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:39.040
[Guest]: all magic. Basically, he wanted anything, and I asked him a lot of questions, and he

00:10:39.040 --> 00:10:42.640
[Guest]: was like, yes, whatever you want on the internet, write it, you get everything here, and all

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:48.640
[Guest]: that stuff, right? I think I fell in love with computers on, like love at first sight

00:10:48.640 --> 00:10:55.320
[Guest]: sort of scene, basically, right? And so I made my father buy me one. Like, within the

00:10:55.320 --> 00:11:00.320
[Guest]: next 60 days, I think we bought one. It was a big deal. It was a big event in our house,

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:04.360
[Guest]: right? It was about 100 kilometers away from our village, in a town called Jhunjhunu. We

00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:08.320
[Guest]: went to buy a computer from there, because my uncle was on that side, so if you need

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:12.040
[Guest]: someone to tell you, because a machine for 35-40 thousand rupees is a very big deal.

00:11:12.040 --> 00:11:18.600
[Guest]: Who buys a computer? It was something that was, and again, in the 10th grade, most people

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:22.800
[Guest]: would tell my father, why are you buying it? He'll play games on it, he won't do anything,

00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:26.440
[Guest]: basically, right? And what is the need in the 10th grade and all, but I somehow felt

00:11:26.440 --> 00:11:30.760
[Guest]: that if I learn something from this, I'll basically do something other than what everybody

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:35.960
[Guest]: else is doing and all, right? So, he brought me from Jhunjhunu in the 10th grade, and again,

00:11:35.960 --> 00:11:42.120
[Guest]: for me, the internet was the entire meaning of it, right? So, the dial-up connection back

00:11:42.120 --> 00:11:49.280
[Guest]: in the day, the 256 kbps connections, right? Now, with the scratch card of SNL, I connected

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:58.280
[Guest]: it and the first search that I made on it was, who is the richest person in the world?

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:04.080
[Guest]: And of course, the irony of life, Bill Gates came at that time, and how did he become?

00:12:04.080 --> 00:12:10.440
[Guest]: He became, that he made computers, which I'm using today, basically, this box useful, essentially.

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:15.880
[Guest]: Like, he made it, he made the software, which made it useful for everybody. And so, everybody

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:20.720
[Guest]: has a PC today, right? And so, his operating system was the best in the world. So, everybody

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:26.960
[Guest]: bought it at that one time. And so, whatever, basically, the simpler definition of it. So,

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:34.800
[Guest]: I grew up in a Marwadi family, basically, Baniyas, my father used to run that, right?

00:12:34.800 --> 00:12:44.800
[Guest]: And so, if there is one topic that you want to discuss and have some commonality in a

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:49.080
[Guest]: Baniya family or in a Marwadi family, it's money. That's something that you grow up with

00:12:49.080 --> 00:12:56.480
[Guest]: that. I keep joking that, and then all of a sudden, you come and say, everybody will

00:12:56.480 --> 00:13:02.320
[Guest]: like be quiet and listen to you, essentially, right? So, I grew up around the idea of money

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:07.640
[Guest]: a lot, right? And so, the other part, which is that I wanted to be best at it, I don't

00:13:07.640 --> 00:13:13.040
[Guest]: know how, but somehow, my life has always been, I feel that if I do something, I should

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:17.000
[Guest]: do my best in life, then there is no point in doing less than that. So, money was the

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:23.480
[Guest]: definition of success, told by my family to me, and my surroundings, and best is what

00:13:23.480 --> 00:13:28.600
[Guest]: I wanted to become. So, my first aspiration in life became that I want to become the richest

00:13:28.600 --> 00:13:33.800
[Guest]: person in the world. That was my sort of a goal that way, right? But I ended up in quota

00:13:33.800 --> 00:13:40.280
[Guest]: to become a doctor, and which is where I discovered that I don't want to become a doctor. So,

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:45.360
[Guest]: a lot of these points in my life story that you will probably discover now in next couple

00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:53.000
[Guest]: of hours is that it has been a lot about what do I not want to do, instead of to be able

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.880
[Guest]: to figure out what do I want to do, right? I think that is also a very efficient system.

00:13:56.880 --> 00:14:01.160
[Guest]: If you understand that you don't want to do this, then you have at least one less option

00:14:01.160 --> 00:14:06.120
[Guest]: to worry about, right? We were taught in the preparation of AIPMT that there are four options,

00:14:06.120 --> 00:14:10.760
[Guest]: either you know the answer, or you know which three are wrong, right? So, you can also find

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:15.560
[Guest]: an answer by elimination. So, probably that kind of state with me, right? So, I discovered

00:14:15.560 --> 00:14:20.280
[Guest]: that I don't want to become a doctor. I used to score physics, chemistry, and bio in three

00:14:20.280 --> 00:14:27.280
[Guest]: classes, right? So, it used to be like 50-50 and 100. 50-50 marks in physics and 100 marks

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:30.280
[Guest]: in chemistry. Basically, I used to get double marks. I don't know the exact number now.

00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:34.280
[Guest]: I don't remember it. So, I used to get equal marks in all three classes. I used to get

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:41.280
[Guest]: 50 marks in physics and 100 marks in biology, right? So, it kind of got clear that I don't

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:48.000
[Guest]: want to become a doctor, right? But then I had made my father spend so much money being

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:52.280
[Guest]: there and all, right? So, it was very hard to go back. So, I used those two years to

00:14:52.280 --> 00:14:57.280
[Guest]: figure out what to do. Let's understand a little. Let's not become a doctor. So, I remembered

00:14:57.280 --> 00:15:00.480
[Guest]: that when you got a computer, you wanted to become the richest person in the world. How

00:15:00.480 --> 00:15:05.480
[Guest]: do you become? How do the richest people in the world become? And I remembered that Bill

00:15:05.480 --> 00:15:10.680
[Guest]: Gates is there. Bill Gates made the operating system. So, that's what happened. So, I decided

00:15:10.680 --> 00:15:14.560
[Guest]: that it's very simple. I don't want to do anything. I want to make an operating system

00:15:14.560 --> 00:15:18.800
[Guest]: which is better than this one. If I make an operating system better than Windows, then

00:15:18.800 --> 00:15:22.200
[Guest]: the whole world will use my operating system and I will become the richest person in the

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:27.800
[Guest]: world. I literally used to carry a pocket diary and I would write features. Like, I

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:34.600
[Guest]: will make this, this is missing in Windows and all of that stuff basically, right? So,

00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:40.120
[Guest]: but I went to become a doctor in Kota. So, what to do? So, my father's dream and plus

00:15:40.120 --> 00:15:44.560
[Guest]: believing that it's my father's dream. So, I made a plan that let's do one thing. First,

00:15:44.560 --> 00:15:48.840
[Guest]: I will do MBBS. Then I will do MBA because we can do business with it. And then I will

00:15:48.840 --> 00:15:54.480
[Guest]: make this company and that's how I will become this thing and all, right? After two years,

00:15:54.480 --> 00:16:00.120
[Guest]: I wrote AIPMT exams, all that stuff, right? So, I was doing BDS, BDS basically, right?

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:05.720
[Guest]: But I knew that if I do this, then basically it will be a miserable life. I don't want

00:16:05.720 --> 00:16:10.880
[Guest]: to become a doctor no matter what. And I gathered courage. I came back home. I came from Kota.

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:15.160
[Guest]: It takes around 5-6 lakhs to stay there for at least two years, right? And it was a very

00:16:15.160 --> 00:16:22.520
[Guest]: big amount for a family, which is basically running a grocery store, right? So, I courageously

00:16:22.520 --> 00:16:27.800
[Guest]: said to my father, sorry, I know you want me to become a doctor, but I don't want to

00:16:27.800 --> 00:16:35.960
[Guest]: become a doctor. And he was like, when did I ask you to become a doctor? So, I was like,

00:16:35.960 --> 00:16:40.280
[Guest]: what happened? I was there for two years for no reason. I don't care if you become a doctor

00:16:40.280 --> 00:16:46.600
[Guest]: or not. And then he said something, I think that became one of the most important cornerstones

00:16:46.600 --> 00:16:54.000
[Guest]: of my life, sensibly. He said, look, son, I have spent my life here in the village,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:58.320
[Guest]: I have worked very hard, I have lived with respect, basically, right? I have never borrowed

00:16:58.320 --> 00:17:03.280
[Guest]: money from anyone, I have given it to someone. And again, in his way of living a respectable

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:07.480
[Guest]: life, right? All I want from you is, I don't care if you are successful or not, it's okay,

00:17:07.480 --> 00:17:12.200
[Guest]: it's not necessary in life, everyone will be successful and all. But I just want that

00:17:12.200 --> 00:17:20.960
[Guest]: my head should never be high because of you, it should never be low. And I was of course,

00:17:20.960 --> 00:17:27.440
[Guest]: I teared up and I was like, it stayed with me. And I think till date, when I make decisions,

00:17:27.440 --> 00:17:32.400
[Guest]: I go back, think about it, that I am not doing anything which is going to probably make him

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:36.960
[Guest]: feel bad about it. And his head should not be low, basically, that's what I keep remembering.

00:17:36.960 --> 00:17:43.360
[Guest]: So, from there, he told me, I came to Delhi, I went to CBSC's office, I said, I am a biological

00:17:43.360 --> 00:17:46.960
[Guest]: student, but I want to become an engineer. So, that I figured out that if I want to make

00:17:46.960 --> 00:17:50.960
[Guest]: a computing system, then basically, I will have to become an engineer, I will have to

00:17:50.960 --> 00:17:54.960
[Guest]: do computer engineering. So, for that, I need non-medical, I had discovered all that in Kota.

00:17:54.960 --> 00:18:00.960
[Guest]: So, here in Delhi, in Paharganj, there is an office in CBSC, I came there. So, I went

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:04.960
[Guest]: and said, boss, I have to do engineering, what should I do? Which is when they told

00:18:04.960 --> 00:18:08.960
[Guest]: me that you write a supplementary exam for maths. And if you pass in maths this year,

00:18:08.960 --> 00:18:14.960
[Guest]: then it will be done. And I took an admission in Akash Institute in Janakpuri. So, there,

00:18:14.960 --> 00:18:18.960
[Guest]: when I went to the first class of maths, you are sitting in dropper ears again, right?

00:18:18.960 --> 00:18:24.960
[Guest]: So, the teacher came, he did the first chapter, I remember only one thing of 11th and 12th

00:18:24.960 --> 00:18:30.960
[Guest]: maths, which is the first chapter of subsets. So, there are symbols of subsets and basically,

00:18:30.960 --> 00:18:36.960
[Guest]: there are ups and downs, essentially, right? So, he came and started teaching all this.

00:18:36.960 --> 00:18:40.960
[Guest]: And he was teaching dropper ears, what was the teacher's fault? I asked the person

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:44.960
[Guest]: in the class, brother, what does this mean? The one who is making C upside down, sometimes

00:18:44.960 --> 00:18:48.960
[Guest]: here, sometimes there, what does this mean? And which is when this guy says, what are

00:18:48.960 --> 00:18:52.960
[Guest]: you doing? Are you making fun of me? I mean, you are sitting in dropper ears, you are

00:18:52.960 --> 00:18:55.960
[Guest]: sitting in the wrong class, what is the scene? I said, no, brother, you tell me, I do not

00:18:55.960 --> 00:18:59.960
[Guest]: know all this. Because I had no idea about 11th and 12th maths, what happens, what does

00:18:59.960 --> 00:19:04.960
[Guest]: not happen. But again, that year came out and thankfully, I passed in the maths exam.

00:19:04.960 --> 00:19:10.960
[Guest]: I have been scared twice in my life, which I remember very distinctly. One is when I

00:19:10.960 --> 00:19:15.960
[Guest]: wrote that maths board exam, I cried a lot before that night. Because if I fail in that

00:19:15.960 --> 00:19:22.960
[Guest]: exam, then there is no hope, essentially, because basically, I left biology a year ago

00:19:22.960 --> 00:19:27.960
[Guest]: and if I do not pass maths, then I cannot write engineering exams. I will not get into

00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:31.960
[Guest]: an engineering college. And I basically will be nowhere, right? And another 3-4 lakhs

00:19:31.960 --> 00:19:36.960
[Guest]: has gone down the drain for my father. So I cried a lot and went to write that exam.

00:19:36.960 --> 00:19:44.960
[Guest]: But again, thankfully, passed in that. I got some 68-69 marks. Again, exam, so distinctly

00:19:44.960 --> 00:19:49.960
[Guest]: I remember how many marks I got. Passed it, went into SRM and like that's how the engineering

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:52.960
[Guest]: journey started. I probably took a longer time to answer this.

00:19:52.960 --> 00:19:56.960
[Amit Varma]: No, no, it was beautiful. The story about your dad is also so moving. And what you said

00:19:56.960 --> 00:20:00.960
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, the first time you saw a computer and I had that same feeling in the

00:20:00.960 --> 00:20:04.960
[Amit Varma]: 90s, when the first time I discovered and someone told me you can search for anything

00:20:04.960 --> 00:20:08.960
[Amit Varma]: and all the pages that there are in the world on that subject, you can see them and this

00:20:08.960 --> 00:20:12.960
[Amit Varma]: was in the early days. So actually, there were limited pages. It's crazy, right? It's

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:17.960
[Amit Varma]: crazy. You can imagine that. I remember Arthur C. Clarke's quote that any sufficiently advanced

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:22.960
[Amit Varma]: technology is indistinguishable from magic. So I try to think about that and not take

00:20:22.960 --> 00:20:27.960
[Amit Varma]: all of this stuff for granted, whether it is computer internet or GPS or the AI that

00:20:27.960 --> 00:20:33.960
[Amit Varma]: is doing it. You know, it's all so magical, but we get very jaded. I want to ask you a

00:20:33.960 --> 00:20:38.960
[Amit Varma]: question following on from like this very interesting concept I learned recently, which

00:20:38.960 --> 00:20:43.960
[Amit Varma]: has made me introspect a lot and think a lot. I came across it in this book called Wanting

00:20:43.960 --> 00:20:49.960
[Amit Varma]: by Luke Burgess. And he was a disciple of the philosopher Rene Girard. So Rene Girard,

00:20:49.960 --> 00:20:53.960
[Amit Varma]: a few decades ago, he's a philosopher, but he was asked to teach a literature class.

00:20:53.960 --> 00:20:58.960
[Amit Varma]: So he needed the money. He said, okay, I'll teach you. So for that, he went through a

00:20:58.960 --> 00:21:02.960
[Amit Varma]: reading list. And when he read all those great novels, which were in the reading list, he

00:21:02.960 --> 00:21:07.960
[Amit Varma]: found that they all have one thing in common, that all the characters in the novel, the

00:21:07.960 --> 00:21:12.960
[Amit Varma]: main characters in the novel, what they want, they don't want it because it's a genuine

00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:17.960
[Amit Varma]: deep interior want, they want it because somebody else wants it. And he termed this thing mimetic

00:21:17.960 --> 00:21:25.960
[Amit Varma]: desire that, you know, you want something because somebody else wants it. Or if you're

00:21:25.960 --> 00:21:29.960
[Amit Varma]: a young person growing up in India, I'll get married, I'll have kids. But why? Because

00:21:29.960 --> 00:21:34.960
[Amit Varma]: it's the way things are done. So you think you want it, but you don't really. I got to

00:21:34.960 --> 00:21:43.960
[Amit Varma]: learn about the frame of thick desires and thin desires. Thick desire is what is intrinsic

00:21:43.960 --> 00:21:52.960
[Amit Varma]: to you. That's a thick desire. And a thin desire is a desire, which is not intrinsic

00:21:52.960 --> 00:22:03.960
[Amit Varma]: to you. And the interesting thing is that thin desires can be very intense. Whereas

00:22:03.960 --> 00:22:10.960
[Amit Varma]: a thick desire can hide in the background. That is going to be intense, not necessarily.

00:22:10.960 --> 00:22:15.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's very counterintuitive. So the thick desire can be hiding in the background. And

00:22:15.960 --> 00:22:20.960
[Amit Varma]: the thin desire, which can often be a desire for fame or money or whatever, can be in the

00:22:20.960 --> 00:22:26.960
[Amit Varma]: forefront can be intense. And so I'm interested in and this is both a question about you,

00:22:26.960 --> 00:22:30.960
[Amit Varma]: and also a question about the sort of milieu in which you grow up, grow up in the people

00:22:30.960 --> 00:22:38.960
[Amit Varma]: all around you. That an older question that I sometimes ask is, why those specific dreams?

00:22:38.960 --> 00:22:42.960
[Amit Varma]: Why do we want those things? Why do we want what we want, which you know, ties into this

00:22:42.960 --> 00:22:49.960
[Amit Varma]: question. And you've mentioned sort of turning on the computer and your first search is who

00:22:49.960 --> 00:22:53.960
[Amit Varma]: is the richest person in the world. Because obviously, if you're a young kid, you're growing

00:22:53.960 --> 00:22:56.960
[Amit Varma]: up in a village, that's the most important thing, right? You think that's what you want.

00:22:56.960 --> 00:23:02.960
[Amit Varma]: And I feel that what happens is that as we go along on that journey, initially, we might

00:23:02.960 --> 00:23:07.960
[Amit Varma]: want to be rich or famous or whatever. But later, it becomes modified in the sense that

00:23:07.960 --> 00:23:12.960
[Amit Varma]: we see money as a means to an end. Yeah, that something larger opens up, like I would

00:23:12.960 --> 00:23:17.960
[Amit Varma]: imagine what the internet would have opened up for you was a thick desire of learning

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:21.960
[Amit Varma]: about the world, and figuring out what to do and all of that. Yeah. So I want you to

00:23:21.960 --> 00:23:26.960
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit about sort of your dreams and your desires. Because what happens is

00:23:26.960 --> 00:23:30.960
[Amit Varma]: that if you have no exposure to the world, let's say you thought experiment, you have

00:23:30.960 --> 00:23:33.960
[Amit Varma]: a 10 year old who's grown up in a room for 10 years with no exposure to the world, what

00:23:33.960 --> 00:23:40.960
[Amit Varma]: does that person want? It's going to be very limited, right? But, you know, so it's all

00:23:40.960 --> 00:23:44.960
[Amit Varma]: it depends on what is your environment? What is your mahal? What do people around you want?

00:23:44.960 --> 00:23:49.960
[Amit Varma]: How society is evolving, that shapes you into wanting whatever you want. So you tell your

00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:54.960
[Amit Varma]: journey from this lens that what were the things you desired? And how did that during

00:23:54.960 --> 00:23:59.960
[Amit Varma]: these years sort of evolve? And also, I know, it's a separate question. So also, what people

00:23:59.960 --> 00:24:04.960
[Amit Varma]: around you, you know, what do you feel about that, that, in a sense, what you do through

00:24:04.960 --> 00:24:09.960
[Amit Varma]: your site, or what any content person really does in whatever they do, is they expand the

00:24:09.960 --> 00:24:15.960
[Amit Varma]: universe of their viewers. And in expanding that universe, you can make them want differently

00:24:15.960 --> 00:24:19.960
[Amit Varma]: because you're looking at the universe in a different way. Take me through this.

00:24:19.960 --> 00:24:24.960
[Guest]: Just to double click on the second part that you just said, I think, is one of the reasons

00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:30.960
[Guest]: why I got into content and I continue to remain in content is because I, one of my strongest

00:24:30.960 --> 00:24:35.960
[Guest]: belief is that there is nothing more powerful than content as a medium of mass influence.

00:24:35.960 --> 00:24:41.960
[Guest]: And yeah, we, by telling these stories, and by creating these different content pieces,

00:24:41.960 --> 00:24:45.960
[Guest]: we expand the horizon of the universe of a person who consumes that content, essentially,

00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:54.960
[Guest]: right? So, like I said, I think the very first aspiration in life I remember is becoming

00:24:54.960 --> 00:25:02.960
[Guest]: the richest person in the world, right? That's what I remember. It was, it has to be a thin

00:25:02.960 --> 00:25:09.960
[Guest]: desire because I no longer want it, one. And second, I now know for a fact that it was

00:25:09.960 --> 00:25:16.960
[Guest]: influenced by the environment around me, right? Like I said, the environment I grew up in,

00:25:16.960 --> 00:25:23.960
[Guest]: money is like probably one of the most important thing, you know, that you grow up around.

00:25:23.960 --> 00:25:27.960
[Guest]: And by the way, I don't mean that in a bad way. I don't think there is anything wrong

00:25:27.960 --> 00:25:32.960
[Guest]: with it. The world we live in, it runs on money. And so you need it. And the community

00:25:32.960 --> 00:25:37.960
[Guest]: that I come from has a certain way of taking care of it basically, right? And I think that

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:42.960
[Guest]: has helped me a lot in becoming the person that I become. I'm very careful about money.

00:25:42.960 --> 00:25:48.960
[Guest]: I'm very, I don't know, I think I know how to handle my finances. I'm a financially literate

00:25:48.960 --> 00:25:54.960
[Guest]: person that way. I'd like to believe that. And most of it comes from, again, the place

00:25:54.960 --> 00:26:01.960
[Guest]: where I grew up, right? But then I think growing up where we grew up, it was like a lower middle

00:26:01.960 --> 00:26:07.960
[Guest]: class setting, right? Gaon hai, 50-60 ghar hai, papa dukaan chala rahe hain. Dukaan chala

00:26:07.960 --> 00:26:13.960
[Guest]: rahe hain is probably a little too extreme, I'm saying. Gaon ke baniye hain, we were well

00:26:13.960 --> 00:26:20.960
[Guest]: to do relatively in that particular place. We would be very poor when you compare it

00:26:20.960 --> 00:26:25.960
[Guest]: with some place, let's say in Delhi, but in our village, we were okay to do, we were well

00:26:25.960 --> 00:26:36.960
[Guest]: to do, right? So, I basically understood about money. I understood about how to even build

00:26:36.960 --> 00:26:43.960
[Guest]: a business, you know, how to treat people, how to... So, for example, one of the best

00:26:43.960 --> 00:26:49.960
[Guest]: things about my father that I carried from him in my business is that gaon mein wahan

00:26:49.960 --> 00:26:55.960
[Guest]: aaj ka kaam bhi karte the dukaan mein, basically. Kisan se anaaj lena hain, phir mandi mein

00:26:55.960 --> 00:26:58.960
[Guest]: usko beechna, trader, basically, right? That way. So, you need a lot of labor to carry

00:26:58.960 --> 00:27:06.960
[Guest]: on those tasks, etc. And I know that all their lunch used to be cooked by my mom throughout.

00:27:06.960 --> 00:27:11.960
[Guest]: Ghar mein, woh wahiin baith ke khaana khaate the, jahaan hum khaate the, basically. And

00:27:11.960 --> 00:27:17.960
[Guest]: a lot of these people I would address as chacha, etc, etc, right? And which ended up giving

00:27:17.960 --> 00:27:23.960
[Guest]: me very important life lessons, like, people are people. Their economic status doesn't

00:27:23.960 --> 00:27:29.960
[Guest]: define who they are and how you treat them, essentially, basically, right? And I don't

00:27:29.960 --> 00:27:34.960
[Guest]: think my father was trying to teach me that, but he ended up basically teaching me that

00:27:34.960 --> 00:27:38.960
[Guest]: in the process and all, basically. Aisi aur bahot saari gaon... humari dukaan mein ek

00:27:38.960 --> 00:27:44.960
[Guest]: poster laga rehta tha and which I again carry with me till date and a philosophy that I

00:27:44.960 --> 00:27:50.960
[Guest]: use in my business. It used to say that, dukaan mera mandir, grahat mera devta. And you can

00:27:50.960 --> 00:27:57.960
[Guest]: find it in most of the Marwadi family shops, basically. And today, Jai Bajos writes a white

00:27:57.960 --> 00:28:01.960
[Guest]: paper on this saying that, you know, how, why should you build customer first businesses

00:28:01.960 --> 00:28:05.960
[Guest]: and whatever, basically, right? And becomes a huge philosophy and like the entire startup

00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:10.960
[Guest]: world is like, Jai Bajos is a god and all. But it was, it's as simple as that, right?

00:28:10.960 --> 00:28:18.960
[Guest]: Ki dukaan aapka woh holy space hai, where you build it. It has to be as holy as a temple,

00:28:18.960 --> 00:28:23.960
[Guest]: which means you hold yourself to the highest level of integrity, honesty, you do the most

00:28:23.960 --> 00:28:29.960
[Guest]: important things, etc. And then at the same time, grahat mera devta, that there's nothing

00:28:29.960 --> 00:28:34.960
[Guest]: bhagwan se upar toh kuch nahi hai. Toh grahat agar aapka bhagwan ke barabar hai, toh basically

00:28:34.960 --> 00:28:41.960
[Guest]: you treat them like that, right? So, I learned that and again, unknowingly, I carried it.

00:28:41.960 --> 00:28:45.960
[Guest]: I like to believe that we have built very customer first businesses over time and, and

00:28:45.960 --> 00:28:50.960
[Guest]: integrity has been one thing, one value that I don't like to compromise on. You do whatever,

00:28:50.960 --> 00:28:54.960
[Guest]: sab kuch maaf hai, lekin integrity pe aap compromise nahi kar sakte hai, essentially.

00:28:54.960 --> 00:28:59.960
[Guest]: Actually, yeh sab cheezein, again, mere environment, mere aas paas ke cheezein, how my family treated

00:28:59.960 --> 00:29:06.960
[Guest]: me and they behaved probably around that. So, I learned from there. Then once I went

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:15.960
[Guest]: to Kota and I discovered the world, I discovered that, like you said, money just means to an

00:29:15.960 --> 00:29:19.960
[Guest]: end. And I think I discovered it in Kota, but I didn't know it. And then I realized

00:29:19.960 --> 00:29:25.960
[Guest]: when I was in college, when I ended up in Chennai in college and like a 100x larger

00:29:25.960 --> 00:29:32.960
[Guest]: world suddenly opened up, right? Haryana to Kota is you don't, you don't get a culture

00:29:32.960 --> 00:29:38.960
[Guest]: shock. From there you go to Chennai and like you have a college which has like people from

00:29:38.960 --> 00:29:42.960
[Guest]: all over the country, including Chennai itself, etc. And like there's a culture shock that

00:29:42.960 --> 00:29:48.960
[Guest]: you realize that this country is so large, there's so many people. I, of course, I also

00:29:48.960 --> 00:29:55.960
[Guest]: had aged by then. So, I, and I had access to computer, internet, etc. So, my knowledge

00:29:55.960 --> 00:30:02.960
[Guest]: had expanded to a very large extent compared to where it was, again, relatively. So, now

00:30:02.960 --> 00:30:08.960
[Guest]: I knew that money only is a means to an end. Money allows you to do what you want to do,

00:30:08.960 --> 00:30:13.960
[Guest]: but it cannot be the goal because then you have a very shallow goal, right?

00:30:13.960 --> 00:30:21.960
[Guest]: You can make money through so many different ways, right? And it matters why you want to

00:30:21.960 --> 00:30:28.960
[Guest]: do what you want to do. And so, it matters how you make that money essentially. And then

00:30:28.960 --> 00:30:32.960
[Guest]: why do you want to make it the way you want to make it essentially, right? So, I think

00:30:32.960 --> 00:30:37.960
[Guest]: those questions became important. And credit where due, one of my college senior, his name

00:30:37.960 --> 00:30:44.960
[Guest]: is Harsh Manitrapati. He's an entrepreneur himself, sold one of his companies to UpGrad.

00:30:44.960 --> 00:30:49.960
[Guest]: So, he was the one who basically helped me discover this, you know, he, he asked me this

00:30:49.960 --> 00:30:54.960
[Guest]: in the first year, second year, we met in end of first year. So, he asked me in the

00:30:54.960 --> 00:30:58.960
[Guest]: second year that, why do you like, what do you want to do? What's your actual goal in

00:30:58.960 --> 00:31:02.960
[Guest]: life? And I used to say that I want to become the richest person and all that stuff, right?

00:31:02.960 --> 00:31:10.960
[Guest]: And he asked me why? And I gave all the wrong reasons. I don't want to work for anyone.

00:31:10.960 --> 00:31:15.960
[Guest]: I want to make a lot of money. I want to be famous. And I don't like to do a job. I don't

00:31:15.960 --> 00:31:21.960
[Guest]: think I made for a job, all of that stuff. And then I ended up at a place where I realized

00:31:21.960 --> 00:31:28.960
[Guest]: that, you know, it doesn't matter if I do a job, doesn't matter if I make a lot of money

00:31:28.960 --> 00:31:33.960
[Guest]: or not make a lot of money. I, what I want to do is that I want to do something that

00:31:33.960 --> 00:31:40.960
[Guest]: really matters that, that, you know, what gives me, for example, every time I watch

00:31:40.960 --> 00:31:49.960
[Guest]: a movie where an underdog wins, I cry, right? For when I see a scene filled with compassion

00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:53.960
[Guest]: without an exception, I cry, right? So, those are the things that make me click, right?

00:31:53.960 --> 00:31:59.960
[Guest]: And so, I realized that all I want to do is just help people. And if in the process, you

00:31:59.960 --> 00:32:04.960
[Guest]: know, if I can make a lot of money, great, awesome. If I, if not, then probably not,

00:32:04.960 --> 00:32:10.960
[Guest]: right? And which is why in the first year itself, and again, articulation happened in

00:32:10.960 --> 00:32:14.960
[Guest]: second year when Harsh Bia asked me about all this, but first year itself, I started

00:32:14.960 --> 00:32:20.960
[Guest]: an NGO. Again, I don't talk about it a lot anymore, but I started an NGO. I discovered

00:32:20.960 --> 00:32:25.960
[Guest]: that I'm a very patriotic person. I love my country and like very intrinsic desire to

00:32:25.960 --> 00:32:33.960
[Guest]: do something with the country and like all that feeling, right? So, I started an NGO

00:32:33.960 --> 00:32:40.960
[Guest]: called Badlega Bharat, and which was triggered by nothing but simple that I realized that

00:32:40.960 --> 00:32:47.960
[Guest]: youth in this country, we keep saying that 67% of the population of this country is a

00:32:47.960 --> 00:32:54.960
[Guest]: young population, below 35, assertive. But I saw most people around me in college were

00:32:54.960 --> 00:32:58.960
[Guest]: preparing for GRE, they're going to write an exam, go do MS somewhere and then never

00:32:58.960 --> 00:33:04.960
[Guest]: coming back, right? So, these guys are not assets, probably. These are, at least I thought

00:33:04.960 --> 00:33:09.960
[Guest]: at that point in time, again, has changed to a large extent now, but I thought these

00:33:09.960 --> 00:33:13.960
[Guest]: are liabilities. You know, these guys are just going to go away from this country. They're

00:33:13.960 --> 00:33:17.960
[Guest]: not going to probably come back here ever again, not care about this. They don't care

00:33:17.960 --> 00:33:25.960
[Guest]: the problems that we have in this country. I thought like that. And so, I said, nobody

00:33:25.960 --> 00:33:30.960
[Guest]: speaks to the youth in their language, the language that they understand. Nobody talks

00:33:30.960 --> 00:33:40.960
[Guest]: to us with respect and asks us, and what you're going to tell me, it matters. So, I started

00:33:40.960 --> 00:33:44.960
[Guest]: this NGO called Badlega Bharat. Then the idea was that we'll talk about the issues around

00:33:44.960 --> 00:33:49.960
[Guest]: youth, etc. in their own language, and we understand. So, it was also probably my first

00:33:49.960 --> 00:33:54.960
[Guest]: content company, because this NGO was nothing but a website. I learned to make websites

00:33:54.960 --> 00:34:01.960
[Guest]: just for that, along with, and I found my co-founders also because of that. One of the

00:34:01.960 --> 00:34:05.960
[Guest]: best things that happened to me ever, Shashank, Shashank Vaishnav, I found him because of

00:34:05.960 --> 00:34:10.960
[Guest]: that. So, we started this NGO called Badlega Bharat, and it was basically a blog, where

00:34:10.960 --> 00:34:15.960
[Guest]: we would have six, seven sections, and we would write about like, incredible India,

00:34:15.960 --> 00:34:19.960
[Guest]: did you know, and like something like six, seven sections. And as the luck would have

00:34:19.960 --> 00:34:29.960
[Guest]: it, 2010 ki baat hai yeh sab, the Anna Hazare movement happened, right? And discovered even

00:34:29.960 --> 00:34:36.960
[Guest]: the deeper, like, very deep desire to do something with the country, etc. Again, we became very,

00:34:36.960 --> 00:34:42.960
[Guest]: we joined the movement, of course, most of the people did at that point in time, we led

00:34:42.960 --> 00:34:46.960
[Guest]: the student movement in Chennai, for that, for the first time ever in SRM University,

00:34:46.960 --> 00:34:52.960
[Guest]: we did a sort of a political event, we carried out a candle march with 3000 students taking

00:34:52.960 --> 00:34:57.960
[Guest]: a part in it, like, crazy stuff, you know, I would, from our college is like a suburban

00:34:57.960 --> 00:35:02.960
[Guest]: area, SRM is at, like, 40-45 kilometers away from the main city, we would take a local

00:35:02.960 --> 00:35:07.960
[Guest]: train every day after college in the evening, go to the protest site in Chennai, and like

00:35:07.960 --> 00:35:12.960
[Guest]: be part of that three, two, three hours, like all chanting all that stuff. And I had some

00:35:12.960 --> 00:35:18.960
[Guest]: photos, like, I'm giving an interview and all that stuff, very, very high energy stuff,

00:35:18.960 --> 00:35:24.960
[Guest]: basically, back in those days, right? In the process, I think we also realized ki yaar

00:35:24.960 --> 00:35:30.960
[Guest]: shakti free mein nahi hoti hai, you need money, even to run an NGO and to do all things we

00:35:30.960 --> 00:35:37.960
[Guest]: want to do. And which is what led us to starting this company, essentially. So, yeh Harsh bhaiya

00:35:37.960 --> 00:35:41.960
[Guest]: se humaari mulaqat aise hai, end of first year, we started this in the second semester,

00:35:41.960 --> 00:35:45.960
[Guest]: end of first year, so we became sort of famous because of this candle march and all. And

00:35:45.960 --> 00:35:50.960
[Guest]: so Harsh bhaiya reached out to us, he discovered us, he reached out to us, he met us, very

00:35:50.960 --> 00:35:54.960
[Guest]: clearly remember it. And this was the last day of our first year. We met in a canteen

00:35:54.960 --> 00:35:58.960
[Guest]: and he asked us like, yaar, bahut sahi hai, bahut amazing kaam kar rahe ho, tum super

00:35:58.960 --> 00:36:03.960
[Guest]: proud hai, and he had his own company already running at that point in time. He said, tum

00:36:03.960 --> 00:36:07.960
[Guest]: mere liye website banaoge, tum logon ne website banate seekha hai, why don't you do it for

00:36:07.960 --> 00:36:12.960
[Guest]: me, and I'll pay you for it. And which is when we were like, okay, this could be a very

00:36:12.960 --> 00:36:17.960
[Guest]: good way for us to make money. And we use that money to basically fuel our NGO and

00:36:17.960 --> 00:36:23.960
[Guest]: basically do it, what we want to do. That's how we started our first ever company, essentially

00:36:23.960 --> 00:36:30.960
[Guest]: the end of first year of engineering. So we started that. Another reason I, since we were

00:36:30.960 --> 00:36:35.960
[Guest]: talking about dreams, etc, another reason I wanted to, we started that NGO and I wanted

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:42.960
[Guest]: to build this was because, and this was before the movement divided, got divided into a movement

00:36:42.960 --> 00:36:49.960
[Guest]: and a political party, etc. I always believe that politics is a very holy profession, if

00:36:49.960 --> 00:36:55.960
[Guest]: done for the right reasons and the right ways, and is the one of the most effective ways

00:36:55.960 --> 00:37:00.960
[Guest]: of creating large scale impact. Again, coming back to the same thing that I wanted to create

00:37:00.960 --> 00:37:08.960
[Guest]: large scale impact. So I've been very fascinated by politics as a profession. And mere life

00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:14.960
[Guest]: may though be hags. So one of them is that I genuinely believe that at some point in

00:37:14.960 --> 00:37:19.960
[Guest]: time, let me say this anyways, out loud on your podcast, it is going to go to some people,

00:37:19.960 --> 00:37:23.960
[Guest]: but then anyways, that I will, I believe that I will become the prime minister of this country

00:37:23.960 --> 00:37:29.960
[Guest]: one day. It's not a dream anymore. I genuinely believe that it will happen at some point

00:37:29.960 --> 00:37:36.960
[Guest]: in time. And second is that I will die on Mars. I will not live here for the entire

00:37:36.960 --> 00:37:42.960
[Guest]: life. I genuinely again believe in the mission of making humans a multi planetary species

00:37:42.960 --> 00:37:46.960
[Guest]: and setting up cities on Mars. And within my lifetime, I believe I'll end up on Mars

00:37:46.960 --> 00:37:52.960
[Guest]: and I'll take my final breath over there. So, Badlika Bharat, one of the reason was

00:37:52.960 --> 00:37:58.960
[Guest]: also because I wanted to actually turn it into a myneta.info. So I actually wanted to

00:37:58.960 --> 00:38:05.960
[Guest]: create a platform like that. If you go to buy a mobile phone, you can compare it with

00:38:05.960 --> 00:38:09.960
[Guest]: a lot of different companies, a lot of different price points, you can compare it feature wise.

00:38:09.960 --> 00:38:14.960
[Guest]: And we are deciding our fate for the next five years and we don't have any way to compare

00:38:14.960 --> 00:38:19.960
[Guest]: the people that we are voting for on their merits. And so I wanted to build a platform.

00:38:19.960 --> 00:38:24.960
[Guest]: Badlika Bharat's larger vision was actually to do that and so change the country through

00:38:24.960 --> 00:38:29.960
[Guest]: making impact in politics, essentially. If we change politics, the country will change

00:38:29.960 --> 00:38:35.960
[Guest]: itself. That was a thought, basic thought around it. Once we got into entrepreneurship,

00:38:35.960 --> 00:38:41.960
[Guest]: that kind of took a backseat over time and like this, the other side of it took off and

00:38:41.960 --> 00:38:46.960
[Guest]: so happened. So the reason I'm in content now coming to that is also for the same reasons

00:38:46.960 --> 00:38:52.960
[Guest]: that and I heard this concept for the first time, thick desire and thin desire. I feel

00:38:52.960 --> 00:39:01.960
[Guest]: it's one of my thick desires that I just want to do anything that allows me to do something

00:39:01.960 --> 00:39:08.960
[Guest]: with the masses. That's my calling, if that is the right word to quote here. To content

00:39:08.960 --> 00:39:14.960
[Guest]: again, no, I believe that is the most powerful medium of mass influence and distribution

00:39:14.960 --> 00:39:18.960
[Guest]: content. Maybe if content is king, distribution is good. I keep saying that. So the real game

00:39:18.960 --> 00:39:23.960
[Guest]: is of distribution, right? We record this podcast, if let's say 10 people hear it versus

00:39:23.960 --> 00:39:27.960
[Guest]: 10,000 people hear it, it makes a lot of difference in the value that we can create like both

00:39:27.960 --> 00:39:34.960
[Guest]: of our time, right? So that's why what I'm doing, I wait if it got shut down, I again

00:39:34.960 --> 00:39:39.960
[Guest]: started a content company for the same reason that I believe it's one of the most powerful

00:39:39.960 --> 00:39:44.960
[Guest]: ways of being able to create a change at a mass level, etc, etc. I don't know if this

00:39:44.960 --> 00:39:49.960
[Amit Varma]: answers your question at all. No, no, it's wonderful. And for what it's worth, I don't

00:39:49.960 --> 00:39:54.960
[Amit Varma]: find your two aims outlandish at all. I mean, it is not something that, you know, my sense

00:39:54.960 --> 00:39:58.960
[Amit Varma]: is that the people who actually achieve things are the people who dream big, right? So you

00:39:58.960 --> 00:40:03.960
[Amit Varma]: should have big dreams, you know, and you can either dream big by, you know, sitting

00:40:03.960 --> 00:40:07.960
[Amit Varma]: in a room or sitting quietly in office or not doing something about it. But clearly

00:40:07.960 --> 00:40:11.960
[Amit Varma]: from your biography, you've been out there and you're always doing things and you're

00:40:11.960 --> 00:40:17.960
[Amit Varma]: always trying new things. I want to ask you sort of a broader question about a clash that

00:40:17.960 --> 00:40:22.960
[Amit Varma]: I think all of us face in our lives and a clash that determines the direction people

00:40:22.960 --> 00:40:27.960
[Amit Varma]: go down on and certain kinds of people may go in different directions. And that's a clash

00:40:27.960 --> 00:40:35.960
[Amit Varma]: between having passion slash principles slash dreams, and also responding to incentives

00:40:35.960 --> 00:40:41.960
[Amit Varma]: and taking reality into account and going, you know, sort of, according to that, for example,

00:40:41.960 --> 00:40:44.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, at one point, you know, in one of your other interviews, you've spoken about

00:40:44.960 --> 00:40:49.960
[Amit Varma]: how, you know, there were nine of you, which became seven of you who, you know, first started

00:40:49.960 --> 00:40:53.960
[Amit Varma]: the thing. And it was only the three of you who were passionate enough to stick with it

00:40:53.960 --> 00:41:00.960
[Amit Varma]: and so on. And the others kind of drifted away. And because you know, other priorities

00:41:00.960 --> 00:41:05.960
[Amit Varma]: came and all of that. And equally in another context, you mentioned politics. And what

00:41:05.960 --> 00:41:12.960
[Amit Varma]: I often say about politics is that politics will always corrode character, because you

00:41:12.960 --> 00:41:17.960
[Amit Varma]: can get into politics for all the right reasons that these are my principles. I want to do

00:41:17.960 --> 00:41:22.960
[Amit Varma]: all these good things. But then the reality of politics is that to rise within a political

00:41:22.960 --> 00:41:28.960
[Amit Varma]: system, you make so many compromises and all of that, that by the time you actually get

00:41:28.960 --> 00:41:33.960
[Amit Varma]: somewhere, those initial principles have all gone, or at best, they are posturing, your

00:41:33.960 --> 00:41:37.960
[Amit Varma]: actions have changed who you are, it doesn't matter anymore. For example, I wrote a column

00:41:37.960 --> 00:41:41.960
[Amit Varma]: once about why, you know, people ask the question, why were our freedom fighters such great leaders?

00:41:41.960 --> 00:41:47.960
[Amit Varma]: And why don't we have that quality of leader today? And my candidate answer for that was

00:41:47.960 --> 00:41:52.960
[Amit Varma]: key, you know, those guys had no power to lust for, they were animated by higher principles,

00:41:52.960 --> 00:41:56.960
[Amit Varma]: they had no power to lust for. So you attracted that kind of principled person who didn't

00:41:56.960 --> 00:42:02.960
[Amit Varma]: give a shit about consequences, and they were in it. And and today, it's all a game of you

00:42:02.960 --> 00:42:07.960
[Amit Varma]: have an all powerful predatory state, it's all a game of power, power interacts with

00:42:07.960 --> 00:42:12.960
[Amit Varma]: money in specific ways that you know, we know about, and it attracts, therefore, that kind

00:42:12.960 --> 00:42:19.960
[Amit Varma]: of person. So, you know, and therefore, it also seems to me that the kind of person who

00:42:19.960 --> 00:42:26.960
[Amit Varma]: says, key, mujhe karna hi hai, that, you know, you've, you've spoken about how through all

00:42:26.960 --> 00:42:29.960
[Amit Varma]: your ventures, every time you think you're doing well, something or the other will bring

00:42:29.960 --> 00:42:33.960
[Amit Varma]: you crashing down. And then you go again, and then you go again, and then you go again.

00:42:33.960 --> 00:42:37.960
[Amit Varma]: And I can totally imagine that at different points of the journey, you could easily have

00:42:37.960 --> 00:42:42.960
[Amit Varma]: said ki theek hai yaar engineering, job le letao yeh kar letao, let me do something safe

00:42:42.960 --> 00:42:47.960
[Amit Varma]: or let me whatever, but you get up and you keep trying again. And that takes a particular

00:42:47.960 --> 00:42:52.960
[Amit Varma]: kind of person. And most people would not do that they would at some point be practical,

00:42:52.960 --> 00:42:57.960
[Amit Varma]: they would say key, you know, my chances of success are 1% 99% I'm going to fail, let

00:42:57.960 --> 00:43:02.960
[Amit Varma]: me just get the guaranteed income and build a stable life and all of that. And you didn't

00:43:02.960 --> 00:43:06.960
[Amit Varma]: do that. And looking around you, you know, so what is your sense of that? Because you've

00:43:06.960 --> 00:43:10.960
[Amit Varma]: been on this journey with people who have moved away and given up and with people who

00:43:10.960 --> 00:43:17.960
[Amit Varma]: stuck to it. And in this on this general larger question of, you know, being principled and

00:43:17.960 --> 00:43:22.960
[Amit Varma]: sticking to something because you're passionate about it, or just taking a conventional route,

00:43:22.960 --> 00:43:27.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, but I mean, how do you look at it? And what are the observations you made during

00:43:27.960 --> 00:43:29.960
[Guest]: this journey on this?

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:34.960
[Guest]: So let me first state that it's not like there has never been an instance where I've not

00:43:34.960 --> 00:43:42.960
[Guest]: thought about it. Right? As you must have found during your research, there have been

00:43:42.960 --> 00:43:48.960
[Guest]: a lot of ups and downs, right? So there are times where I have thought about it. There

00:43:48.960 --> 00:43:57.960
[Guest]: are times where my family said, what the hell, basically, why are you struggling so much?

00:43:57.960 --> 00:44:06.960
[Guest]: Right? And I just turned 31 three days ago. And I think it's not that old, but I feel

00:44:06.960 --> 00:44:12.960
[Guest]: very old because of probably the kind of experience we have had in last, I've been doing this

00:44:12.960 --> 00:44:22.960
[Guest]: for 12 years now. And I had my fair share of it, right? So it has happened that, dad

00:44:22.960 --> 00:44:28.960
[Guest]: says a lot of times, given the startup environment out there, I can probably get a crore or so

00:44:28.960 --> 00:44:37.960
[Guest]: as a salary out there, right? I've also thought about it a lot of times, dad says, if we spend

00:44:37.960 --> 00:44:44.960
[Guest]: affluently, we can spend 10 lakhs. That's it. 10-12 lakhs, lakhs a month. Our family

00:44:44.960 --> 00:44:48.960
[Guest]: doesn't have the courage to spend more than that. I mean, they don't even know how to

00:44:48.960 --> 00:44:54.960
[Guest]: spend more than that, basically, right? On our normal day-to-day life, basically. So

00:44:54.960 --> 00:45:00.960
[Guest]: even if I get half of what I just said, this is more money than our family can ever consume,

00:45:00.960 --> 00:45:04.960
[Guest]: basically, right? Which is when I realized that it's probably not about money for me

00:45:04.960 --> 00:45:09.960
[Guest]: anymore. Like one of the validations that I got, that this is not about money, and I'm

00:45:09.960 --> 00:45:17.960
[Guest]: not doing it for money anyways, right? And I think I will never make the mistake of saying

00:45:17.960 --> 00:45:23.960
[Guest]: that this is very easy, or once you believe in something, it all comes out. No, no, it

00:45:23.960 --> 00:45:32.960
[Guest]: doesn't happen like that. It's very hard to stick to what you believe in. Principal

00:45:32.960 --> 00:45:39.960
[Guest]: life is a very troubled life, to be honest. There has been instances where there has been

00:45:39.960 --> 00:45:44.960
[Guest]: offers where I could have made easy money, even in the business, right? And I decided

00:45:44.960 --> 00:45:51.960
[Guest]: not to. And again, I've gotten slack from my family, even from my co-founders at times,

00:45:51.960 --> 00:45:58.960
[Guest]: and I'm like, man, it's all because of your values. But then I think, I tell them the

00:45:58.960 --> 00:46:03.960
[Guest]: same thing, man. And see, a lot of times, like it's been 10-12 years, we have a lot

00:46:03.960 --> 00:46:08.960
[Guest]: of our peers who have made companies, who are doing well, someone got an exit, someone

00:46:08.960 --> 00:46:15.960
[Guest]: raised a crown, someone got secondaries, so they live an affluent life and all, right?

00:46:15.960 --> 00:46:24.960
[Guest]: One of my co-founders was telling me once that he met one of those people in some event,

00:46:24.960 --> 00:46:31.960
[Guest]: and he's doing like a, he met one of our peers, basically. Not even peers, he used to be our

00:46:31.960 --> 00:46:37.960
[Guest]: affiliate at some point in his life. And he's now doing phenomenally well, he's made a

00:46:37.960 --> 00:46:42.960
[Guest]: lot of money in life. And he met him, one of my co-founders met him. And he said, I

00:46:42.960 --> 00:46:49.960
[Guest]: met him and I went back to my hotel and I cried. And I kept kind of like, what am I

00:46:49.960 --> 00:46:55.960
[Guest]: doing with my life? I think it has happened to me also. There are times when our peers

00:46:55.960 --> 00:47:01.960
[Guest]: do really amazingly well, and I want to, I feel happy for them. But I feel very sad for

00:47:01.960 --> 00:47:14.960
[Guest]: myself. I feel jealous, to be honest. You know, it feels, I've been doing it. When things

00:47:14.960 --> 00:47:18.960
[Guest]: don't work out, you ask yourself, I haven't done anything wrong to anyone, basically,

00:47:18.960 --> 00:47:22.960
[Guest]: in a very desi term, I haven't done anything wrong to anyone. So why the hell is it? So

00:47:22.960 --> 00:47:28.960
[Guest]: you, there are, my point, the point, the larger point I'm trying to make is that sense of

00:47:28.960 --> 00:47:35.960
[Guest]: doubt prevails at all times, to be honest. It's there, a constant question mark hovering

00:47:35.960 --> 00:47:45.960
[Guest]: right over your head at all times. Right? But then I think a sense of purpose in life

00:47:45.960 --> 00:47:55.960
[Guest]: outweighs all of it. When once you, once you realize that, I'm not able to remember who

00:47:55.960 --> 00:48:02.960
[Guest]: to credit it for. I think it's a quote from a novel. When you feel jealous of someone,

00:48:02.960 --> 00:48:11.960
[Guest]: when you feel, you should be willing to, you know, replace every aspect of your life with

00:48:11.960 --> 00:48:22.960
[Guest]: every aspect of their life. I go back and ask myself that, do I want to be Amit? And

00:48:22.960 --> 00:48:27.960
[Guest]: do I want to be everything that Amit is today versus what I am, which includes my family,

00:48:27.960 --> 00:48:34.960
[Guest]: my wife, you know, and, and, and it, it, it reminds me that I am so much more beyond just

00:48:34.960 --> 00:48:39.960
[Guest]: my work and I have a life and a family and, and so much more. Right. And, and I think

00:48:39.960 --> 00:48:52.960
[Guest]: it helps me a lot to continue basically. I can keep doing what I'm doing for a long time,

00:48:52.960 --> 00:49:00.960
[Guest]: basically. I think it was the most liberating thing that ever happened to me. The fact that,

00:49:00.960 --> 00:49:06.960
[Guest]: and again, I'm, I'm an entrepreneur, I'm building a company, so I am a capitalist person at

00:49:06.960 --> 00:49:10.960
[Guest]: the end of the day. So I'm, I'm not saying I'm a socialist. I'm not saying that I will

00:49:10.960 --> 00:49:15.960
[Guest]: distribute all my money, whatever the hell. Right. I'm saying I want to make money, but

00:49:15.960 --> 00:49:24.960
[Guest]: I am not driven by it anymore. Right. I don't care about how much I make anymore. Right.

00:49:24.960 --> 00:49:30.960
[Guest]: And like you said, it's a means to an end and it's very important distinction between

00:49:30.960 --> 00:49:36.960
[Guest]: us. And, and most people don't, I think most people don't realize that. Right. I think

00:49:36.960 --> 00:49:44.960
[Guest]: it has been a liberation from there onwards.

00:49:44.960 --> 00:50:09.960
[Guest]: Right. Every other player is an incumbent, every other player. I know we'll talk about

00:50:09.960 --> 00:50:13.960
[Guest]: it later, but point being that it was a very hard thing to do, but did it because it felt

00:50:13.960 --> 00:50:21.960
[Guest]: like the right thing to do. So I think if any listener out there wants to live a principled

00:50:21.960 --> 00:50:26.960
[Guest]: life, I would say if the first thing you should do is sit down and resolve your feelings about

00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:35.960
[Guest]: money and how you feel about it, because the world we live in today, money, you may not

00:50:35.960 --> 00:50:43.960
[Guest]: know it, but it, it does impact every decision we make every second out there. So yeah, that's

00:50:43.960 --> 00:50:44.960
[Guest]: what I would say.

00:50:44.960 --> 00:50:48.960
[Amit Varma]: That's inspiring. And that's a fantastic frame also, that if you feel jealous of someone

00:50:48.960 --> 00:50:52.960
[Amit Varma]: replace every aspect of their lives, I'm, I'm going to use it on myself every time I

00:50:52.960 --> 00:50:58.960
[Amit Varma]: look at someone and say, I wish. And also another aside, I think, you know, being a

00:50:58.960 --> 00:51:02.960
[Amit Varma]: capitalist is not something anybody should say apologetically. I think capitalist is

00:51:02.960 --> 00:51:06.960
[Amit Varma]: a good word because, you know, as you would know, being a Baniya, how do you make money?

00:51:06.960 --> 00:51:11.960
[Amit Varma]: You make money by being, making someone else better off by giving them what they want and

00:51:11.960 --> 00:51:18.960
[Amit Varma]: what their value, you know, that whole thing about being Bhagwan, you know, it's a positive

00:51:18.960 --> 00:51:22.960
[Guest]: something that somebody feels valuable enough that they're ready to pay for it, which means

00:51:22.960 --> 00:51:27.960
[Guest]: you created enough value for them. So yeah, building businesses is not a bad thing at

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:36.960
[Guest]: all, right? We make our entrepreneurs villains, basically.

00:51:36.960 --> 00:52:02.960
[Guest]: And all that stuff, right? So we actually all grow up feeling that making money is a

00:52:02.960 --> 00:52:20.960
[Guest]: bad thing somehow. So I think we need to celebrate our entrepreneurs more versus

00:52:20.960 --> 00:52:24.960
[Guest]: probably the other people that we celebrate so much. And yeah, like you said, it's not

00:52:24.960 --> 00:52:26.960
[Amit Varma]: a bad thing.

00:52:26.960 --> 00:52:32.960
[Amit Varma]: I think like the frame that I look at it as a writer, John Stossel had once spoken of

00:52:32.960 --> 00:52:37.960
[Amit Varma]: the double thank you moment. And when the, you know, the person hands you the coffee,

00:52:37.960 --> 00:52:41.960
[Amit Varma]: you say, thank you. She says, thank you. Right. And what's happening here is that you value

00:52:41.960 --> 00:52:45.960
[Amit Varma]: the coffee more than the money you paid for it. And the cafe values are money more than

00:52:45.960 --> 00:52:49.960
[Amit Varma]: the coffee they gave you. So both are benefiting. And I think in India, image is bad because

00:52:49.960 --> 00:52:58.960
[Amit Varma]: like double thank you moment, positive sum, free market, where the state with this power

00:52:58.960 --> 00:53:04.960
[Amit Varma]: is ruling everything. And a lot of the people who are making money are not necessarily providing

00:53:04.960 --> 00:53:08.960
[Amit Varma]: a service, but they're using the power of the state to take a monopoly in some area

00:53:08.960 --> 00:53:13.960
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth. People have made money through undue advantages. So I think

00:53:13.960 --> 00:53:19.960
[Amit Varma]: this is our legacy because definitely 70s, 80s, you know, when I was a kid in the 80s,

00:53:19.960 --> 00:53:24.960
[Amit Varma]: this was the image. And to some extent, it's not like businessmen had a choice. They had

00:53:24.960 --> 00:53:29.960
[Amit Varma]: to work within the system. And it was like that. But I think that image is changing slightly.

00:53:29.960 --> 00:53:34.960
[Amit Varma]: My next question is, you know, what I'm sort of really impressed and moved by your answers

00:53:34.960 --> 00:53:39.960
[Amit Varma]: is a self-reflective nature that you have not just sat back and thought a lot about

00:53:39.960 --> 00:53:43.960
[Amit Varma]: the business and the things that you do. You've also sat back and thought a lot about

00:53:43.960 --> 00:53:48.960
[Amit Varma]: yourself in the questions that you asked yourself and so on and so forth. And I remember

00:53:48.960 --> 00:53:53.960
[Amit Varma]: reading this chapter on wiki feed in Snigdha Poonam's book Dreamers, where she speaks

00:53:53.960 --> 00:53:57.960
[Amit Varma]: about how you have a plaster on your hand. And the reason you had that plaster on your

00:53:57.960 --> 00:54:03.960
[Amit Varma]: hand is because you had gotten angry and punched the wall. Right. And I saw a talk on

00:54:03.960 --> 00:54:10.960
[Amit Varma]: Twitter about the plaster on your hand since 2016. And I am like, one, of course, that

00:54:10.960 --> 00:54:16.960
[Amit Varma]: anger is coming from a place of intense desire. And two, I'm sure you've also during

00:54:16.960 --> 00:54:21.960
[Amit Varma]: this time, therefore, reflected on all of these aspects, figured out how to moderate

00:54:21.960 --> 00:54:26.960
[Amit Varma]: that desire, figured out how to channel the anger. So take me through a little bit of

00:54:26.960 --> 00:54:30.960
[Amit Varma]: your personal journey and the sort of growth that you've had in this period.

00:54:30.960 --> 00:54:34.960
[Guest]: Oh, very interesting. Thank you that you actually went through so much and asked this

00:54:34.960 --> 00:54:43.960
[Guest]: question. I was actually a very short tempered person, so to say. Right. And I have actually

00:54:43.960 --> 00:54:51.960
[Guest]: thought about it a lot so much so that last, especially last three years, when the witty

00:54:51.960 --> 00:54:55.960
[Guest]: feed situation happened, it changed me as a person a lot. Because it meant that I had

00:54:55.960 --> 00:54:59.960
[Guest]: a lot of time to reflect, etc. I had almost a decade of being an entrepreneur in a certain

00:54:59.960 --> 00:55:07.960
[Guest]: way. And then all of a sudden there was emptiness and I was able to think about what am I doing.

00:55:07.960 --> 00:55:14.960
[Guest]: And I realized that it's actually very bad for me in a lot of different ways. And so

00:55:14.960 --> 00:55:18.960
[Guest]: I made it as one of the reasons why I went to therapy. I've been doing therapy for the

00:55:18.960 --> 00:55:24.960
[Guest]: last two and a half years, two and a half years now. And I also have an executive coach

00:55:24.960 --> 00:55:29.960
[Guest]: which has helped. Actually, she was the one who helped me work through my anger first

00:55:29.960 --> 00:55:35.960
[Guest]: and then therapy, of course, dug a little deeper, figured out where it comes from, etc.

00:55:35.960 --> 00:55:39.960
[Guest]: During my reflection, what I realized was that apart from the fact that so my mom is

00:55:39.960 --> 00:55:49.960
[Guest]: a very angry person and I grew up and her own. I had a very strained relationship because

00:55:49.960 --> 00:55:53.960
[Guest]: of that with her. And then therapy again helped me reflect a lot on that and figure out why

00:55:53.960 --> 00:56:01.960
[Guest]: was it and how it happened and why my mom was or is the way she is, etc. But I think

00:56:01.960 --> 00:56:08.960
[Guest]: I probably inherited some of it from her. And then I made it my coping mechanism for

00:56:08.960 --> 00:56:16.960
[Guest]: multiple things. One, for a lot of inferiority complex. I started this company when I was

00:56:16.960 --> 00:56:28.960
[Guest]: 19. So was Sushant and Praveen was like 16 or younger. Basically, I didn't have a beard

00:56:28.960 --> 00:56:34.960
[Guest]: at that time and I looked like a kid. Even now, I'm not like a very macho man type.

00:56:34.960 --> 00:56:43.960
[Guest]: I'm a very sleek guy that way. So, if you go to ask someone for a job, they would not

00:56:43.960 --> 00:56:48.960
[Guest]: give you the same kind of respect if a man in his 40s walks in and doesn't know shit,

00:56:48.960 --> 00:56:54.960
[Guest]: but still will get the respect because he is big, basically, or whatever. Again, another

00:56:54.960 --> 00:57:02.960
[Guest]: contradiction in our Indian society. So, I started keeping a beard. I used to keep,

00:57:02.960 --> 00:57:07.960
[Guest]: now I actually keep a clean shave. Earlier, I used to keep a French shave that this man

00:57:07.960 --> 00:57:14.960
[Guest]: should look good, basically. Then you want people to work for you. I was hiring people

00:57:14.960 --> 00:57:22.960
[Guest]: when we were 20, 21, something like that. And again, growing up, one more thing, I mean,

00:57:22.960 --> 00:57:27.960
[Guest]: we are taught that if you want someone to work for you, you have to be a little tough

00:57:27.960 --> 00:57:33.960
[Guest]: and you have to be a little threatening. So, all of these things were there with me. Some

00:57:33.960 --> 00:57:39.960
[Guest]: of the bad ones that I carried from my family and business that way. So, my way of establishing

00:57:39.960 --> 00:57:51.960
[Guest]: my authority as a CEO on my team was through being very strict and tough. And I had a problem

00:57:51.960 --> 00:57:56.960
[Guest]: of anger, but I would basically now justify it by saying that it is important, it is needed

00:57:56.960 --> 00:58:07.960
[Guest]: for me to, and I did this for four, five, six years, probably more than that. I hope

00:58:07.960 --> 00:58:12.960
[Guest]: some of them listen it now. I was thinking to write a letter to all my ex-employees at

00:58:12.960 --> 00:58:17.960
[Guest]: Witty Feed. And I wanted to write an apology letter to all of them saying that it feels

00:58:17.960 --> 00:58:23.960
[Guest]: like I was a very toxic boss because I used to get angry a lot. I don't believe I was

00:58:23.960 --> 00:58:30.960
[Guest]: a bad boss to them actually, but that part of me was very toxic. I believe that we have

00:58:30.960 --> 00:58:35.960
[Guest]: built Witty Feed with an amazing culture, cared about people, but there were two extremes

00:58:35.960 --> 00:58:42.960
[Guest]: of me. And there is one side where I was, I would get so angry and the people would

00:58:42.960 --> 00:58:49.960
[Guest]: be scared of talking to me. And the other side, which would be like extremely empathetic,

00:58:49.960 --> 00:58:54.960
[Guest]: go 10 steps out of the way to do anything for those people that they need. Right. And

00:58:54.960 --> 00:58:59.960
[Guest]: which is why so many people stuck with us even when we had nothing right then during

00:58:59.960 --> 00:59:06.960
[Guest]: the Witty Feed thing. So it was justified for many years. Plus there is one more thing

00:59:06.960 --> 00:59:13.960
[Guest]: that happens, see in your twenties you believe something. And I started a company, it was

00:59:13.960 --> 00:59:18.960
[Guest]: such a busy thing to do, but I never had a chance to sit down and think about who am

00:59:18.960 --> 00:59:25.960
[Guest]: I, what am I doing here? Right. Because I had gone through a very amazing journey of

00:59:25.960 --> 00:59:30.960
[Guest]: building a company and I got married, which is another story and so much more. Right.

00:59:30.960 --> 00:59:41.960
[Guest]: So your belief system changes, but not many of us realize that and realize the fact that

00:59:41.960 --> 00:59:57.960
[Guest]: you need to sit down and reflect on it and think about it. Do I still believe that? Do

00:59:57.960 --> 01:00:05.960
[Guest]: I still believe all of that? You may believe the same or it might have changed on the opposite

01:00:05.960 --> 01:00:12.960
[Guest]: side, but you will only realize that when you will sit down and reflect on it. And that

01:00:12.960 --> 01:00:20.960
[Guest]: awareness of reflection is something that was missing. And I was so busy. Right. End

01:00:20.960 --> 01:00:26.960
[Guest]: of 2018 when this Witty Feed thing happened. And again, I'm very lucky for this one person

01:00:26.960 --> 01:00:35.960
[Guest]: Harsh Bhaiya. Harsh Bhaiya just joined us. October 2018 he joined us, November 2018 the

01:00:35.960 --> 01:00:41.960
[Guest]: Witty Feed thing happened. But he is the man that he is, so he decided to stick with us

01:00:41.960 --> 01:00:45.960
[Guest]: and he said that we will make it together, whatever new journey you start, then I will

01:00:45.960 --> 01:00:52.960
[Guest]: probably leave. But I am with you. And he is someone who is one of the most articulate

01:00:52.960 --> 01:00:56.960
[Guest]: person. I had heard the word articulation from him for the first time in my life. So

01:00:56.960 --> 01:01:00.960
[Guest]: I learned from him what articulation means. Most articulate person that you will meet

01:01:00.960 --> 01:01:06.960
[Guest]: and like he has these deep thoughts, he'll ask you questions, he'll make you think about

01:01:06.960 --> 01:01:13.960
[Guest]: things that you've never done that. And which is where finally when I got some time, I realized

01:01:13.960 --> 01:01:19.960
[Guest]: that this anger is actually bad for everything. Like it's very toxic for the people who have

01:01:19.960 --> 01:01:25.960
[Guest]: to face it because of me. More importantly, it is even more toxic to me, my mental health,

01:01:25.960 --> 01:01:34.960
[Guest]: even my physical health. And I have no shame in saying it now because I thankfully worked

01:01:34.960 --> 01:01:43.960
[Guest]: out through it, that I used to shout so much so that my stomach used to hurt. And I think

01:01:43.960 --> 01:01:49.960
[Guest]: about it today and I'm like, why? Why did I do so much harm to myself? There's no reason.

01:01:49.960 --> 01:01:56.960
[Guest]: But just that I wanted to ensure that, you know, I am the alpha in the room and there

01:01:56.960 --> 01:02:02.960
[Guest]: is an authority. I am the CEO. I have 150 people to manage and I'm 23, 24. Like how

01:02:02.960 --> 01:02:11.960
[Guest]: do you comprehend that? And there was so much inferiority complex inbuilt in me.

01:02:11.960 --> 01:02:19.960
[Guest]: People who dress in a certain way, people who speak in a certain way, people who eat

01:02:19.960 --> 01:02:26.960
[Guest]: certain kind of food. There was a lot of inferiority that I've been able to thankfully, I think,

01:02:26.960 --> 01:02:31.960
[Guest]: work out and process in last few years, last three, four years, especially. And I'm so

01:02:31.960 --> 01:02:39.960
[Guest]: happy that I'm actually a better person at the end of it now. But yeah, maybe this podcast

01:02:39.960 --> 01:02:44.960
[Guest]: is the way to do it. I am really sorry for all those people who had to go through this

01:02:44.960 --> 01:02:49.960
[Guest]: because of something that was truly just my internal stuff.

01:02:49.960 --> 01:02:54.960
[Amit Varma]: No, when you say you're 31, you know, most people who are 31 or most people at any age

01:02:54.960 --> 01:02:59.960
[Amit Varma]: don't really go through this period of self-reflection where they can, you know, talk about themselves

01:02:59.960 --> 01:03:04.960
[Amit Varma]: in the way that they have. My other question is this, you know, sort of following on from

01:03:04.960 --> 01:03:09.960
[Amit Varma]: what you've said about controlling your anger, that do you not feel angry anymore? Or do

01:03:09.960 --> 01:03:13.960
[Amit Varma]: you still feel angry, but you immediately control it because you have the self-awareness?

01:03:13.960 --> 01:03:19.960
[Guest]: I absolutely feel angry. There's no doubt about it. Right. But now I'm aware of it.

01:03:19.960 --> 01:03:24.960
[Guest]: I can look at myself in third person. So the way I process through my anger is that my

01:03:24.960 --> 01:03:31.960
[Guest]: therapy and my coach, they were able to help me look at myself, like time travel, basically

01:03:31.960 --> 01:03:39.960
[Guest]: where when I'm about to get angry, 90% of the times I am able to see through five minutes

01:03:39.960 --> 01:03:45.960
[Guest]: down the line. And what am I going to do? Literally, I can stand as a third person and

01:03:45.960 --> 01:03:50.960
[Guest]: I'm looking at the entire scene. How am I behaving right now? And how am I going to

01:03:50.960 --> 01:03:56.960
[Guest]: make the other person feel? And how am I? I am going to feel in five, ten minutes from

01:03:56.960 --> 01:04:00.960
[Guest]: now. And I would feel terrible every time after getting angry by the way. Because like

01:04:00.960 --> 01:04:05.960
[Guest]: I said, that the true self in me was in a very empathetic person. I would feel like

01:04:05.960 --> 01:04:09.960
[Guest]: I shouted at him for no reason. I would almost every single time I would go and say sorry

01:04:09.960 --> 01:04:14.960
[Guest]: to those people. And then you've done the damage you've done. Right. So I'm able to

01:04:14.960 --> 01:04:20.960
[Guest]: visualize that now. Right. And so 90% of the time I'm like, what are you doing Vinay?

01:04:20.960 --> 01:04:25.960
[Guest]: Do you want to feel like this? Do you want to make him feel or her feel like this? And

01:04:25.960 --> 01:04:30.960
[Guest]: I realize there's a better way. And I literally repeat the sentence in my mind that if I'm

01:04:30.960 --> 01:04:37.960
[Guest]: going to say something in a certain way to someone, I reiterate that sentence. And I'm

01:04:37.960 --> 01:04:42.960
[Guest]: like, there's a better way of saying it. Like I say to someone, what have you done?

01:04:42.960 --> 01:04:47.960
[Guest]: Versus, if you do it like this, it might be better. And I'm like, I'm able to somehow

01:04:47.960 --> 01:04:52.960
[Guest]: do that, you know, thanks to my coach and my therapist, I'm able to do that. And that

01:04:52.960 --> 01:04:59.960
[Guest]: is what basically avoids. So I don't think my anger went away, because that's who I am.

01:04:59.960 --> 01:05:04.960
[Guest]: But I know how to work through it now. And I'm able to process it, basically.

01:05:04.960 --> 01:05:09.960
[Amit Varma]: One of the concepts in philosophy, which had a big influence on me, and I think about it

01:05:09.960 --> 01:05:15.960
[Amit Varma]: often, is Immanuel Kant's categorical imperative. And basically, what it says is that you should

01:05:15.960 --> 01:05:21.960
[Amit Varma]: never treat other people as a means to an end, but as an end in themselves. Right. And

01:05:21.960 --> 01:05:26.960
[Amit Varma]: sometimes, when I look at all of us, look at myself, look around at people, and I have

01:05:26.960 --> 01:05:30.960
[Amit Varma]: to ask myself the question that, am I treating other people, even those who are close to

01:05:30.960 --> 01:05:34.960
[Amit Varma]: me, closest to me, as a means to an end, that, you know, we all have a play in our heads,

01:05:34.960 --> 01:05:40.960
[Amit Varma]: and we are the central character, and everyone else is a prop, right? So I consciously try

01:05:40.960 --> 01:05:45.960
[Amit Varma]: to then make the effort that you step back, and you think of other people as people. And

01:05:45.960 --> 01:05:49.960
[Amit Varma]: partly this plays to in conversation also, like one of the things that doing this long

01:05:49.960 --> 01:05:54.960
[Amit Varma]: form show has taught me, is that just listen, like Stephen Covey once said that we don't

01:05:54.960 --> 01:05:59.960
[Amit Varma]: listen to understand, we listen to respond. Or usme kya hai, usme poora ego hai. So I

01:05:59.960 --> 01:06:03.960
[Amit Varma]: could be talking to you, but everything is about my ego, I am the central character,

01:06:03.960 --> 01:06:08.960
[Amit Varma]: you are a prop who is there for my amusement. But then if you really listen, then you treat

01:06:08.960 --> 01:06:11.960
[Amit Varma]: the other person as an end in themselves, then you're trying to learn from them, then

01:06:11.960 --> 01:06:17.960
[Amit Varma]: it's not about your ego, then you're just taking it in. And I find that our default

01:06:17.960 --> 01:06:22.960
[Amit Varma]: mode can sometimes be that aap main character ho, baaki sab, you know, it could be like

01:06:22.960 --> 01:06:26.960
[Amit Varma]: baaki sab could, like this virtual reality, you know, it could be a similar thing, that

01:06:26.960 --> 01:06:30.960
[Amit Varma]: you are playing a game and everybody else is a character in this virtual reality around

01:06:30.960 --> 01:06:34.960
[Amit Varma]: you. And then you have to remind myself, and I thought of this, because, you know, when

01:06:34.960 --> 01:06:39.960
[Amit Varma]: you were speaking, this sort of these moments of pause, when you get angry, and you ask

01:06:39.960 --> 01:06:43.960
[Amit Varma]: yourself, should I say it like this? Or should I say it like that? What you are, I think

01:06:43.960 --> 01:06:48.960
[Amit Varma]: doing immediately in that moment is converting that person from just a means to an end to

01:06:48.960 --> 01:06:51.960
[Amit Varma]: an end in themselves, right? This person is a human being, I got to think about how they

01:06:51.960 --> 01:06:55.960
[Amit Varma]: will feel, and which you would do anyway, like you said, because that empathy is also

01:06:55.960 --> 01:07:02.960
[Amit Varma]: inbuilt. So, you know, and you've spoken earlier in other sort of talks and interviews, you

01:07:02.960 --> 01:07:06.960
[Amit Varma]: give, I think a TEDx talk on this, which I'll link from the show notes, where you speak

01:07:06.960 --> 01:07:10.960
[Amit Varma]: about the importance of people, you know, the importance of, you know, how you deal

01:07:10.960 --> 01:07:16.960
[Amit Varma]: with people, how you manage people, all of that. So take me through your learnings in

01:07:16.960 --> 01:07:21.960
[Amit Varma]: this, not just from the point of view of a manager with so many people working for you,

01:07:21.960 --> 01:07:24.960
[Amit Varma]: but also from a personal point of view.

01:07:24.960 --> 01:07:29.960
[Guest]: Yeah, before that, I remember one thing that you asked, do you still get angry, etc, right?

01:07:29.960 --> 01:07:34.960
[Guest]: So, just yesterday, I lost myself with my father, we were having a discussion and I

01:07:34.960 --> 01:07:40.960
[Guest]: was thinking about it when you were asking questions, that yesterday, it happened with

01:07:40.960 --> 01:07:45.960
[Guest]: me. And so it happens even now, right? And again, I felt terrible, I wrote an apology

01:07:45.960 --> 01:07:53.960
[Guest]: message before sleeping, etc. Basically, see people, I didn't know about the philosophy

01:07:53.960 --> 01:07:57.960
[Guest]: that you said, but I think I look at people in a similar manner, like that's my articulation

01:07:57.960 --> 01:08:03.960
[Guest]: of it also, that people are, people can never be a means to an end, no matter who they are.

01:08:03.960 --> 01:08:11.960
[Guest]: Basically, if you try to, whoever you are talking to, whose life is also going to be

01:08:11.960 --> 01:08:17.960
[Guest]: impacted by any of your actions, if you can walk into their shoes for those few seconds

01:08:17.960 --> 01:08:24.960
[Guest]: and think about how is it going to feel if it were you, I think it changes your entire

01:08:24.960 --> 01:08:34.960
[Guest]: perspective, right? So, like while building the company, we always, so customer is God,

01:08:34.960 --> 01:08:43.960
[Guest]: right? But your people, those people are equally important. They are basically, they say that

01:08:43.960 --> 01:08:50.960
[Guest]: if you can treat people better, that's probably the best worship of a God anyways, right?

01:08:50.960 --> 01:08:57.960
[Guest]: So, if you treat your people properly, they will take care of your, they are the priest

01:08:57.960 --> 01:09:01.960
[Guest]: whom you have assigned, the priest whom you have told to worship your God. And if you

01:09:01.960 --> 01:09:05.960
[Guest]: take care of that priest, then that priest is also a God, who is going to do anything

01:09:05.960 --> 01:09:11.960
[Guest]: for you, right? So, you have to anyways really be, you know, very, you have to be taking

01:09:11.960 --> 01:09:17.960
[Guest]: care of your people. Those people are your company's employees, your relatives, your

01:09:17.960 --> 01:09:23.960
[Guest]: family, your parents, your wife, anybody basically. So, you, I think we are nothing but a sum

01:09:23.960 --> 01:09:29.960
[Guest]: of people that we earn in life. And at least in my understanding, every relationship has

01:09:29.960 --> 01:09:35.960
[Guest]: to be earned. Whether it is with your parents, with your siblings, we get something in the

01:09:35.960 --> 01:09:42.960
[Guest]: gift, but again, if we want to have them and build on them, we have to earn those relationships

01:09:42.960 --> 01:09:47.960
[Guest]: as well. So, like we get our parents, we get our siblings, at least these 2-3 things we

01:09:47.960 --> 01:09:54.960
[Guest]: get. But I think we should also earn over time, you know, you have to, and to earn,

01:09:54.960 --> 01:09:59.960
[Guest]: everybody says you have to invest into relationships. You really have to invest in your people, right?

01:09:59.960 --> 01:10:05.960
[Guest]: So, you have to do that, whoever it is, right? So, I tried, that is one of my modus operandi.

01:10:05.960 --> 01:10:13.960
[Guest]: And I learned it while, I think, I think empathy was natural. I don't know where it came from.

01:10:13.960 --> 01:10:18.960
[Guest]: My father is a very empathetic person, but he has other traits also. I'm not sure if

01:10:18.960 --> 01:10:22.960
[Guest]: it came, it came from him, but it came from somewhere. There are a lot of things that

01:10:22.960 --> 01:10:26.960
[Guest]: I keep wondering, where did it come from? You know, why am I the way I am? A lot of

01:10:26.960 --> 01:10:31.960
[Guest]: times, because I don't see my surroundings, which would have led to this. I don't see

01:10:31.960 --> 01:10:37.960
[Guest]: my parents or anybody in my family who would have impacted me to be that way. But anyways,

01:10:37.960 --> 01:10:44.960
[Guest]: so when we were making the company, one of the philosophies that I built it on was that

01:10:44.960 --> 01:10:52.960
[Guest]: if you share the company, what you're building, I didn't know about eShops back then. So,

01:10:52.960 --> 01:10:56.960
[Guest]: I built it with absolute transparency. So, one of the things that I value most and is

01:10:56.960 --> 01:11:00.960
[Guest]: the most critical thing in my understanding or to build relationships and value people

01:11:00.960 --> 01:11:06.960
[Guest]: is you have to be very transparent. So, I built my companies with the utmost transparency.

01:11:06.960 --> 01:11:11.960
[Guest]: I mean, we had a small team, a big team, a team of 150 people and a team of 5 people

01:11:11.960 --> 01:11:15.960
[Guest]: in between. And plus now again, we are at about 30-35 people. Everybody knows everything

01:11:15.960 --> 01:11:21.960
[Guest]: about the company. If you are working with us, you can call our accountant and ask him

01:11:21.960 --> 01:11:25.960
[Guest]: the most secret questions and there is no secret there basically. You will know everything

01:11:25.960 --> 01:11:30.960
[Guest]: by. If you trust me with your career, which is like one of the most important parts of

01:11:30.960 --> 01:11:34.960
[Guest]: your life, then I need to trust you with the information that this company has, right?

01:11:34.960 --> 01:11:38.960
[Guest]: And why should anything be hidden from you? At least, I still believe this. I don't know

01:11:38.960 --> 01:11:43.960
[Guest]: what will happen when I grow up. Like you said, politics changes your character. I think

01:11:43.960 --> 01:11:47.960
[Guest]: it happens in business too, when businesses grow up. But hopefully, we haven't gone there

01:11:47.960 --> 01:11:50.960
[Guest]: yet, right? So, we should be able to maintain it till now. I built it with absolute transparency.

01:11:50.960 --> 01:11:57.960
[Guest]: I tell them about the worst of the things in the company, what's going wrong, what's

01:11:57.960 --> 01:12:19.960
[Guest]: going right. I basically speak very transparently to my people. Second, I think again, means

01:12:19.960 --> 01:12:38.960
[Guest]: to an end, right? I don't remember. There are a lot of people, 3-4 people that I can

01:12:38.960 --> 01:12:49.960
[Guest]: think of now, who still haven't returned that money, basically. So, I always felt that this

01:12:49.960 --> 01:12:53.960
[Guest]: man needs 2-3 lakhs. I have more money in my account and this 3-4 lakhs is not going

01:12:53.960 --> 01:13:01.960
[Guest]: to make a dent in this entire thing. But if he gets it, his life changes. If I don't give

01:13:01.960 --> 01:13:08.960
[Guest]: it to him, he will go somewhere, take a loan. If he doesn't get a bank loan, he will do

01:13:08.960 --> 01:13:16.960
[Guest]: something like this. He will unnecessarily become part of that monstrous interest rates

01:13:16.960 --> 01:13:25.960
[Guest]: and will get stuck in a debt cycle. I used to think that the stress he will face in life

01:13:25.960 --> 01:13:31.960
[Guest]: is better than the interest rate. If he doesn't get that much stress in his life, this guy

01:13:31.960 --> 01:13:36.960
[Guest]: will be more productive. My way of justifying it as a business was that. But then, what

01:13:36.960 --> 01:13:42.960
[Guest]: I felt was, okay, I had kept the money here, I needed it here, I used it, it's over, basically.

01:13:42.960 --> 01:13:48.960
[Guest]: So, we used to do one of those things. If anyone in the company needs money, they get

01:13:48.960 --> 01:13:55.960
[Guest]: basically whatever they need. Another philosophy outside the company or in the company I have

01:13:55.960 --> 01:14:00.960
[Guest]: always followed with people is that, if you don't participate in someone's happiness,

01:14:00.960 --> 01:14:04.960
[Guest]: it doesn't make much difference to anyone. If someone invites you to a wedding and you

01:14:04.960 --> 01:14:08.960
[Guest]: don't go, the wedding won't stop. Nothing will happen. He will tell you that you didn't

01:14:08.960 --> 01:14:13.960
[Guest]: come. But they are not going to really remember it or care about it too much. Except it's

01:14:13.960 --> 01:14:21.960
[Guest]: like a really close friend or whatever, right? But if someone is in pain, like let's say

01:14:21.960 --> 01:14:27.960
[Guest]: somebody has a family member pass away, and if you're not there at that point in time,

01:14:27.960 --> 01:14:32.960
[Guest]: they are going to remember you for the rest of their life. He will remember. At least

01:14:32.960 --> 01:14:37.960
[Guest]: I follow this. It doesn't matter if you're in my happiness or not. But if you're not

01:14:37.960 --> 01:14:43.960
[Guest]: there at that point in time, he will remember. And so, then you should always be there for

01:14:43.960 --> 01:14:47.960
[Guest]: people you care about when they are down, when the chips are down. Because that's when

01:14:47.960 --> 01:14:52.960
[Guest]: everyone says that everyone salutes the rising sun, no one stands with you in sadness. So

01:14:52.960 --> 01:14:57.960
[Guest]: someone has to be there to change it. If I say that, then I need to be with you when

01:14:57.960 --> 01:15:04.960
[Guest]: your chips are down, right? So, I don't know, like when India and Australia are playing,

01:15:04.960 --> 01:15:09.960
[Guest]: then I support India, of course. But when India is playing Bangladesh, then I support

01:15:09.960 --> 01:15:17.960
[Guest]: Bangladesh by default. So, I feel that you need to stand with the weak or the people

01:15:17.960 --> 01:15:24.960
[Guest]: who are in pain, basically. Right? So, I used to make this a point and I try to do this

01:15:24.960 --> 01:15:31.960
[Guest]: even today. Once, one of my employees during the defeat days lost their grandmother. And

01:15:31.960 --> 01:15:36.960
[Guest]: he used to live in the village, somewhere in front of Jabalpur, basically. It took me

01:15:36.960 --> 01:15:42.960
[Guest]: some 20 hours to travel, by train he could travel. My phone got stolen for Rs. 75,000

01:15:42.960 --> 01:15:48.960
[Guest]: to reach there and all, a new phone had come. But I felt very contentful going there. And

01:15:48.960 --> 01:15:54.960
[Guest]: I think I made a lifelong relationship with that guy by doing that. He won't forget me

01:15:54.960 --> 01:16:01.960
[Guest]: ever. I used to call him and say, Sonil, sorry, I feel very bad for you. Let me know if you

01:16:01.960 --> 01:16:08.960
[Guest]: need anything. But then he, you know, I took the pain to go there and he will always remember

01:16:08.960 --> 01:16:13.960
[Guest]: me. My point being that if you stand in pain, people will stand in your pain, basically.

01:16:13.960 --> 01:16:19.960
[Guest]: You have no right to complain that people were not with you when chips are down, when

01:16:19.960 --> 01:16:25.960
[Guest]: your chips were down. If you, before that, have not been with all those people when their

01:16:25.960 --> 01:16:29.960
[Guest]: chips were down. Because there is no one who is doing everything well. Everyone's life

01:16:29.960 --> 01:16:35.960
[Guest]: is bad, right? So that's another thing that I really follow a lot in life. Not your typical

01:16:35.960 --> 01:16:41.960
[Guest]: management stuff, right? But I follow this also. What else?

01:16:41.960 --> 01:16:45.960
[Amit Varma]: One interesting thing that you had mentioned in one of your interviews was, and this also

01:16:45.960 --> 01:16:50.960
[Amit Varma]: struck me as very self-aware at the time, that, you know, you might have a hundred employees.

01:16:50.960 --> 01:16:55.960
[Amit Varma]: So for you talking to one employee for a minute, it's just, oh, you have a hundred of them.

01:16:55.960 --> 01:17:00.960
[Amit Varma]: But for that person, that person is one boss. And talking to you kind of makes a little

01:17:00.960 --> 01:17:02.960
[Guest]: bit of work. Absolutely. It makes or breaks that day.

01:17:02.960 --> 01:17:15.960
[Guest]: I mean, you have 150 people, you talked to them, you got busy later. You talked to him

01:17:15.960 --> 01:17:17.960
[Guest]: in a weird voice, you talked to him in anger. His whole day was ruined. Because for him,

01:17:17.960 --> 01:17:21.960
[Guest]: like you said, he has only one boss, right? So again, I mean, you treat people like people.

01:17:21.960 --> 01:17:26.960
[Guest]: I think in simple language, in one sentence, the point is the same as you said. Treat people

01:17:26.960 --> 01:17:34.960
[Guest]: like people. Don't treat them like objects. You can't look at people as employees. You

01:17:34.960 --> 01:17:39.960
[Guest]: can't look at them as one number on a balance sheet or on an Excel sheet, basically. You

01:17:39.960 --> 01:17:43.960
[Guest]: have to look at them as people. When you do that, I think the entire perspective changes.

01:17:43.960 --> 01:17:49.960
[Amit Varma]: And you were mentioning that there are certain characteristics that you look back on and

01:17:49.960 --> 01:17:54.960
[Amit Varma]: you wonder, where did this come from? How did I become like this? And like two of those

01:17:54.960 --> 01:17:59.960
[Amit Varma]: elements, of course, are those two sides of the same coin, perhaps anger and empathy,

01:17:59.960 --> 01:18:03.960
[Amit Varma]: which you mentioned, which are interesting to you. What else?

01:18:03.960 --> 01:18:11.960
[Guest]: I don't care about money. My entire family does. I like to, within my family also, I

01:18:11.960 --> 01:18:15.960
[Guest]: have a very large family. My father has four brothers and five sisters. My mother also

01:18:15.960 --> 01:18:19.960
[Guest]: has four brothers and five sisters. It's a very big family. Especially on my father's

01:18:19.960 --> 01:18:24.960
[Guest]: side. I come from Haryana, so it's a bit of a misogynistic family. So I have more influence

01:18:24.960 --> 01:18:29.960
[Guest]: on father's side. I have two brothers older than my father. I mean, I have two uncles

01:18:29.960 --> 01:18:36.960
[Guest]: and I have three cousins who are elder to me. But I still have like, I am positioned

01:18:36.960 --> 01:18:43.960
[Guest]: in the family as sort of a pseudo leader of the house, larger family. And I think I have

01:18:43.960 --> 01:18:50.960
[Guest]: kind of given that place to myself. I conducted myself in a way that it basically became mine,

01:18:50.960 --> 01:19:04.960
[Guest]: right? I was very close to my grandfather. He was a very smart guy. He wanted, I am a

01:19:04.960 --> 01:19:13.960
[Guest]: big fan of joint family and all that stuff. And I kind of carried that legacy with me.

01:19:13.960 --> 01:19:23.960
[Guest]: So those leadership type qualities, I don't see any person in such a big family who has

01:19:23.960 --> 01:19:32.960
[Guest]: those basic characteristics. It's a bit self-boosting, but I like to believe that I am a very selfless

01:19:32.960 --> 01:19:41.960
[Guest]: person. I have achieved 70% of that at least. I mean, there are times when I become selfish,

01:19:41.960 --> 01:19:46.960
[Guest]: but I like to believe. The 30 times when I am not, even after that, after a while, I

01:19:46.960 --> 01:19:51.960
[Guest]: feel bad that I did something wrong. It was a very selfish thing to do and all. I don't

01:19:51.960 --> 01:19:56.960
[Guest]: think I have a very selfless family. Not many people are like that. My mother had some of

01:19:56.960 --> 01:20:00.960
[Guest]: it. She used to make so many things for everybody in the village.

01:20:00.960 --> 01:20:04.960
[Guest]: Sometimes she used to make ladoos for them, sometimes she used to make a sweater for them.

01:20:04.960 --> 01:20:10.960
[Guest]: But other than that, I mean, there is no such selfless type of family. They are very self-centered

01:20:10.960 --> 01:20:17.960
[Guest]: type of people. Then there are a lot of things. I mean, I think many times that I feel very

01:20:17.960 --> 01:20:25.960
[Guest]: out of the place in my own family. I don't know, I mean, I like to believe I am a very

01:20:25.960 --> 01:20:31.960
[Guest]: liberal person by thoughts. I don't have a family which is very liberal by thoughts at

01:20:31.960 --> 01:20:37.960
[Guest]: all. Right. I don't know, I don't remember. There are a lot of things. Like I said, sometimes

01:20:37.960 --> 01:20:44.960
[Guest]: it happens that I feel out of the place. How was I born in this family? And I love all

01:20:44.960 --> 01:20:49.960
[Guest]: of them. They are nice people. Of course, I ended up like this for some reason because

01:20:49.960 --> 01:20:55.960
[Guest]: they were around me. Right. But how did I end up? I ended up with these guys. Right.

01:20:55.960 --> 01:21:04.960
[Guest]: So there's an aspiration. Sorry. Sorry. Aspiration. Right. It's very important human trait.

01:21:04.960 --> 01:21:27.960
[Guest]: Right. It's okay if I share that. Right. So, my family was married and other one was

01:21:27.960 --> 01:21:38.960
[Guest]: about to get married or something. My grandfather was still there. He was very unhappy and like

01:21:38.960 --> 01:21:47.960
[Guest]: very sad about it. And I made a presentation. I literally made a PowerPoint presentation.

01:21:47.960 --> 01:21:54.960
[Guest]: I had a computer. I made a PowerPoint presentation. And basically all the men in the house, because

01:21:54.960 --> 01:22:03.960
[Guest]: they are the ones who decide. I basically pulled all of them in one room. We are eight

01:22:03.960 --> 01:22:09.960
[Guest]: cousins. All seven of us, we pulled all of them in one room and I presented a grand vision

01:22:09.960 --> 01:22:15.960
[Guest]: of building the single group one day. I was like, you have heard of Ambarni, you have

01:22:15.960 --> 01:22:19.960
[Guest]: heard of Birla, you have heard of all these names. But have you ever heard of a single

01:22:19.960 --> 01:22:24.960
[Guest]: group? Have you heard of a big one? We will build it. Why don't four of you, eight of

01:22:24.960 --> 01:22:29.960
[Guest]: us, twelve people, if we all do some businesses, like a very grand vision, all of that.

01:22:29.960 --> 01:22:36.960
[Guest]: Let's talk about money. Everyone listens in our house. We can make thousands of crores.

01:22:36.960 --> 01:22:40.960
[Guest]: We will build big businesses. We will do this, we will do that. They, of course, listened

01:22:40.960 --> 01:22:43.960
[Guest]: to it. They calmed down. It didn't happen for a few days. It happened after six months.

01:22:43.960 --> 01:22:53.960
[Guest]: But nobody cared about it later on. In my family, it's basically a useless thing that

01:22:53.960 --> 01:22:59.960
[Guest]: I did at that point in time, basically. My cousin started a mobile shop in the village

01:22:59.960 --> 01:23:04.960
[Guest]: after leaving studies at that time. My belief was that I will have to study if I want to

01:23:04.960 --> 01:23:11.960
[Guest]: build a single group. Basically, I slept in the same room with him that night and I cried

01:23:11.960 --> 01:23:17.960
[Guest]: the entire night because he left his education and started a shop. I was like, yaar ye to

01:23:17.960 --> 01:23:21.960
[Guest]: kaise banayenge hum single group agar tum aise chhod doge to. Aise kaise hoga and all that

01:23:21.960 --> 01:23:29.960
[Guest]: stuff, right? So which is how? Sometimes I feel out of the place in the family that I

01:23:29.960 --> 01:23:36.960
[Amit Varma]: am. I love all of them. So you mentioned that you are a selfless person and I am not such

01:23:36.960 --> 01:23:40.960
[Amit Varma]: a selfless person. But for the moment, I can see that I think both of us need a break.

01:23:40.960 --> 01:23:43.960
[Amit Varma]: So let's be selfish, take a short break and come back after that.

01:24:11.960 --> 01:24:16.960
[Amit Varma]: Well, that phase in my life ended for various reasons and now it is time to revive it. Only

01:24:16.960 --> 01:24:21.960
[Amit Varma]: now, I am doing it through a newsletter. I have started the India Uncut newsletter at

01:24:21.960 --> 01:24:27.960
[Amit Varma]: indiancut.substack.com where I will write regularly about whatever catches my fancy.

01:24:27.960 --> 01:24:32.960
[Amit Varma]: I'll write about some of the themes I cover in this podcast and about much else. So please

01:24:32.960 --> 01:24:38.960
[Amit Varma]: do head on over to indiancut.substack.com and subscribe. It is free. Once you sign up,

01:24:38.960 --> 01:24:42.960
[Amit Varma]: each new installment that I write will land up in your email inbox. You don't need to

01:24:42.960 --> 01:24:50.960
[Amit Varma]: go anywhere. So subscribe now for free. The India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com.

01:24:50.960 --> 01:24:51.960
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

01:24:53.960 --> 01:24:57.960
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with Vinay Singhal and we've had

01:24:57.960 --> 01:25:03.960
[Amit Varma]: our little selfish break. Now it's time to just open up and sort of have a conversation

01:25:03.960 --> 01:25:09.960
[Amit Varma]: again. And tell me now about, you know, that part of the journey, which eventually ends

01:25:09.960 --> 01:25:15.960
[Amit Varma]: up in WittyFeed. Like you've, you know, we've gone with you to college and that sort of

01:25:15.960 --> 01:25:20.960
[Amit Varma]: that change has been happening. You've started your little NGO. You've started this little

01:25:20.960 --> 01:25:25.960
[Amit Varma]: site business making websites. Then eventually, how did you sort of gravitate towards WittyFeed

01:25:25.960 --> 01:25:26.960
[Guest]: happening?

01:25:26.960 --> 01:25:31.960
[Guest]: Yeah. So like I told you, the journey started with that NGO and the idea of funding that

01:25:31.960 --> 01:25:39.960
[Guest]: NGO. We were seven people when we started it, which is how the first, the name of our

01:25:39.960 --> 01:25:45.960
[Guest]: legal entity also came up. The company was called Vatsana Technologies and Vatsana also

01:25:45.960 --> 01:25:50.960
[Guest]: it's a Thai word, which means trust actually. And that's how we ended up like adopting the

01:25:50.960 --> 01:25:55.960
[Guest]: name. It's initial of everybody's name, all seven people's name, essentially. So we started

01:25:55.960 --> 01:26:02.960
[Guest]: to make websites, software for people. Literally we used to make websites for people for 500

01:26:02.960 --> 01:26:09.960
[Guest]: rupees. All your packer movers, all your property guys and all. And this is what 2010, 11, those

01:26:09.960 --> 01:26:17.960
[Guest]: years, right? So website was a cool thing, basically. And this was a time when here in

01:26:17.960 --> 01:26:22.960
[Guest]: Karol Bagh or somewhere I used to go to ask people for work, essentially. When I used

01:26:22.960 --> 01:26:27.960
[Guest]: to get clients from Chennai, we would get some clients and time when people will not

01:26:27.960 --> 01:26:32.960
[Guest]: take us seriously. Basically, what will we do? We will run away with the money or whatever,

01:26:32.960 --> 01:26:40.960
[Guest]: basically all that stuff, right? After, since Badlega Bharat Mein, we didn't know, like

01:26:40.960 --> 01:26:44.960
[Guest]: when I look back at it now, now we know that it was a content thing at the end of the day.

01:26:44.960 --> 01:26:51.960
[Guest]: We were writing a lot of content, etc. We had got a taste of it. Facebook happened basically

01:26:51.960 --> 01:26:56.960
[Guest]: around that time to us. And Purveen actually started a Facebook page, which was called

01:26:56.960 --> 01:27:03.960
[Guest]: amazing things in the world. And the idea was very simple. The idea was that we were

01:27:03.960 --> 01:27:10.960
[Guest]: just sitting and talking like this. Why is everything so negative in the world? Look

01:27:10.960 --> 01:27:15.960
[Guest]: at everything in the media, social media, you know, all your electronic media, look

01:27:15.960 --> 01:27:21.960
[Guest]: at Facebook, look at new channels, everyone looks at them like the world is going to end

01:27:21.960 --> 01:27:26.960
[Guest]: now, everything is going bad in the world. Whereas the world definitely has more good

01:27:26.960 --> 01:27:33.960
[Guest]: than bad, right? And that thought led us to sort of a brainstorming overnight thinking

01:27:33.960 --> 01:27:41.960
[Guest]: that what we realized was that negative is naturally viral because we are genetically

01:27:41.960 --> 01:27:48.960
[Guest]: prepared to spread bad news. Because see, our animal instincts say that the moment I

01:27:48.960 --> 01:27:53.960
[Guest]: see danger, the moment I see something bad, I'm supposed to warn everybody else of my

01:27:53.960 --> 01:28:01.960
[Guest]: kind. That is what virality is. So today's all these viral mechanisms, those clickbait

01:28:01.960 --> 01:28:10.960
[Guest]: sites like one we had, what people essentially do is they take sensational stuff, package

01:28:10.960 --> 01:28:17.960
[Guest]: it with fear. And so you share it very fast, which is why WhatsApp University and all these

01:28:17.960 --> 01:28:23.960
[Guest]: clips and all of those things work so fast, right? So we realized which means there is

01:28:23.960 --> 01:28:28.960
[Guest]: definitely more good in the world and there is more good in the world than bad. And so

01:28:28.960 --> 01:28:33.960
[Guest]: can we create something that appreciates the good in the world? So we started a community

01:28:33.960 --> 01:28:38.960
[Guest]: which was basically just for that. And it was called amazing things in the world. The

01:28:38.960 --> 01:28:42.960
[Guest]: Facebook page was called amazing things in the world. Exactly what it, it did exactly

01:28:42.960 --> 01:28:47.960
[Guest]: what it said, that we would, again, we're not content people by education, right?

01:28:47.960 --> 01:28:53.960
[Guest]: No one has done any journalism or mass communication and all that stuff, right? So we were engineers

01:28:53.960 --> 01:28:58.960
[Guest]: and we were all just figuring it out from a very common sense point of view. It makes

01:28:58.960 --> 01:29:03.960
[Guest]: sense, there should be more good. And at that time, frankly speaking, we still don't know,

01:29:03.960 --> 01:29:08.960
[Guest]: I mean, this was, this happened in 2012. We still don't know that we are making something

01:29:08.960 --> 01:29:12.960
[Guest]: of content or making a content company. In our minds, we just want to do something good

01:29:12.960 --> 01:29:17.960
[Guest]: in life, so let's do something like that. So we started this community. The idea was

01:29:17.960 --> 01:29:24.960
[Guest]: simple. We would curate, you know, content from everywhere on the internet and put it

01:29:24.960 --> 01:29:31.960
[Guest]: on this Facebook page. We didn't create any new content. We did curation basically. The

01:29:31.960 --> 01:29:39.960
[Guest]: idea went viral. The people, people responded. It seems like what worked in our favor was

01:29:39.960 --> 01:29:44.960
[Guest]: one was consistency. And going back to what my father taught, that shop is my temple,

01:29:44.960 --> 01:29:50.960
[Guest]: customer is my God. If you are doing this, then do it with genuine honesty. I mean, consistently

01:29:50.960 --> 01:29:55.960
[Guest]: we like one post every hour, meaning one post every hour, no matter what. We used to bring

01:29:55.960 --> 01:30:01.960
[Guest]: so much content from anywhere. And customer is my God, meaning that we would get at peak,

01:30:01.960 --> 01:30:10.960
[Guest]: I think, some thousand messages every day. Some people would come with requests, some

01:30:10.960 --> 01:30:16.960
[Guest]: people would come with, you know, suggestions, advice, criticism, whatever, basically. We

01:30:16.960 --> 01:30:22.960
[Guest]: used to reply to those messages in 24 hours. We would just sit down and reply to those

01:30:22.960 --> 01:30:26.960
[Guest]: messages. And this is when we had no idea what would happen. Why are we doing this?

01:30:26.960 --> 01:30:30.960
[Guest]: What will happen to this Facebook page, basically, at the end of the day, right? But we were

01:30:30.960 --> 01:30:36.960
[Guest]: doing it very religiously, you know. And I think that paid off. The community became

01:30:36.960 --> 01:30:40.960
[Guest]: very huge. Within the first six months, we had about a million followers. And this is

01:30:40.960 --> 01:30:46.960
[Guest]: all organic. Back in the day, in 2012, Facebook, Boost, Post, all this was not there. Organic

01:30:46.960 --> 01:30:51.960
[Guest]: was a thing. And I think we also got lucky, right place at the right time. Facebook was

01:30:51.960 --> 01:30:57.960
[Guest]: promoting pages as a thing. And organic reach was at its peak. And we just happened to create

01:30:57.960 --> 01:31:02.960
[Guest]: a Facebook page with a unique thing, basically, back in the day. If you remember, at that

01:31:02.960 --> 01:31:08.960
[Guest]: time, there was a very viral page called I Love Science. Its goodies were also sold and

01:31:08.960 --> 01:31:13.960
[Guest]: all that stuff, right? So we were one of those, we were pages of that category, at the same

01:31:13.960 --> 01:31:22.960
[Guest]: level. And primarily in the US. And so that Facebook page was our introduction to the

01:31:22.960 --> 01:31:26.960
[Guest]: world of content. At that time, we realized for the first time that we are a content company,

01:31:26.960 --> 01:31:31.960
[Guest]: a media company, we are talking about everything. Around the same time, in the first two years,

01:31:31.960 --> 01:31:35.960
[Guest]: we did not even know that this is a start-up. This is called a start-up. And what are investors,

01:31:35.960 --> 01:31:41.960
[Guest]: what are VCs? Frankly speaking, for the longest time, I did not understand why would somebody

01:31:41.960 --> 01:31:46.960
[Guest]: give you money when you are a loss-making company and all that stuff, right? Flipkart

01:31:46.960 --> 01:31:51.960
[Guest]: news, at that time, in 2010-11, Flipkart itself was big, basically. News used to hear about

01:31:51.960 --> 01:31:55.960
[Guest]: a loss of 5,000 crores, a loss of 4,000 crores, and it is also getting funding, 1 billion,

01:31:55.960 --> 01:32:01.960
[Guest]: 2 billion, etc. So my Marwadi mind used to ask me, and my father used to tell me that

01:32:01.960 --> 01:32:06.960
[Guest]: business is a function of wealth creation, in his own words. He used to say that. Here

01:32:06.960 --> 01:32:11.960
[Guest]: this story is going on, there are losses, people are giving money, what is this story?

01:32:11.960 --> 01:32:17.960
[Guest]: Basically, I had no idea how VC works, etc. So in the next 2-3 years, I understood that

01:32:17.960 --> 01:32:23.960
[Guest]: we are building a start-up, why investors invest, how does this entire thing work. Then

01:32:23.960 --> 01:32:29.960
[Guest]: we also realized that we are building a media company, content company, what does that mean?

01:32:29.960 --> 01:32:34.960
[Guest]: And what are the ways to make money in media? One of the earliest things that you realize

01:32:34.960 --> 01:32:39.960
[Guest]: is that you make money from ads, basically. You set up a blog, drive traffic, make money,

01:32:39.960 --> 01:32:45.960
[Guest]: right? So we did that. The first website that we made was called thestupidstation.com.

01:32:45.960 --> 01:32:48.960
[Amit Varma]: Nice name, man.

01:32:48.960 --> 01:32:56.960
[Guest]: I thought so, at least, when we started it, that TSS, thestupidstation.com, that it's

01:32:56.960 --> 01:33:01.960
[Guest]: a place of amazing stuff. Amazing people are stupid, basically, is what I believe. So,

01:33:01.960 --> 01:33:08.960
[Guest]: okay, you'll all come here. It's a place where you discover things which are unbelievable

01:33:08.960 --> 01:33:14.960
[Guest]: sort of stuff and all. And it was a unique name. The idea was, my understanding is a

01:33:14.960 --> 01:33:18.960
[Guest]: name should be so unique that it sticks with you. That's the function of it, basically.

01:33:18.960 --> 01:33:22.960
[Guest]: The work of the brand is not that much. It was definitely unique enough to stick, right?

01:33:22.960 --> 01:33:28.960
[Guest]: So we started, we set up a website and we would basically, whatever stories we posted

01:33:28.960 --> 01:33:33.960
[Guest]: on the website, we would write their detailed version on the website, essentially. So here

01:33:33.960 --> 01:33:41.960
[Guest]: we started creating some actual content. We started to write stuff of our own. And the

01:33:41.960 --> 01:33:49.960
[Guest]: idea would be that out of 24 posts a day, probably some 15 would still be on Facebook

01:33:49.960 --> 01:33:54.960
[Guest]: and 8-10 of them will be on the website and we'll post a link and drive the traffic. Crazy

01:33:54.960 --> 01:34:00.960
[Guest]: traffic. There was no limit to the organic reach at that time. It was amazing work. I

01:34:00.960 --> 01:34:06.960
[Guest]: mean, 20-30 million traffic. I mean, 10 million when we hit it for the first time. And we

01:34:06.960 --> 01:34:11.960
[Guest]: would go to all these Chennai meetups, founder meetups. We used to meet entrepreneurs. We

01:34:11.960 --> 01:34:14.960
[Guest]: used to tell them that we have 10 million traffic on our website. We are college students.

01:34:14.960 --> 01:34:19.960
[Guest]: People were like crazy. 10 million. How can that even happen? How is that even true?

01:34:19.960 --> 01:34:24.960
[Guest]: They ask us for a screenshot of our analytics. Show us a screenshot of Google Analytics.

01:34:24.960 --> 01:34:29.960
[Guest]: Another thing, most of our life, people have not believed what we have done because it

01:34:29.960 --> 01:34:34.960
[Guest]: was so unbelievable at least. I look back and I was like, we used to do a lot of crazy

01:34:34.960 --> 01:34:41.960
[Guest]: work at that time. 10 million, and this is 2013. 10 million traffic in India, I mean,

01:34:41.960 --> 01:34:49.960
[Guest]: it was crazy. 10 million, flip card traffic, probably 10-20 million at that time. And 30-40

01:34:49.960 --> 01:34:55.960
[Guest]: million page views a month, 10 million traffic. And it was all free. We had created a community

01:34:55.960 --> 01:35:02.960
[Guest]: and it was coming from there. We would monetize through Google Ads. And so in May 2013, Shashank

01:35:02.960 --> 01:35:08.960
[Guest]: and I passed out of college. In 2014, Praveen passed out. And when we passed out in 2013,

01:35:08.960 --> 01:35:15.960
[Guest]: we used to make 20-25 lakh rupees a month. And this was basically free money. Right?

01:35:15.960 --> 01:35:24.960
[Guest]: So, we, and you're like 22-23, you have so much money, 25 lakhs, my family must have

01:35:24.960 --> 01:35:30.960
[Guest]: seen Sahid once. Basically, my father would tell us that we are not doing anything wrong

01:35:30.960 --> 01:35:36.960
[Guest]: because 25 lakhs a month is a lot of money, right? So we did all that, it was quite amazing.

01:35:36.960 --> 01:35:41.960
[Guest]: So from here, our journey of content started. We learned two very important lessons out

01:35:41.960 --> 01:35:46.960
[Guest]: of this. Number one, which I have spoken about actually, during our earlier questions, which

01:35:46.960 --> 01:35:50.960
[Guest]: is that, number one, that there is nothing more powerful than content as a medium of

01:35:50.960 --> 01:35:56.960
[Guest]: mass influence. We understood this very clearly from here. Because look, we were a bunch of

01:35:56.960 --> 01:36:02.960
[Guest]: college kids sitting out of a dormitory in Chennai. And we were here, a Facebook page

01:36:02.960 --> 01:36:08.960
[Guest]: where we were making friends in the US, UK, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, all over Europe.

01:36:08.960 --> 01:36:14.960
[Guest]: And these were people, there was a mother who would message us saying that your page

01:36:14.960 --> 01:36:25.960
[Guest]: is like a bedtime story to my kids. Because it was all positive stuff, right? And basically

01:36:25.960 --> 01:36:30.960
[Guest]: she was like, you know, your page makes my kids believe that it's a really nice world

01:36:30.960 --> 01:36:35.960
[Guest]: out there, you know, believe in the good of the world, basically. We didn't sign up to

01:36:35.960 --> 01:36:40.960
[Guest]: do this, basically, to be honest. We didn't start with that in mind. There was a teacher

01:36:40.960 --> 01:36:47.960
[Guest]: in New Zealand whose message was that I teach 5th grade students and I start my class with

01:36:47.960 --> 01:36:53.960
[Guest]: your page, right? There was this girl, it became too much to handle when there was this

01:36:53.960 --> 01:36:57.960
[Guest]: girl who messaged us saying that you saved my life. We were like, what happened, you

01:36:57.960 --> 01:37:02.960
[Guest]: messaged us? She was a content creator, I think. She was in suspense. She wrote, you

01:37:02.960 --> 01:37:08.960
[Guest]: saved my life, thank you, you saved my life and left the message. Like, what happened?

01:37:08.960 --> 01:37:15.960
[Guest]: And then she told us the entire story. She had lost her father recently. And then she

01:37:15.960 --> 01:37:21.960
[Guest]: basically, she went into a depression. She was admitted to a hospital, so much so, and

01:37:21.960 --> 01:37:27.960
[Guest]: she was suicidal. And one of these days, she was just scrolling through Facebook. So, a

01:37:27.960 --> 01:37:32.960
[Guest]: post from our page landed into her feed through some friend or something. She went to our

01:37:32.960 --> 01:37:39.960
[Guest]: page and kept on, like, down the rabbit hole, but she kept on scrolling for hours and hours

01:37:39.960 --> 01:37:45.960
[Guest]: and hours. And then she was like, your page made me believe that there is so much good

01:37:45.960 --> 01:37:51.960
[Guest]: out there in the world that I'm missing out on. And now I'm going on a world tour. And

01:37:51.960 --> 01:37:55.960
[Guest]: I'm all out of depression, all that stuff, you know, like, what the hell? It's too much,

01:37:55.960 --> 01:38:00.960
[Guest]: right? Again, 23-year-olds, how do you handle all of that stuff? Which is when we realized

01:38:00.960 --> 01:38:08.960
[Guest]: that content is not a medium to create mass influence. In the world, we had six, that

01:38:08.960 --> 01:38:13.960
[Guest]: community grew to about six million, let it speak. Six million people, through that,

01:38:13.960 --> 01:38:18.960
[Guest]: it was at least 40-50 million, even more than that at peak, probably. We reach so many people

01:38:18.960 --> 01:38:23.960
[Guest]: every month, which is humongous, right? I will do anything, but reaching 50 million

01:38:23.960 --> 01:38:29.960
[Guest]: people is not a joke, right? So, that was the first belief. Second belief that we understood

01:38:29.960 --> 01:38:35.960
[Guest]: from there was that if content is king, distribution is God. The real power is distribution, because

01:38:35.960 --> 01:38:40.960
[Guest]: we also realized that none of these stories, none of these content pieces were something

01:38:40.960 --> 01:38:47.960
[Guest]: that did not exist before we existed. All these nice places, nice people, nice inventions

01:38:47.960 --> 01:38:57.960
[Guest]: that we talked about. All we did was we brought them and we created a distribution mechanism

01:38:57.960 --> 01:39:02.960
[Guest]: through this community that it can reach to so many people, right? And so, the real power

01:39:02.960 --> 01:39:07.960
[Guest]: was in distribution itself, right? So, you can write an amazing book, you can create

01:39:07.960 --> 01:39:11.960
[Guest]: a great movie, but if nobody reads it, nobody watches it, what's the point basically, right?

01:39:11.960 --> 01:39:16.960
[Guest]: It is then made for libraries. And so, our second belief from there became very strong

01:39:16.960 --> 01:39:23.960
[Guest]: that the real power is in distribution. And that is what then finally in 2014, when we

01:39:23.960 --> 01:39:30.960
[Guest]: figured out what to do, which is what led us to starting WittyFeed. WittyFeed, in the

01:39:30.960 --> 01:39:36.960
[Guest]: front of it, it was like a viral content site, basically pretty much like that. But in the

01:39:36.960 --> 01:39:42.960
[Guest]: back end, we actually solved the distribution. So, the unique thing that we did, the real

01:39:42.960 --> 01:39:47.960
[Guest]: secret source of WittyFeed was the distribution. Again, we were not people of content. I am

01:39:47.960 --> 01:39:52.960
[Guest]: saying this again and again that content was not our forte. So, what we did, he said, if

01:39:52.960 --> 01:39:57.960
[Guest]: one Facebook page can do so much, and if all the Facebook pages of the world are combined

01:39:57.960 --> 01:40:03.960
[Guest]: and their distribution is combined, then you can build a very, very large influence basically.

01:40:03.960 --> 01:40:07.960
[Guest]: And on the other hand, there was no way to make money through Facebook pages. So, again,

01:40:07.960 --> 01:40:12.960
[Guest]: social good and a way to make money, right? So, we figured it out. We set up a website,

01:40:12.960 --> 01:40:17.960
[Guest]: we set up a Google ad, drive traffic on it, manage its entire server infrastructure. So,

01:40:17.960 --> 01:40:21.960
[Guest]: we were like, if you can provide this as a service to people, you know, there is no way

01:40:21.960 --> 01:40:25.960
[Guest]: to make money through Facebook pages today. People have millions and millions of followers,

01:40:25.960 --> 01:40:29.960
[Guest]: but they don't know how to make money out of it. And not everybody knows how to set

01:40:29.960 --> 01:40:36.960
[Guest]: up a website, then regularly create content on it, figure out Google ads, people just

01:40:36.960 --> 01:40:42.960
[Guest]: don't know all of that shit, right? So, we said, let's do this. So, we created

01:40:42.960 --> 01:40:49.960
[Guest]: world's first ever content affiliate network back in the day. If you have a social community,

01:40:49.960 --> 01:40:55.960
[Guest]: join us. You have access to all content of WittyFeed, you share it with your people and

01:40:55.960 --> 01:40:59.960
[Guest]: whatever traffic you will drive back to our website, we will basically do a revenue share

01:40:59.960 --> 01:41:06.960
[Guest]: with you. So, this was a very unique idea at that time. And the idea went viral. Over

01:41:06.960 --> 01:41:14.960
[Guest]: the next four years, we had 65,000 such influencers working with us across the world. And we scaled

01:41:14.960 --> 01:41:19.960
[Guest]: to about 120 million uniques month on month on the website. It was a bootstrap company.

01:41:19.960 --> 01:41:26.960
[Guest]: Again, back in the day, we were doing... So, we shifted to Indore in 2014. And we started

01:41:26.960 --> 01:41:36.960
[Guest]: this company in September 2014. So, we were doing everything that most, that was basically

01:41:36.960 --> 01:41:41.960
[Guest]: things that the startup world believed that couldn't be done at that point in time. Building

01:41:41.960 --> 01:41:49.960
[Guest]: from tier 2, bootstrapped, revenue, profitable, and global from India. This is like every

01:41:49.960 --> 01:41:55.960
[Guest]: notion of startups that people thought that this can't be done from India basically. At

01:41:55.960 --> 01:42:00.960
[Guest]: peak of about 40 crores annual revenue, we became the third largest media balance sheet

01:42:00.960 --> 01:42:05.960
[Guest]: in India back in the day, digital media balance sheet. Times Internet, HD and then us. Because

01:42:05.960 --> 01:42:11.960
[Guest]: no one made revenue of 40 crores at that time. Digital didn't make that much money. We used

01:42:11.960 --> 01:42:14.960
[Guest]: to tell people 100 million traffic here. So, people used to say, what are you talking about?

01:42:14.960 --> 01:42:17.960
[Guest]: There must be some scam from Indore, there must be some scam, there must be a lot of

01:42:17.960 --> 01:42:21.960
[Guest]: traffic, 100 million. Does it happen? There are not 100 million users in India right now.

01:42:21.960 --> 01:42:26.960
[Guest]: But they wouldn't realize that out of 100, 50, 60 million was, out of 120, 60 million

01:42:26.960 --> 01:42:31.960
[Guest]: was from US alone. And when you told them that, it became even more unbelievable. How

01:42:31.960 --> 01:42:38.960
[Guest]: do you create content for US from Indore and all that stuff. But yeah, so that's how we

01:42:38.960 --> 01:42:42.960
[Guest]: landed at WittyFeed and then it became a story of its own.

01:42:42.960 --> 01:42:47.960
[Amit Varma]: So, tell me a bit about how you arrived at your content philosophy in terms of figuring

01:42:47.960 --> 01:42:53.960
[Amit Varma]: out what works. Like a lot of you are from Sringda's book, I looked at some of your headlines

01:42:53.960 --> 01:42:57.960
[Amit Varma]: from that day and like one of them is, why your best friend is your true love, just like

01:42:57.960 --> 01:43:02.960
[Amit Varma]: Mila Kunis and Ashton Kutcher. And then this is what you want to know about Amanda, Justin

01:43:02.960 --> 01:43:09.960
[Amit Varma]: Bieber's new girlfriend, and so on and so forth. So, how did you sort of arrive at the

01:43:09.960 --> 01:43:14.960
[Amit Varma]: triggers and the hooks which really work in terms of content? And looking back on it now,

01:43:14.960 --> 01:43:18.960
[Amit Varma]: or even thinking about it back then, because you obviously, as soon as you figured out

01:43:18.960 --> 01:43:22.960
[Amit Varma]: the triggers, you figured out the deeper question, which is what does it reveal about us? What

01:43:22.960 --> 01:43:27.960
[Amit Varma]: does it reveal about human beings that a certain set of things draw our attention and make

01:43:27.960 --> 01:43:29.960
[Amit Varma]: us click and other things don't?

01:43:29.960 --> 01:43:35.960
[Guest]: Yeah, so I actually used to give a presentation on this. Virality, I believe, is more science

01:43:35.960 --> 01:43:43.960
[Guest]: less art. Tukka nahi hota hai basically virality, right? You can actually plan it pretty much.

01:43:43.960 --> 01:43:48.960
[Guest]: Ab to chalo most people do that, usse time pe itna wo nahi hota tha. There are three

01:43:48.960 --> 01:43:54.960
[Guest]: elements to it. There is a title. And this is again back in the days when text content

01:43:54.960 --> 01:43:59.960
[Guest]: articles were the way to consume most of the content, right? So there's a title, there's

01:43:59.960 --> 01:44:05.960
[Guest]: a thumbnail, and then there is distribution, basically that how do you distribute it, right?

01:44:05.960 --> 01:44:13.960
[Guest]: So title and thumbnail are pretty much like a trailer of a movie, right? So they give

01:44:13.960 --> 01:44:20.960
[Guest]: you that your title and thumbnail of a story has to be good enough. It tells you enough

01:44:20.960 --> 01:44:26.960
[Guest]: to generate a curiosity that it should want to make you click. So title aur thumbnail

01:44:26.960 --> 01:44:32.960
[Guest]: ka kaam hota hai clickability drive karna. So clickability is the number one masala in

01:44:32.960 --> 01:44:37.960
[Guest]: the recipe basically of virality. So title and thumbnail leads to clickability of it.

01:44:37.960 --> 01:44:41.960
[Guest]: So it generates enough curiosity that you want to click on it, but doesn't tell you

01:44:41.960 --> 01:44:47.960
[Guest]: everything so that you're not interested anymore, basically, right? The second one is shareability.

01:44:47.960 --> 01:44:58.960
[Guest]: That is the job of the content inside, right? So people share stuff when it makes you feel

01:44:58.960 --> 01:45:04.960
[Guest]: something. And it can be good, bad, anger, happiness, whatever, basically, but it has

01:45:04.960 --> 01:45:09.960
[Guest]: to generate an emotion. That is when you will share it, you will comment on it. It has to

01:45:09.960 --> 01:45:14.960
[Guest]: trigger you basically. It has to speak to you in some way. So relatability of the content

01:45:14.960 --> 01:45:20.960
[Guest]: is very, very important, which basically leads to shareability over time. So more people

01:45:20.960 --> 01:45:25.960
[Guest]: share it, more people see it. So more people click on it. And so it's a virtuous cycle

01:45:25.960 --> 01:45:33.960
[Guest]: basically that way, right? But for this entire thing to work, there is a threshold distribution

01:45:33.960 --> 01:45:37.960
[Guest]: that has to happen. And which is what we correct through the platform that we built. It was

01:45:37.960 --> 01:45:46.960
[Guest]: called Viral 9, by the way, Viral 9 as a number. So Viral 9 was our way to jumpstart and give

01:45:46.960 --> 01:45:50.960
[Guest]: the threshold distribution to a particular story. And then it basically, then it took

01:45:50.960 --> 01:45:55.960
[Guest]: off from there, essentially, right? So clickability, shareability, and then distribution, threshold

01:45:55.960 --> 01:46:01.960
[Guest]: distribution. Those are the three elements to making it viral. What worked as a content

01:46:01.960 --> 01:46:10.960
[Guest]: basically? People want to know about other people. Basically, we are creepily very interested

01:46:10.960 --> 01:46:16.960
[Guest]: into what other people are doing in their lives, etc. Right? So celebrity stuff would

01:46:16.960 --> 01:46:24.960
[Guest]: work amazingly well. Humor is a evergreen content basically. So again, there's so much

01:46:24.960 --> 01:46:30.960
[Guest]: bad out there at all times. When something that lightens your mood and something that

01:46:30.960 --> 01:46:37.960
[Guest]: cheers you up, pops up in your feed, you will mostly click on it and you will go and see

01:46:37.960 --> 01:46:42.960
[Guest]: what is there and all, right? And then the specialty that we built was, like I said,

01:46:42.960 --> 01:46:47.960
[Guest]: we tried to remain on the positive side of the content all the time. Like at least, if

01:46:47.960 --> 01:46:54.960
[Guest]: it is not positive, then this content should not be negative. Our underlining agenda was

01:46:54.960 --> 01:47:00.960
[Guest]: that I used to say that every interaction of a content that we generate with people

01:47:00.960 --> 01:47:07.960
[Guest]: out there, imagine it as a smile. So this exercise will sound almost like a cult building.

01:47:07.960 --> 01:47:11.960
[Guest]: But when we used to do morning stand-ups, I would basically ask my entire team to close

01:47:11.960 --> 01:47:17.960
[Guest]: their eyes and tell them that, like, imagine every click that a user is doing on your content.

01:47:17.960 --> 01:47:21.960
[Guest]: Every time your content pops up in their feed and they click on it, they like it, they share

01:47:21.960 --> 01:47:25.960
[Guest]: it, they comment on it, they land on our website and then they scroll through the page. Every

01:47:25.960 --> 01:47:30.960
[Guest]: single instance is a smile that you are leaving out there, a positive energy that you are

01:47:30.960 --> 01:47:35.960
[Guest]: leaving out there in the world. And that is why you work, like that is the work that you

01:47:35.960 --> 01:47:42.960
[Guest]: are doing here. That was my way of basically helping my team find a purpose in whatever

01:47:42.960 --> 01:47:46.960
[Guest]: we were doing basically. So purpose was to generate more smiles out there. And so we

01:47:46.960 --> 01:47:52.960
[Guest]: tried to remain on the positive side of the content. I would not make the mistake of saying

01:47:52.960 --> 01:47:57.960
[Guest]: that our 100% content was like this. I am sure it was a team of 70 people. In order

01:47:57.960 --> 01:48:03.960
[Guest]: to generate traffic, they must have made something that would be negative as well. But we tried

01:48:03.960 --> 01:48:10.960
[Guest]: to remain on the positive side of it. So like photography, I mean, like photography and

01:48:10.960 --> 01:48:14.960
[Guest]: travel used to get mixed a lot, 10 places to travel and like amazing pictures. People

01:48:14.960 --> 01:48:18.960
[Guest]: loved that. People used to love that with us. Because everything started from there

01:48:18.960 --> 01:48:25.960
[Guest]: originally. Amazing people stories, you know, stories of underdogs, people winning, you

01:48:25.960 --> 01:48:31.960
[Guest]: know, and good winning over bad. We used to do a lot of such viral content. You remember

01:48:31.960 --> 01:48:38.960
[Guest]: there was a website back in the day, parallel to us called Upworthy. So we actually would

01:48:38.960 --> 01:48:44.960
[Guest]: have a lot of similar, we were all of the same category, you know, BuzzFeed, Upworthy,

01:48:44.960 --> 01:48:49.960
[Guest]: WittyFeed, Dipply, little things. All of us were in the same category of that, which is

01:48:49.960 --> 01:48:55.960
[Guest]: why all of us are dead now. So same, same usse basically sab belong karte the sense

01:48:55.960 --> 01:49:00.960
[Guest]: similar type of content is what we would create. So negative works, but we had to figure out

01:49:00.960 --> 01:49:06.960
[Guest]: beyond negative and which is where we figured out that compassion works, you know, celebrity

01:49:06.960 --> 01:49:11.360
[Guest]: works, humor works, history works. History was another very big thing for us by the way.

01:49:11.360 --> 01:49:17.860
[Guest]: If you show historical photographs to people, it was a very viral content.

01:49:17.860 --> 01:49:24.660
[Guest]: You know, 10 pictures from India from 1857 for example.

01:49:24.660 --> 01:49:27.260
[Guest]: It's a viral article. If you make it today, it will work even today.

01:49:27.260 --> 01:49:29.960
[Guest]: I know this forever. There is a lot of curiosity in these articles.

01:49:29.960 --> 01:49:32.660
[Guest]: How did India look like? How were the people at that time?

01:49:32.660 --> 01:49:34.960
[Guest]: So we will want to see that basically.

01:49:34.960 --> 01:49:38.760
[Guest]: It was mostly pictorial content. So it used to work.

01:49:38.760 --> 01:49:42.460
[Amit Varma]: Amazing. One negative headline of yours which I found was,

01:49:42.460 --> 01:49:46.360
[Amit Varma]: how your face would look if you survived a car crash.

01:49:46.360 --> 01:49:48.260
[Amit Varma]: And I can imagine this would have been pictorial also.

01:49:48.260 --> 01:49:51.160
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to actually go and look for this because I'm very curious now

01:49:51.160 --> 01:49:55.360
[Amit Varma]: that how would your face look if you survived a car crash.

01:49:55.360 --> 01:50:01.260
[Amit Varma]: The other very interesting thing I find about this is that you are creating content

01:50:01.260 --> 01:50:05.260
[Amit Varma]: which is going madly viral in the United States most of all

01:50:05.260 --> 01:50:07.260
[Amit Varma]: where the culture is completely different.

01:50:07.260 --> 01:50:10.260
[Amit Varma]: American pop culture is completely different there.

01:50:10.260 --> 01:50:12.160
[Amit Varma]: Everything is completely different.

01:50:12.160 --> 01:50:16.460
[Amit Varma]: You know, little things like how people romance, how people date, how people...

01:50:16.460 --> 01:50:20.460
[Amit Varma]: Everything is different. Right? And you have a bunch of young kids in indoor.

01:50:20.460 --> 01:50:25.660
[Amit Varma]: And they have to get inside the minds of the American public as it were

01:50:25.660 --> 01:50:28.260
[Amit Varma]: and figure out what works, what doesn't work, all of that.

01:50:28.260 --> 01:50:34.260
[Amit Varma]: So how was this process? Was it a process of kind of discovering universal hooks

01:50:34.260 --> 01:50:36.660
[Amit Varma]: that these are things that everyone is interested in?

01:50:36.660 --> 01:50:40.160
[Amit Varma]: Or was it a case of also doing trial and error where you figure out

01:50:40.160 --> 01:50:42.660
[Amit Varma]: some things don't work and therefore the other things work?

01:50:42.660 --> 01:50:46.960
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, when you're writing pieces like which might have dating advice

01:50:46.960 --> 01:50:49.060
[Amit Varma]: or why your best friend is your true love,

01:50:49.060 --> 01:50:54.160
[Amit Varma]: then, you know, how do these young people who are from indoor,

01:50:54.160 --> 01:50:58.860
[Amit Varma]: how are they able to sort of do something that actually works with an American audience?

01:50:58.860 --> 01:51:02.460
[Guest]: So two, three things. One, it was a mix of all of this basically.

01:51:02.460 --> 01:51:05.760
[Guest]: So, of course, we try to keep a lot of our content global

01:51:05.760 --> 01:51:09.160
[Guest]: because it was not just Americans which were our audience.

01:51:09.160 --> 01:51:13.260
[Guest]: So Canada, UK, Australia, New Zealand and all these are very different cultures.

01:51:13.260 --> 01:51:19.260
[Guest]: So they're not like... not very similar in nature apart from the fact that they speak English.

01:51:19.260 --> 01:51:22.960
[Guest]: So we would try to keep a lot of our content global in nature, etc.

01:51:22.960 --> 01:51:24.860
[Guest]: And advice, etc. global in nature.

01:51:24.860 --> 01:51:28.260
[Guest]: But having said that, all our team was...

01:51:28.260 --> 01:51:31.560
[Guest]: Ek toh, we would ask them to watch all American sitcoms,

01:51:31.560 --> 01:51:35.160
[Guest]: all American serials, understand the cultural nuances,

01:51:35.160 --> 01:51:37.760
[Guest]: the way people talk, what they say, etc.

01:51:37.760 --> 01:51:40.260
[Guest]: So that's how we would do it.

01:51:40.260 --> 01:51:43.560
[Guest]: Second, we would use a lot of data.

01:51:43.560 --> 01:51:49.260
[Guest]: So basically, being engineers came into play there, right?

01:51:49.260 --> 01:51:52.860
[Guest]: That all three, all between the three founders, two of us were engineers.

01:51:52.860 --> 01:51:55.160
[Guest]: So we knew that...

01:51:55.160 --> 01:51:59.060
[Guest]: And the guy who runs content was not the engineer in our case, right?

01:51:59.060 --> 01:52:02.860
[Guest]: So Shashank is an engineer, he's a CTO.

01:52:02.860 --> 01:52:07.160
[Guest]: I was the engineer and Praveen, who is not the engineer, was the content guy among us.

01:52:07.160 --> 01:52:09.360
[Guest]: So it was a very complimentary skill set there.

01:52:09.360 --> 01:52:13.560
[Guest]: And we would have a lot of data in terms of what stories work, what don't.

01:52:13.560 --> 01:52:17.460
[Guest]: In which story does the user read up to, where does it drop, why is it dropping.

01:52:17.460 --> 01:52:20.360
[Guest]: A lot of such insights we would essentially use.

01:52:20.360 --> 01:52:24.660
[Guest]: And all of this data would go back to our team and...

01:52:24.660 --> 01:52:28.360
[Guest]: Again, like I said, virality is less gut, more science.

01:52:28.360 --> 01:52:31.260
[Guest]: And so we would use that data to plan,

01:52:31.260 --> 01:52:36.760
[Guest]: that okay, this story is going on, so let's make more of these type of stories, etc.

01:52:36.760 --> 01:52:40.960
[Guest]: We did... Whatever is written in this, it must be correct, so it's going on, basically.

01:52:40.960 --> 01:52:43.260
[Guest]: So how do we mimic more of these and also...

01:52:43.260 --> 01:52:45.760
[Guest]: Actually, a lot of content used to be of a similar type.

01:52:45.760 --> 01:52:48.960
[Guest]: Because once it goes on, you want to repeat that as a business at the end of the day, right?

01:52:48.960 --> 01:52:50.760
[Guest]: So we would do that.

01:52:50.760 --> 01:52:56.960
[Guest]: Secondly, it was my underlining agenda, basically.

01:52:56.960 --> 01:52:59.760
[Guest]: And my patriotic side came into play there.

01:52:59.760 --> 01:53:08.260
[Guest]: And also, I always felt that West has some unnecessary and undue influence

01:53:08.260 --> 01:53:14.160
[Guest]: on how the rest of the world's media works, basically, right?

01:53:14.160 --> 01:53:20.360
[Guest]: You can call it our colonial baggage, or you can call it racism.

01:53:20.360 --> 01:53:23.860
[Guest]: Whites are smart, blacks are not, right?

01:53:23.860 --> 01:53:25.760
[Guest]: And all of that, basically.

01:53:25.760 --> 01:53:29.160
[Guest]: And these guys are genuinely great storytellers.

01:53:29.160 --> 01:53:32.160
[Guest]: So they have made it like that.

01:53:32.160 --> 01:53:37.560
[Guest]: For some reason, US is the power center of the world.

01:53:37.560 --> 01:53:41.960
[Guest]: At least the entire world believes that, even if it's not, right?

01:53:41.960 --> 01:53:52.160
[Guest]: So I wanted a flavor of Indian or Asian thing going to the world.

01:53:52.160 --> 01:53:55.360
[Guest]: I mean, we always consume them, right?

01:53:55.360 --> 01:54:02.160
[Guest]: Why can't we create media in India and the world should consume it, right?

01:54:02.160 --> 01:54:04.960
[Guest]: So actually, I used to consciously tell my team,

01:54:04.960 --> 01:54:06.360
[Guest]: yes, we want to be relevant.

01:54:06.360 --> 01:54:07.560
[Guest]: Our audience is Americans.

01:54:07.560 --> 01:54:09.160
[Guest]: We want to be relevant to them.

01:54:09.160 --> 01:54:12.360
[Guest]: But I don't want you to lose the fact that you are Indians

01:54:12.360 --> 01:54:14.560
[Guest]: or writing it for them, basically.

01:54:14.560 --> 01:54:20.360
[Guest]: So I want you to preserve that and so have a taste of that always,

01:54:20.360 --> 01:54:24.560
[Guest]: you know, when you're giving some advice or writing any piece of article, etc, right?

01:54:24.560 --> 01:54:27.560
[Guest]: I remember an anecdote.

01:54:27.560 --> 01:54:30.160
[Guest]: Late Siri Gatilbihari Vajpayee ji passed away, right?

01:54:30.160 --> 01:54:35.360
[Guest]: And so I told my team that we should definitely do a front page story.

01:54:35.360 --> 01:54:39.160
[Guest]: It should be a story and it should be a homepage story,

01:54:39.160 --> 01:54:42.360
[Guest]: definitely on our website, etc.

01:54:42.360 --> 01:54:45.560
[Guest]: So my team, my editorial, of course, disagreed with it.

01:54:45.560 --> 01:54:47.160
[Guest]: They said, it's not relevant.

01:54:47.160 --> 01:54:49.160
[Guest]: Our audience is US.

01:54:49.160 --> 01:54:50.760
[Guest]: What difference does it make to them?

01:54:50.760 --> 01:54:52.960
[Guest]: I said, tell me something.

01:54:52.960 --> 01:54:58.360
[Guest]: If an American leader passes away, let's say Obama, for example, or whatever, whoever,

01:54:58.360 --> 01:55:03.560
[Guest]: would every Indian publication do a story on them and would it feature on homepage or not?

01:55:03.560 --> 01:55:05.960
[Guest]: And of course, we are America's leader.

01:55:05.960 --> 01:55:09.360
[Guest]: In the same way, this is an important country in the world.

01:55:09.360 --> 01:55:12.360
[Guest]: We are one of the more powerful country and like,

01:55:12.360 --> 01:55:16.360
[Guest]: it represents seventh of the population of the world or more than that, actually.

01:55:16.360 --> 01:55:20.360
[Guest]: So why do you think that the leader of these people passed away

01:55:20.360 --> 01:55:21.960
[Guest]: and it is not relevant for the world?

01:55:21.960 --> 01:55:25.560
[Guest]: If you don't feel so, the world is never going to feel it, right?

01:55:25.560 --> 01:55:29.160
[Guest]: So we used to add such flavors in between.

01:55:29.160 --> 01:55:32.360
[Guest]: I don't, again, I might be thinking wrong here.

01:55:32.360 --> 01:55:34.160
[Guest]: There's no right and wrong, I think.

01:55:34.160 --> 01:55:39.560
[Guest]: It was just my perspective, my opinion, my way of bringing an Indian flavor to the world.

01:55:39.560 --> 01:55:42.960
[Guest]: Like, why should world not have an Indian flavor of content, etc.

01:55:42.960 --> 01:55:44.960
[Guest]: They used to do all of it.

01:55:44.960 --> 01:55:46.360
[Guest]: There was a lot of trial and error.

01:55:46.360 --> 01:55:48.760
[Guest]: Some content used to work, some didn't.

01:55:48.760 --> 01:55:53.960
[Guest]: We were like a content factory.

01:55:53.960 --> 01:56:00.360
[Guest]: 70 people writing more than 100 new articles every day.

01:56:00.360 --> 01:56:05.760
[Guest]: Thankfully, we had to write less text because it was pictorial content.

01:56:05.760 --> 01:56:07.960
[Guest]: But still, it's a lot.

01:56:07.960 --> 01:56:11.560
[Guest]: So when you are producing in such a mass,

01:56:11.560 --> 01:56:15.560
[Guest]: if we had 10 stories on any given day, that was a lot.

01:56:15.560 --> 01:56:19.160
[Guest]: Then every influencer, all these 65,000 would share the same story.

01:56:19.160 --> 01:56:22.560
[Guest]: They go big, we get our traffic, it's all good, right?

01:56:22.560 --> 01:56:25.760
[Guest]: So more of them didn't work, less of them worked,

01:56:25.760 --> 01:56:28.560
[Guest]: but the ones who worked gave us all the traffic that we needed.

01:56:28.560 --> 01:56:30.960
[Guest]: That's how, basically, we built it.

01:56:30.960 --> 01:56:34.560
[Amit Varma]: I think that point you made about wanting to push Indian content out there

01:56:34.560 --> 01:56:39.360
[Amit Varma]: is really interesting because I think like the argument your guys would have made against it,

01:56:39.360 --> 01:56:40.960
[Amit Varma]: it's about supply and demand.

01:56:40.960 --> 01:56:41.960
[Amit Varma]: There is no demand from there.

01:56:41.960 --> 01:56:43.960
[Amit Varma]: Here, we will do Obama because there is demand.

01:56:43.960 --> 01:56:46.560
[Amit Varma]: And there is a perception that there is demand, but it's not there.

01:56:46.560 --> 01:56:50.760
[Amit Varma]: But the counterpoint to that is that you can change the demand with supply.

01:56:50.760 --> 01:56:51.760
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:56:51.760 --> 01:56:55.760
[Guest]: My point was that if that story is not visible in front of the audience,

01:56:55.760 --> 01:56:58.160
[Guest]: then how will they consume it?

01:56:58.160 --> 01:56:59.760
[Guest]: You put it, maybe it will not work.

01:56:59.760 --> 01:57:04.160
[Guest]: Maybe your typical story does 100k users.

01:57:04.160 --> 01:57:05.560
[Guest]: This one will do 10,000.

01:57:05.560 --> 01:57:06.960
[Guest]: But that's okay, right?

01:57:06.960 --> 01:57:09.760
[Guest]: 10,000 have read that narrative.

01:57:09.760 --> 01:57:11.360
[Guest]: And so that will make an impact.

01:57:11.360 --> 01:57:14.360
[Guest]: So you don't have to go big every time.

01:57:14.360 --> 01:57:17.760
[Guest]: Those small, small changes would lead to some large impact over time.

01:57:17.760 --> 01:57:19.760
[Guest]: So that's exactly the point I made.

01:57:19.760 --> 01:57:23.360
[Guest]: And maybe I was the CEO, that is why I won.

01:57:23.360 --> 01:57:25.960
[Guest]: Or maybe the point won it, but I got the story.

01:57:25.960 --> 01:57:27.960
[Amit Varma]: I got the story on the homepage for a day.

01:57:27.960 --> 01:57:29.560
[Amit Varma]: And there's another interesting angle here,

01:57:29.560 --> 01:57:32.360
[Amit Varma]: with which I'll lead to my next observation and question,

01:57:32.360 --> 01:57:33.560
[Amit Varma]: which is that, like you said,

01:57:33.560 --> 01:57:36.560
[Amit Varma]: if a regular story gets 100,000 and this gets 10,000,

01:57:36.560 --> 01:57:41.960
[Amit Varma]: the point is that these 10,000 are more engaged than those other 100,000

01:57:41.960 --> 01:57:44.160
[Amit Varma]: because these people clicked on it in the first place

01:57:44.160 --> 01:57:46.560
[Amit Varma]: because they are interested or they are that curious

01:57:46.560 --> 01:57:47.560
[Amit Varma]: and they're finding out.

01:57:47.560 --> 01:57:48.760
[Amit Varma]: Whereas in the 100,000,

01:57:48.760 --> 01:57:51.760
[Amit Varma]: there'll be a lot of people who just kind of skim the content.

01:57:51.760 --> 01:57:55.760
[Amit Varma]: And I have recently sort of been trying to think about media

01:57:55.760 --> 01:57:57.360
[Amit Varma]: and the creator economy.

01:57:57.360 --> 01:57:59.960
[Amit Varma]: And the frame that I use is something like earlier,

01:57:59.960 --> 01:58:02.560
[Amit Varma]: we were talking about thin desires and thick desires.

01:58:02.560 --> 01:58:06.960
[Amit Varma]: And the frame that I use for this is thick engagement and thin engagement.

01:58:06.960 --> 01:58:10.360
[Amit Varma]: Like I keep telling people that I would rather have

01:58:10.360 --> 01:58:13.560
[Amit Varma]: a 100,000 people listen to one of my episodes

01:58:13.560 --> 01:58:16.960
[Amit Varma]: than do a 10-minute video and get 20 million views for it.

01:58:16.960 --> 01:58:19.360
[Amit Varma]: And the reason for that is at 20 million views,

01:58:19.360 --> 01:58:21.160
[Amit Varma]: the engagement will be thin,

01:58:21.160 --> 01:58:23.960
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, people will drop off at 15 seconds,

01:58:23.960 --> 01:58:25.560
[Amit Varma]: drop off at 20 seconds.

01:58:25.560 --> 01:58:28.160
[Amit Varma]: But here my average session time is 40 minutes plus

01:58:28.160 --> 01:58:30.560
[Amit Varma]: and here the engagement is much deeper.

01:58:30.560 --> 01:58:31.960
[Amit Varma]: I hear from my listeners.

01:58:31.960 --> 01:58:34.960
[Amit Varma]: I am, you know, and in very tangible ways,

01:58:34.960 --> 01:58:37.560
[Amit Varma]: I understand how thick the engagement is.

01:58:37.560 --> 01:58:40.760
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is that this is not something

01:58:40.760 --> 01:58:45.560
[Amit Varma]: like when advertisers or sponsors think about your business.

01:58:45.560 --> 01:58:47.360
[Amit Varma]: They think in those absolute numbers.

01:58:47.360 --> 01:58:50.960
[Amit Varma]: That 20 million is way more impressive than a 100,000 or whatever.

01:58:50.960 --> 01:58:53.960
[Amit Varma]: But actually the value of that thick engagement to me

01:58:53.960 --> 01:58:55.760
[Amit Varma]: is like way greater, right?

01:58:55.760 --> 01:58:59.360
[Amit Varma]: So in your business, is that also something that

01:58:59.360 --> 01:59:00.560
[Amit Varma]: you sort of thought about?

01:59:00.560 --> 01:59:02.960
[Amit Varma]: Like you've already said that you could see

01:59:02.960 --> 01:59:05.560
[Amit Varma]: which article people are reading to what extent,

01:59:05.560 --> 01:59:08.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, which is also an element of how much engagement there is.

01:59:08.160 --> 01:59:08.360
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:59:08.360 --> 01:59:10.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I guess how many times they are sharing is an example

01:59:10.960 --> 01:59:12.760
[Amit Varma]: because that obviously indicates.

01:59:12.760 --> 01:59:17.360
[Amit Varma]: So tell me your sort of learnings with regard to different levels of engagement

01:59:17.360 --> 01:59:21.560
[Amit Varma]: and not like, you know, people speak of clickbait disparagingly

01:59:21.560 --> 01:59:25.960
[Amit Varma]: that you made a person click, but the main process really starts after that

01:59:25.960 --> 01:59:26.960
[Amit Varma]: that how engaged are they?

01:59:26.960 --> 01:59:27.760
[Amit Varma]: Are they going to come back?

01:59:27.760 --> 01:59:28.560
[Guest]: Are they going to share?

01:59:28.560 --> 01:59:28.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:59:28.760 --> 01:59:30.360
[Amit Varma]: So what are your learnings on that?

01:59:30.360 --> 01:59:33.960
[Guest]: Yeah, so yeah, like I think what you said at the end of it

01:59:33.960 --> 01:59:35.360
[Guest]: is probably the answer of it also.

01:59:35.360 --> 01:59:40.360
[Guest]: That you can make somebody click on it by doing a clickbait article,

01:59:40.360 --> 01:59:42.760
[Guest]: a clickbait title and thumbnail,

01:59:42.760 --> 01:59:45.960
[Guest]: but you can't make them stay on your website

01:59:45.960 --> 01:59:48.560
[Guest]: if you don't really have a meat, you know,

01:59:48.560 --> 01:59:51.160
[Guest]: in the content that you are writing.

01:59:51.160 --> 01:59:57.160
[Guest]: So which is why the stuff that you write has to be really really solid, right?

01:59:57.160 --> 02:00:01.960
[Guest]: And that's why we used to do lengthy type of stories.

02:00:01.960 --> 02:00:06.160
[Guest]: There's a business sense also in it, by the way.

02:00:06.160 --> 02:00:11.560
[Guest]: What happens is that the amount of effort it takes to bring the users

02:00:11.560 --> 02:00:14.560
[Guest]: to consume a piece of content is the same,

02:00:14.560 --> 02:00:17.160
[Guest]: whether it's 10 minutes or 10 hours.

02:00:17.160 --> 02:00:21.160
[Guest]: The amount of effort is the same to bring the user there, right?

02:00:21.160 --> 02:00:23.960
[Guest]: After that, whether they watch it for 10 minutes or 10 hours,

02:00:23.960 --> 02:00:26.760
[Guest]: that depends on your quality of content, right?

02:00:26.760 --> 02:00:31.160
[Guest]: So you're actually better off creating a very high quality content

02:00:31.160 --> 02:00:33.760
[Guest]: and make the same effort to bring the user there

02:00:33.760 --> 02:00:35.560
[Guest]: and then engaging them for a long time, right?

02:00:35.560 --> 02:00:37.760
[Guest]: So it actually makes a lot more business sense

02:00:37.760 --> 02:00:39.160
[Guest]: to create very high quality content

02:00:39.160 --> 02:00:41.160
[Guest]: and keep them engaged for a long long time, right?

02:00:41.160 --> 02:00:47.160
[Guest]: So we used to try, like we had a lot of stories in which

02:00:47.160 --> 02:00:49.760
[Guest]: there were like 100 things, right?

02:00:49.760 --> 02:00:52.360
[Guest]: It used to go up and down, right?

02:00:52.360 --> 02:00:54.760
[Guest]: And it makes business sense also because the deeper you go,

02:00:54.760 --> 02:00:57.160
[Guest]: the more ads I can show and the more money I can make

02:00:57.160 --> 02:00:58.960
[Guest]: probably out of this back in the day, right?

02:00:58.960 --> 02:01:04.960
[Guest]: So yeah, we used to, I mean, it was the trade of the business

02:01:04.960 --> 02:01:07.760
[Guest]: that the more engaging content you make, the more money you make.

02:01:07.760 --> 02:01:09.960
[Guest]: I'm probably not getting the question deeper in terms of

02:01:09.960 --> 02:01:12.760
[Guest]: what do you want to know, like how do you create engaging content, is it?

02:01:12.760 --> 02:01:14.960
[Amit Varma]: Not just how you create engaging content,

02:01:14.960 --> 02:01:19.160
[Amit Varma]: but for example, you spoke about how this girl wrote to you

02:01:19.160 --> 02:01:22.160
[Guest]: and she said, you know, you saved her life.

02:01:22.160 --> 02:01:25.760
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, she engaged with your content at a very deep level.

02:01:25.760 --> 02:01:27.360
[Unknown]: It meant something to her, right?

02:01:27.360 --> 02:01:31.160
[Amit Varma]: At the same time, you could create a content which is like,

02:01:31.160 --> 02:01:33.360
[Amit Varma]: just yesterday I clicked on some stupid headline

02:01:33.360 --> 02:01:37.160
[Amit Varma]: on some stupid viral site, which was to the effect of

02:01:37.160 --> 02:01:39.560
[Amit Varma]: why X did this to Y, right?

02:01:39.560 --> 02:01:41.560
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, it's paginated.

02:01:41.560 --> 02:01:43.960
[Unknown]: You have one picture and one piece of information

02:01:43.960 --> 02:01:47.360
[Unknown]: and you're like clicking 40 times before you get to the point

02:01:47.360 --> 02:01:49.960
[Amit Varma]: and you actually figure out why X did something to Y.

02:01:49.960 --> 02:01:51.960
[Amit Varma]: And to me, that's not engagement.

02:01:51.960 --> 02:01:54.760
[Amit Varma]: You know, you're clicking 40 times, you're showing 40 ads,

02:01:54.760 --> 02:01:56.360
[Amit Varma]: you're making it interesting enough,

02:01:56.360 --> 02:01:59.960
[Amit Varma]: perhaps that the reader stays with you and goes on to the next one,

02:01:59.960 --> 02:02:02.360
[Amit Varma]: but it doesn't mean anything to them emotionally

02:02:02.360 --> 02:02:04.560
[Amit Varma]: or intellectually or in any way at all.

02:02:04.560 --> 02:02:08.360
[Amit Varma]: So they've spent time, but the engagement isn't high, you know?

02:02:08.360 --> 02:02:09.960
[Amit Varma]: And you're monetizing it.

02:02:09.960 --> 02:02:12.560
[Amit Varma]: But then the point is, if you create that deeper engagement,

02:02:12.560 --> 02:02:15.760
[Amit Varma]: like that girl whose life, who wrote that thing to you,

02:02:15.760 --> 02:02:18.360
[Amit Varma]: would have come to your site every day after that, right?

02:02:18.360 --> 02:02:20.960
[Amit Varma]: It would have been a part of her life in that deep way.

02:02:20.960 --> 02:02:23.160
[Amit Varma]: And you can't measure that, right?

02:02:23.160 --> 02:02:25.560
[Amit Varma]: So do you sort of have any thoughts about it?

02:02:25.560 --> 02:02:27.360
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah. So I think you're right.

02:02:27.360 --> 02:02:30.560
[Guest]: Just the fact that at least at that point in time,

02:02:30.560 --> 02:02:34.560
[Guest]: I believe that the fact that the user is actually clicking 40 times

02:02:34.560 --> 02:02:37.360
[Guest]: to find out what it is, they're probably interested enough

02:02:37.360 --> 02:02:38.760
[Guest]: and so they are engaged enough.

02:02:38.760 --> 02:02:41.560
[Guest]: We did have the paginated system at one point in time.

02:02:41.560 --> 02:02:42.960
[Guest]: We removed it later on,

02:02:42.960 --> 02:02:46.560
[Guest]: figuring out that this is a very bad way of keeping the users on the site and all,

02:02:46.560 --> 02:02:50.160
[Guest]: but we did have it for probably a few months or so.

02:02:50.160 --> 02:02:53.560
[Guest]: So, see, my answer to that is,

02:02:53.560 --> 02:02:56.560
[Guest]: first of all, I feel that the fact that she clicked 40 times,

02:02:56.560 --> 02:03:00.760
[Guest]: you see, you can't make anybody click so many times

02:03:00.760 --> 02:03:06.960
[Guest]: without the intent, right, of really finding out what happened, etc.

02:03:06.960 --> 02:03:10.160
[Guest]: And you clicked 40 times,

02:03:10.160 --> 02:03:14.360
[Guest]: or you scrolled it down and then disclosed it.

02:03:14.360 --> 02:03:17.960
[Guest]: It's the same thing packaged in a different way, right?

02:03:17.960 --> 02:03:19.760
[Guest]: It's just that if you click again and again,

02:03:19.760 --> 02:03:23.760
[Guest]: you probably make more money because you can show more ads and whatever, right?

02:03:23.760 --> 02:03:27.760
[Guest]: So I don't agree with the part where you say that is not engagement.

02:03:27.760 --> 02:03:31.160
[Guest]: At least in my mind, to my business, it was engagement.

02:03:31.160 --> 02:03:34.360
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it is engagement, but it's what I would call thin engagement.

02:03:34.360 --> 02:03:39.160
[Guest]: But then that depends on the kind of content we did, right?

02:03:39.160 --> 02:03:44.160
[Guest]: So we didn't necessarily do all content which was thick engagement content.

02:03:44.160 --> 02:03:46.160
[Guest]: I don't think we did.

02:03:46.160 --> 02:03:50.760
[Guest]: And I think that was one of the things that was wrong with WittyFeed.

02:03:50.760 --> 02:03:52.560
[Guest]: So that reminds me of something very interesting.

02:03:52.560 --> 02:03:58.760
[Guest]: When WittyFeed got shut down and it was doing 120 million uniques at that point in time,

02:03:58.760 --> 02:04:02.960
[Guest]: and when we were thinking about what to do next and what was wrong with WittyFeed,

02:04:02.960 --> 02:04:07.960
[Guest]: one of the things that we thought about was that when a product is actually good

02:04:07.960 --> 02:04:13.960
[Guest]: and it really matters to its people and it goes away, people cry for it.

02:04:13.960 --> 02:04:17.560
[Guest]: There will be somebody somewhere out there that it mattered so much

02:04:17.560 --> 02:04:19.760
[Guest]: that they would want it back anyhow, right?

02:04:19.760 --> 02:04:24.160
[Guest]: And they'll miss it, they'll reach out to you, they'll write to you, all of that, right?

02:04:24.160 --> 02:04:28.160
[Guest]: Out of 120 million, nobody did, right?

02:04:28.160 --> 02:04:34.760
[Guest]: And which is why I feel that because of the format or because of the way you can monetize

02:04:34.760 --> 02:04:36.760
[Guest]: online content through ads, etc.,

02:04:36.760 --> 02:04:41.960
[Guest]: unfortunately, most of us ended up building very thin engagement websites.

02:04:41.960 --> 02:04:44.760
[Guest]: You have to bring the user to the website.

02:04:44.760 --> 02:04:48.960
[Guest]: How do you optimize for maximum time spent so that you can show maximum ads

02:04:48.960 --> 02:04:52.160
[Guest]: and so you can make maximum money out of it?

02:04:52.160 --> 02:04:59.360
[Guest]: And which is where, again, from believing that you want to create a positive content site,

02:04:59.360 --> 02:05:02.160
[Guest]: that dilute happens, that you keep telling yourself,

02:05:02.160 --> 02:05:04.560
[Guest]: no, I'm not making positive content anyway,

02:05:04.560 --> 02:05:07.560
[Guest]: but it's not for that deep engagement.

02:05:07.560 --> 02:05:10.960
[Guest]: Now, how do I optimize for maximum revenue and so on and so forth?

02:05:10.960 --> 02:05:13.160
[Guest]: So nobody cried for WittyFeed, right?

02:05:13.160 --> 02:05:14.760
[Guest]: And we wanted to change that this time.

02:05:14.760 --> 02:05:18.160
[Guest]: When we were thinking about a new idea, we said, we won't make it like this.

02:05:18.160 --> 02:05:19.960
[Guest]: Even if we make it for less people this time,

02:05:19.960 --> 02:05:23.360
[Guest]: but this time when I want to do it, I want to do it.

02:05:23.360 --> 02:05:25.760
[Guest]: I want to build a product that really matters to people.

02:05:25.760 --> 02:05:28.560
[Guest]: If it doesn't exist, then maybe someone will cry and say,

02:05:28.560 --> 02:05:31.960
[Guest]: what happened to my life? It was so important to me, basically.

02:05:31.960 --> 02:05:35.160
[Guest]: So I think WittyFeed over time became a thin engagement site only.

02:05:35.160 --> 02:05:38.560
[Guest]: If it was a thick engagement site, it wouldn't have died from Facebook.

02:05:38.560 --> 02:05:39.960
[Amit Varma]: Is what I would say.

02:05:39.960 --> 02:05:43.560
[Amit Varma]: I'm not even making a judgment call in the sense that some things I do,

02:05:43.560 --> 02:05:46.360
[Amit Varma]: I try to be thick engagement. Some things I'm okay with thin engagement.

02:05:46.360 --> 02:05:47.760
[Amit Varma]: There's a value to that as well.

02:05:47.760 --> 02:05:51.360
[Amit Varma]: If you're entertaining people or if you're, you know, satisfying some other need,

02:05:51.360 --> 02:05:54.360
[Amit Varma]: I don't see anything to look down on at all.

02:05:54.360 --> 02:05:57.960
[Amit Varma]: That's also important and people who do it well are doing a great job.

02:05:57.960 --> 02:06:02.560
[Amit Varma]: Tell me also about your approach to building the team that you did.

02:06:02.560 --> 02:06:06.560
[Amit Varma]: Like one really, one insight you shared in one of your talks,

02:06:06.560 --> 02:06:10.960
[Amit Varma]: which impressed me a lot, was where you were sharing the story of a team member,

02:06:10.960 --> 02:06:12.960
[Amit Varma]: who when he came to you for the interview,

02:06:12.960 --> 02:06:15.960
[Amit Varma]: he said, this is my last interview, I won't do it again.

02:06:15.960 --> 02:06:18.160
[Amit Varma]: And you asked, why is that? And he said,

02:06:18.160 --> 02:06:21.360
[Amit Varma]: No, I go everywhere and people ask, how is your English?

02:06:21.360 --> 02:06:23.160
[Amit Varma]: And this is where I get marked.

02:06:23.160 --> 02:06:25.760
[Amit Varma]: And you said, it's not like that here.

02:06:25.760 --> 02:06:28.360
[Amit Varma]: And you hired the person and then at the time you gave the talk,

02:06:28.360 --> 02:06:31.560
[Amit Varma]: you said he was leading one of your teams and all of that.

02:06:31.560 --> 02:06:36.360
[Amit Varma]: And this is something that I totally agree with in the sense that over time,

02:06:36.360 --> 02:06:40.360
[Amit Varma]: I would not have thought this when I was, say, a manager 20 years ago or whatever.

02:06:40.360 --> 02:06:45.560
[Amit Varma]: But over time, I have come to realize that the most important thing is attitude.

02:06:45.560 --> 02:06:47.560
[Amit Varma]: That are you open to learning?

02:06:47.560 --> 02:06:50.760
[Amit Varma]: You know, if you have the humility and you have the openness to learn,

02:06:50.760 --> 02:06:52.360
[Amit Varma]: then the skills don't matter so much.

02:06:52.360 --> 02:06:53.760
[Amit Varma]: You can teach anything.

02:06:53.760 --> 02:06:59.360
[Amit Varma]: So one, tell me a little bit about how you evolved your philosophy towards employees,

02:06:59.360 --> 02:07:03.360
[Amit Varma]: because like another unusual thing you did and Sringda mentions in a book that

02:07:03.360 --> 02:07:05.760
[Amit Varma]: everybody used to live in these two large bungalows.

02:07:05.760 --> 02:07:07.560
[Amit Varma]: So it was like a family.

02:07:07.560 --> 02:07:11.160
[Amit Varma]: The orientation was that it's not just a normal company,

02:07:11.160 --> 02:07:13.160
[Amit Varma]: you're an employee, you come into work,

02:07:13.160 --> 02:07:16.560
[Amit Varma]: attendance is done, you check out your card and you get out of there.

02:07:16.560 --> 02:07:19.360
[Amit Varma]: But you're all actually kind of living together.

02:07:19.360 --> 02:07:22.160
[Amit Varma]: You and your wife are called brother and sister-in-law apparently.

02:07:22.160 --> 02:07:24.160
[Amit Varma]: So where did this philosophy come from?

02:07:24.160 --> 02:07:25.360
[Amit Varma]: That we will do it this way.

02:07:25.360 --> 02:07:27.560
[Amit Varma]: Like, why did you, how did you come up with this?

02:07:27.560 --> 02:07:29.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, what were the roadblocks you faced?

02:07:29.560 --> 02:07:31.360
[Amit Varma]: What were the learnings that you got from it?

02:07:31.360 --> 02:07:35.960
[Amit Varma]: So I'm just very keen to understand your approach towards people and employees.

02:07:35.960 --> 02:07:40.160
[Guest]: Yeah, let me start by completing that story that you mentioned, right?

02:07:40.160 --> 02:07:44.360
[Guest]: So see, again, we were very young and we were hiring, right?

02:07:44.360 --> 02:07:48.760
[Guest]: So by default, you don't get the best of the talent options for you.

02:07:48.760 --> 02:07:49.160
[Guest]: Number one.

02:07:49.160 --> 02:07:55.160
[Guest]: Second, it's very hard to work with people who are older in age,

02:07:55.160 --> 02:08:00.560
[Guest]: because again, it's very hard to establish authority and like all that.

02:08:00.560 --> 02:08:01.760
[Guest]: It doesn't work very well.

02:08:01.760 --> 02:08:02.960
[Guest]: Actually, it does not.

02:08:02.960 --> 02:08:06.160
[Guest]: Over time it changed, but at least when you're little too young,

02:08:06.160 --> 02:08:11.560
[Guest]: who will listen to a 22-year-old boy, basically, right? So we mostly hired freshers at that time.

02:08:11.560 --> 02:08:12.760
[Guest]: How do you judge them?

02:08:12.760 --> 02:08:15.560
[Guest]: How do you figure out if this guy is a good guy or not, right?

02:08:15.560 --> 02:08:16.960
[Guest]: So then attitude is the only skill.

02:08:16.960 --> 02:08:19.760
[Guest]: You can't do much anyway.

02:08:19.760 --> 02:08:23.760
[Guest]: And we ended up building a policy of hiring only freshers.

02:08:23.760 --> 02:08:27.960
[Guest]: Let's work with only freshers.

02:08:27.960 --> 02:08:29.560
[Guest]: One, we get them at a low price.

02:08:29.560 --> 02:08:34.960
[Guest]: And second, we can hire them on their attitude.

02:08:34.960 --> 02:08:36.360
[Guest]: We'll teach them the skill, basically.

02:08:36.360 --> 02:08:39.760
[Guest]: Always believed that skill can be taught and attitude can't be.

02:08:39.760 --> 02:08:42.160
[Guest]: So how do you judge?

02:08:42.160 --> 02:08:48.760
[Guest]: So we, and again, when you're young and like I believed in hustling so much.

02:08:48.760 --> 02:08:52.160
[Guest]: I still do, but a little too much at that point in time.

02:08:52.160 --> 02:08:59.560
[Guest]: So we used to actually judge at two things and this was Shashank's discovery.

02:08:59.560 --> 02:09:02.360
[Guest]: He's always been better among the three,

02:09:02.360 --> 02:09:08.760
[Guest]: the best among three of us in terms of finding out the right ways to interview people, etc.

02:09:08.760 --> 02:09:10.760
[Guest]: Not that I'm very proud of what we used to do.

02:09:10.760 --> 02:09:17.560
[Guest]: We wanted to see how he reacts when he's put out of comfort zone.

02:09:17.560 --> 02:09:20.760
[Guest]: And second, is he never giving up attitude or not?

02:09:20.760 --> 02:09:24.160
[Guest]: If he's a person who gives up, he won't be able to do it because he has to learn new things.

02:09:24.160 --> 02:09:26.760
[Guest]: It's a start-up, anyway, he'll have to work extra hard.

02:09:26.760 --> 02:09:29.960
[Guest]: People used to work for 2-3 days at night at that time.

02:09:29.960 --> 02:09:33.560
[Guest]: Again, that is how companies are built in the initial days.

02:09:33.560 --> 02:09:38.360
[Guest]: So what we used to do, we used to ask people to do push-ups.

02:09:38.360 --> 02:09:41.960
[Guest]: Nobody would expect to do push-ups in the interview.

02:09:41.960 --> 02:09:45.760
[Guest]: Mostly boys and girls were also asked to do something like this, something weird.

02:09:45.760 --> 02:09:50.560
[Guest]: And this was Sunil's name, it started with Sunil.

02:09:50.560 --> 02:09:54.360
[Guest]: So Sunil came and he said,

02:09:54.360 --> 02:10:01.360
[Guest]: this is my last interview, I'm done, I've come from the village, I've tried a lot.

02:10:01.360 --> 02:10:03.560
[Guest]: But everyone says, what do you know already?

02:10:03.560 --> 02:10:06.360
[Guest]: And they ask in English, what else do you know?

02:10:06.360 --> 02:10:09.360
[Guest]: Nobody is ready to teach, I'm ready to learn, but nobody is ready to teach.

02:10:09.360 --> 02:10:13.760
[Guest]: So now I'll go to my village, I'll do farming, I'm done here.

02:10:13.760 --> 02:10:16.760
[Guest]: Shashank was the interviewer, by the way.

02:10:16.760 --> 02:10:20.360
[Guest]: So Shashank said, okay, what can you do?

02:10:20.360 --> 02:10:23.760
[Guest]: I said, sir, I'll do whatever you say for this job.

02:10:23.760 --> 02:10:25.960
[Guest]: So I think he did one of the two things.

02:10:25.960 --> 02:10:28.560
[Guest]: Either he was asked to do push-ups at that time,

02:10:28.560 --> 02:10:30.960
[Guest]: or another thing that Shashank used to do,

02:10:30.960 --> 02:10:33.960
[Guest]: our office was on the 6th floor.

02:10:33.960 --> 02:10:37.960
[Guest]: So he would ask people to do 6 floors up and down through stairs,

02:10:37.960 --> 02:10:40.360
[Guest]: some 4-5 times, something like that, basically.

02:10:40.360 --> 02:10:43.960
[Guest]: Something that is basically undoable, essentially, right?

02:10:43.960 --> 02:10:46.760
[Guest]: And if you're ready to do that, the idea was that I know.

02:10:46.760 --> 02:10:49.760
[Guest]: It was basically an army-type style of hiring.

02:10:49.760 --> 02:10:53.760
[Guest]: It was a roadie-type interview, that if you do something that is unthinkable,

02:10:53.760 --> 02:10:56.760
[Guest]: then at least you don't have an attitude problem.

02:10:56.760 --> 02:10:59.760
[Guest]: The skill is on us whether we can teach or not.

02:10:59.760 --> 02:11:02.360
[Guest]: So we told Sunil something like that, and he did it.

02:11:02.360 --> 02:11:06.760
[Guest]: And it was crazy, he turned out to be an amazing hire, actually.

02:11:06.760 --> 02:11:08.760
[Guest]: And he was with us for the longest time,

02:11:08.760 --> 02:11:12.760
[Guest]: and I'm so proud to tell you that he runs his own company today in Indore.

02:11:12.760 --> 02:11:16.760
[Guest]: He runs his own IT company, has some employees,

02:11:16.760 --> 02:11:18.760
[Guest]: some 40-50 people, I think.

02:11:18.760 --> 02:11:21.760
[Guest]: And he's doing phenomenal, actually.

02:11:21.760 --> 02:11:25.760
[Guest]: That guy, if his interview didn't go well that day, he would have left.

02:11:25.760 --> 02:11:31.760
[Guest]: So much talent which goes, you know, unutilized because nobody gave them a chance, right?

02:11:31.760 --> 02:11:37.760
[Guest]: And plus, I think language cannot be a judge.

02:11:37.760 --> 02:11:41.760
[Guest]: Language cannot be a parameter to judge somebody's talent, basically.

02:11:41.760 --> 02:11:44.760
[Guest]: That's the most poor way of, very lazy way of finding out

02:11:44.760 --> 02:11:47.760
[Guest]: how talented you are or not, right?

02:11:47.760 --> 02:11:50.760
[Guest]: So then that interview turned into a thing.

02:11:50.760 --> 02:11:52.760
[Guest]: It was a roadie-style interview.

02:11:52.760 --> 02:11:55.760
[Guest]: Of course, we would ask simple questions, all that stuff also.

02:11:55.760 --> 02:11:58.760
[Guest]: But then, by default, there were push-ups in every interview.

02:11:58.760 --> 02:11:59.760
[Guest]: It was something weird.

02:11:59.760 --> 02:12:02.760
[Guest]: Then Shashank did something weird.

02:12:02.760 --> 02:12:05.760
[Guest]: We had a golf strip in the office.

02:12:05.760 --> 02:12:07.760
[Guest]: So basically, he used to say,

02:12:07.760 --> 02:12:10.760
[Guest]: you have to put it in 10 times in a row or 5 times in a row.

02:12:10.760 --> 02:12:12.760
[Guest]: The ball should go into the hole.

02:12:12.760 --> 02:12:14.760
[Guest]: If you miss once in the middle, start again.

02:12:14.760 --> 02:12:18.760
[Guest]: Now, it would take hours, but people used to do that.

02:12:18.760 --> 02:12:19.760
[Guest]: People used to do that,

02:12:19.760 --> 02:12:22.760
[Guest]: that they would continuously put it in 5 times.

02:12:22.760 --> 02:12:23.760
[Guest]: And that is when you know,

02:12:23.760 --> 02:12:26.760
[Guest]: if a person gives something to him, he will put his life on the line.

02:12:26.760 --> 02:12:27.760
[Guest]: This is confirmed.

02:12:27.760 --> 02:12:28.760
[Guest]: Whether it will happen or not, that is later,

02:12:28.760 --> 02:12:29.760
[Guest]: but he will put his life on the line.

02:12:29.760 --> 02:12:30.760
[Guest]: This is confirmed.

02:12:30.760 --> 02:12:31.760
[Guest]: The person will never give up.

02:12:31.760 --> 02:12:35.760
[Guest]: And I think which is why we ended up building an army of, you know,

02:12:35.760 --> 02:12:36.760
[Guest]: it was generally an army,

02:12:36.760 --> 02:12:40.760
[Guest]: an army of people who were just not ready to give up on anything.

02:12:40.760 --> 02:12:44.760
[Guest]: And that is why we were able to build a company against all odds.

02:12:44.760 --> 02:12:49.760
[Guest]: So that is how we built it up.

02:12:49.760 --> 02:12:51.760
[Amit Varma]: One, this sounds like a great way of electing for attitude,

02:12:51.760 --> 02:12:53.760
[Amit Varma]: but it's also a little, you know,

02:12:53.760 --> 02:12:55.760
[Amit Varma]: like you said that looking back,

02:12:55.760 --> 02:12:57.760
[Guest]: I would not have done this now or something.

02:12:57.760 --> 02:12:58.760
[Guest]: So why is that?

02:12:58.760 --> 02:13:00.760
[Guest]: What are the misgivings you have about this?

02:13:00.760 --> 02:13:05.760
[Guest]: This is very masculine in nature, I think, right?

02:13:05.760 --> 02:13:07.760
[Guest]: And again,

02:13:07.760 --> 02:13:17.760
[Guest]: it's not like 100% correct way of basically finding it out.

02:13:17.760 --> 02:13:20.760
[Guest]: We still look for never giving up attitude.

02:13:20.760 --> 02:13:21.760
[Guest]: We still look for,

02:13:21.760 --> 02:13:23.760
[Guest]: I think even today in the new company that we're building,

02:13:23.760 --> 02:13:26.760
[Guest]: we still look for similar stuff that we test for.

02:13:26.760 --> 02:13:31.760
[Guest]: The thing that has changed is that we do look for skill fit also,

02:13:31.760 --> 02:13:35.760
[Guest]: but I think we still look for culture fit and never giving up attitude.

02:13:35.760 --> 02:13:39.760
[Guest]: And that are you, do you have a learning attitude?

02:13:39.760 --> 02:13:45.760
[Guest]: There are different type of questions that we ask now to understand that,

02:13:45.760 --> 02:13:48.760
[Guest]: but we do still look for the same skill.

02:13:48.760 --> 02:13:50.760
[Guest]: I think that we used to look back in the day.

02:13:50.760 --> 02:13:52.760
[Amit Varma]: And these days in corporate circles,

02:13:52.760 --> 02:13:54.760
[Amit Varma]: like where I have been a long time back,

