[Guest]: Mujhe lagta hai ki yaar as an entrepreneur, anyways hum materialistic cheezein toh deni

02:34:30.480 --> 02:34:35.520
[Guest]: paate hain un logon ko kuch zyada, right, kyuki humesai tangi rehti hain, paise ki toh.

02:34:35.520 --> 02:34:39.840
[Guest]: So you're always underpaid, you're always short on, you know, there's something or the

02:34:39.840 --> 02:34:44.920
[Guest]: other going wrong in your company and so you're always under stress, all of that stuff, right.

02:34:44.920 --> 02:34:48.600
[Guest]: At least aap unko samay de sakte hoon.

02:34:48.600 --> 02:34:50.760
[Guest]: And that's the most important gift that you can give them, right.

02:34:50.760 --> 02:34:53.640
[Guest]: So you sit down, listen to them.

02:34:53.640 --> 02:35:00.040
[Guest]: And also, I try my best to give as much time as I can give to my wife, my family, my parents

02:35:00.040 --> 02:35:01.800
[Guest]: live with me.

02:35:01.800 --> 02:35:07.360
[Guest]: That's also a condition I put on them ki, I just will not live without you guys and

02:35:07.360 --> 02:35:12.040
[Guest]: I hope they continue to live with me for the rest of their days or my days, whatever.

02:35:12.040 --> 02:35:16.200
[Guest]: So yeah, I do that, spending time with family a lot more.

02:35:16.200 --> 02:35:20.400
[Amit Varma]: That's also a lovely, that's such a lovely thought of, you know, giving time to your

02:35:20.400 --> 02:35:25.680
[Amit Varma]: family because just thinking aloud, you know, when people are gone and you miss them, you

02:35:25.680 --> 02:35:29.120
[Guest]: never remember the things they gave you, you remember the time you spent with them.

02:35:29.120 --> 02:35:34.720
[Guest]: Again, meri wife ka bahut influence raha hai isme.

02:35:34.720 --> 02:35:38.760
[Guest]: And I probably found her and fell in love with her and we married because of those similarities

02:35:38.760 --> 02:35:44.960
[Guest]: and thoughts also that both of us are far, far away from metalistic stuff, basically.

02:35:44.960 --> 02:35:49.800
[Guest]: Toh humein na jyada mehenge kapde, na jyada mehengi cheeze, na badi gadi, na bada ghar

02:35:49.800 --> 02:35:52.480
[Guest]: yeh sab bilkul bhi samajh nahi aata hai, thankfully.

02:35:52.480 --> 02:35:53.960
[Guest]: And we both are alike that way, right.

02:35:53.960 --> 02:36:02.880
[Guest]: So matlab, my way of showing you my love will never be about giving you costly, like very

02:36:02.880 --> 02:36:07.680
[Guest]: expensive gifts, mujhe toh, I feel actually very bad when even somebody gives it to me

02:36:07.680 --> 02:36:14.640
[Guest]: and like, I can't do it, mere bas ki baat nahi hai, I will, I will sit down with you,

02:36:14.640 --> 02:36:17.300
[Guest]: I will be there when you need me.

02:36:17.300 --> 02:36:22.000
[Guest]: If you are feeling down, I'm going to sit down with you and have like a three hour long

02:36:22.000 --> 02:36:25.760
[Guest]: conversation in a row and I don't mind doing it, mera koi bahut important meeting hoga

02:36:25.760 --> 02:36:30.720
[Guest]: main miss kar dunga usko, if I need to sit with you and like, spend time with you.

02:36:30.720 --> 02:36:34.840
[Guest]: But mere se yeh nahi hoga ki aapke birthday pe main 50,000 rupee ka gift dera hun, mere

02:36:34.840 --> 02:36:39.760
[Guest]: bas ki baat, 5000 kai dena muskil kaam hai, metalistic cheeze nahi hoti hai mujhe, basically,

02:36:39.760 --> 02:36:43.080
[Guest]: it's very, very hard for me to do that.

02:36:43.080 --> 02:36:47.480
[Amit Varma]: You've also, you know, mentioned at different times, how there have been so many ups and

02:36:47.480 --> 02:36:52.960
[Amit Varma]: downs, ebbs and flows in your time, you know, and especially the way Witty Feed ended, like

02:36:52.960 --> 02:36:57.080
[Amit Varma]: if it happened to something I built, I think it would have been so incredibly traumatic

02:36:57.080 --> 02:37:01.640
[Amit Varma]: ki mujhe pata nahi ki motivation kaise aati mujhe ki continue karo, you know, it would

02:37:01.640 --> 02:37:03.280
[Amit Varma]: have felt like the end of the world.

02:37:03.280 --> 02:37:07.480
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about that phase, if you want to talk about any earlier downs,

02:37:07.480 --> 02:37:13.480
[Amit Varma]: if you think they are relevant, but you know, when it was ending, you know, how did it happen?

02:37:13.480 --> 02:37:15.000
[Amit Varma]: How did you get through it?

02:37:15.000 --> 02:37:20.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, like, wo poora process kaisa tha ki aap wahan se aap phir continue karke yahan

02:37:20.240 --> 02:37:21.240
[Amit Varma]: tak hai?

02:37:21.240 --> 02:37:29.360
[Guest]: So, so yeah, I mean, there have been multiple instances, even Witty Feed banane se pehle

02:37:29.360 --> 02:37:36.880
[Guest]: bhi aur banate time bhi bhot saari time aisa hua, sab hua, but for without a doubt, this

02:37:36.880 --> 02:37:42.040
[Guest]: experience of losing Witty Feed entirely, after building it at such a large scale was

02:37:42.040 --> 02:37:45.840
[Guest]: the biggest one in the entire thing, right?

02:37:45.840 --> 02:37:47.000
[Guest]: And it was very traumatic.

02:37:47.000 --> 02:37:48.640
[Guest]: It was very depressing.

02:37:48.640 --> 02:37:52.800
[Guest]: All three of us, we were diagnosed clinically depressed after that.

02:37:52.800 --> 02:37:56.960
[Guest]: Teen saal se hum log therapy kari rahe hain, jab bhi jaisa hi figure out kiya and then

02:37:56.960 --> 02:38:00.840
[Guest]: we started, tab se hum, all of us are on therapy.

02:38:00.840 --> 02:38:05.440
[Guest]: We did some medication also in between, we had to take some medication also to come out

02:38:05.440 --> 02:38:08.480
[Guest]: of it and all.

02:38:08.480 --> 02:38:16.360
[Guest]: See it's the right analogy and I'm not exaggerating when I say it is that you raise a baby and

02:38:16.360 --> 02:38:20.480
[Guest]: you lose it when they are eight year old.

02:38:20.480 --> 02:38:23.600
[Guest]: That's what it was.

02:38:23.600 --> 02:38:30.400
[Guest]: Now couple it with the fact that this is the only identity that you have of yourself out

02:38:30.400 --> 02:38:31.880
[Guest]: there to the world.

02:38:31.880 --> 02:38:37.480
[Guest]: You started it in college and that's the only way people know you and there's so much, there

02:38:37.480 --> 02:38:39.720
[Guest]: was so much fucking fame around it.

02:38:39.720 --> 02:38:45.080
[Guest]: Matlab yaar, we were at one point in time, the poster boys of the tier two ecosystem,

02:38:45.080 --> 02:38:46.880
[Guest]: startup ecosystem in the country.

02:38:46.880 --> 02:38:54.480
[Guest]: There was ET writing about us, like everywhere we were being called to every conference.

02:38:54.480 --> 02:38:58.840
[Guest]: We were sort of a mini celebrity in our own right at that point in time, right?

02:38:58.840 --> 02:39:03.080
[Guest]: And then all of a sudden it all goes away.

02:39:03.080 --> 02:39:08.680
[Guest]: So entrepreneurs do one thing, which is that, and it's a big mistake we all make, which

02:39:08.680 --> 02:39:12.720
[Guest]: is that we, not entrepreneurs, I think all people who are passionate about building anything

02:39:12.720 --> 02:39:20.640
[Guest]: they do, this is that they associate their idea of self with the work that they do, right?

02:39:20.640 --> 02:39:21.920
[Guest]: And we did that of course.

02:39:21.920 --> 02:39:27.040
[Guest]: Toh hamara toh identity hi witty feed, witty feed founders, witty feed founders and all

02:39:27.040 --> 02:39:29.680
[Guest]: of a sudden that didn't exist.

02:39:29.680 --> 02:39:33.080
[Guest]: So the very first thing we had was identity crisis.

02:39:33.080 --> 02:39:34.080
[Guest]: Who are we?

02:39:34.080 --> 02:39:38.200
[Guest]: Witty feed hi nahi hai, hum witty feed ke founders hai, toh hum kaun hai?

02:39:38.200 --> 02:39:46.040
[Guest]: And we had no idea, kyuki itni, itna, see, you need to understand Amit that the intensity

02:39:46.040 --> 02:39:52.360
[Guest]: of, the intensity with which you have to build when you're building a company, the entrepreneurial

02:39:52.360 --> 02:39:55.780
[Guest]: experience people don't realize that that's so dense.

02:39:55.780 --> 02:40:01.280
[Guest]: The density of experiences when you are building a company is so very high that aapko ek baar

02:40:01.280 --> 02:40:06.700
[Guest]: bhi aise sochane ka time nahi milta ki yaar yeh sab, you don't really have time to process

02:40:06.700 --> 02:40:07.700
[Guest]: any of this, right?

02:40:07.700 --> 02:40:11.440
[Guest]: And you're having the highest level of density of experiences in your life, right?

02:40:11.440 --> 02:40:14.160
[Guest]: And so the intensity is very, very high.

02:40:14.160 --> 02:40:16.360
[Guest]: And all of a sudden all of it goes away.

02:40:16.360 --> 02:40:19.480
[Guest]: So you don't know who you are, essentially.

02:40:19.480 --> 02:40:22.560
[Guest]: And we were certain something of a certain level.

02:40:22.560 --> 02:40:27.000
[Guest]: Phir hum Indore mein the, toh waha toh hume feeling of a king aati thi, kyuki hum waha

02:40:27.000 --> 02:40:31.480
[Guest]: ke toh sabse badi company the, toh, which is, which is why we were in Indore actually

02:40:31.480 --> 02:40:32.480
[Guest]: in the first place.

02:40:32.480 --> 02:40:36.240
[Guest]: We, we went there because we said ki yaar saare bade sehro mein itne start-ups huma

02:40:36.240 --> 02:40:40.360
[Guest]: toh hum kho jaayenge, can we go to a city where we can build the entire ecosystem and

02:40:40.360 --> 02:40:42.000
[Guest]: be the kings of our own world?

02:40:42.000 --> 02:40:46.000
[Guest]: And we were, and all of a sudden you are a nobody.

02:40:46.000 --> 02:40:53.680
[Guest]: So I think it started with denial, the typical first phase of any grief cycle, I think.

02:40:53.680 --> 02:40:57.080
[Guest]: Toh we said, arey, arey aise kaise ho sakta hai, we are witty feet, we'll fight it out,

02:40:57.080 --> 02:41:02.100
[Guest]: hum Facebook se ladenge hai, we'll do legal battle, yeh wo sab, humne kiya bhi, we hired

02:41:02.100 --> 02:41:05.880
[Guest]: the best of the lawyers and we wrote back and all that stuff.

02:41:05.880 --> 02:41:12.000
[Guest]: Do teen maine mein we lost all the money that we had accued in terms of profits.

02:41:12.000 --> 02:41:14.360
[Guest]: We even took loans.

02:41:14.360 --> 02:41:17.080
[Guest]: You make a lot of foolish decisions in times like this, right?

02:41:17.080 --> 02:41:22.880
[Guest]: So kyunki humari books bahut strong thi, toh har bank ne humein unsecured, pre-approved

02:41:22.880 --> 02:41:29.920
[Guest]: loan 25 lakh rupee ke dedi hai, humne le liye, some 13-14 banks se yeh saare loans le liye

02:41:29.920 --> 02:41:30.920
[Guest]: bhi.

02:41:30.920 --> 02:41:32.840
[Guest]: Jo koi basically dera tha, wo sabse le liye.

02:41:32.840 --> 02:41:35.440
[Guest]: Teen, chaar crore rupee ke gareeb loans ho gaye.

02:41:35.440 --> 02:41:39.480
[Guest]: People who used to have a couple of million dollars in their account as their profits

02:41:39.480 --> 02:41:46.400
[Guest]: for now at minus three, three and a half crores, essentially, and with no idea of what to do.

02:41:46.400 --> 02:41:50.620
[Guest]: It came to a point where we would probably have to shut down the company, right?

02:41:50.620 --> 02:41:56.680
[Guest]: And then all that story of how employees bailed us out, which is why, which was the biggest

02:41:56.680 --> 02:41:57.680
[Guest]: validation of that.

02:41:57.680 --> 02:42:02.080
[Guest]: We probably built it the right way and also we made a pitch, we did a town hall basically

02:42:02.080 --> 02:42:08.220
[Guest]: and we made a pitch to 90 employees that we don't know what to do from here.

02:42:08.220 --> 02:42:11.160
[Guest]: But if you believe in us, you stay with us.

02:42:11.160 --> 02:42:13.000
[Guest]: We will figure it out what to do from here.

02:42:13.000 --> 02:42:16.480
[Guest]: 6 maine ki bet lo hum pe, but humaar pe paise nahi aapko dene ke liye.

02:42:16.480 --> 02:42:21.640
[Guest]: You take 25% of your salary, the rest 75%, we will double it and we'll give you as an

02:42:21.640 --> 02:42:22.640
[Guest]: equity in the company.

02:42:22.640 --> 02:42:24.480
[Guest]: So you become our angel investor.

02:42:24.480 --> 02:42:29.400
[Guest]: And this is a pitch to employees in Indore back in 2018 when these things were not so

02:42:29.400 --> 02:42:31.600
[Guest]: common, right?

02:42:31.600 --> 02:42:35.920
[Guest]: And this was all from that idea of ki yaar, this can't be the climax of my story.

02:42:35.920 --> 02:42:42.760
[Guest]: Well, again, that attitude of ki yaar, aise kaise ho sakta hai, meri story, meri picture

02:42:42.760 --> 02:42:45.720
[Guest]: yahaan khatam nahi ho rahi hai basically.

02:42:45.720 --> 02:42:50.160
[Guest]: Out of 90, 54 people decided to stay back.

02:42:50.160 --> 02:42:55.080
[Guest]: And even jo jaare the, us din, wo bechare majboori mein jaare the, they were mostly

02:42:55.080 --> 02:42:58.840
[Guest]: the sole earning members in their families and all that stuff, right?

02:42:58.840 --> 02:43:04.320
[Guest]: And it was, it was probably the most emotional or second most emotional day of my life.

02:43:04.320 --> 02:43:09.480
[Guest]: So much crying and, you know, you don't know what to do with these people who are leaving,

02:43:09.480 --> 02:43:14.880
[Guest]: you know why they're leaving and people who are staying, you don't know, like there's

02:43:14.880 --> 02:43:17.000
[Guest]: so much weight on your shoulders.

02:43:17.000 --> 02:43:21.000
[Guest]: Chogan log bhot hote hain, unki 25% salary bhi bhot hoti hai.

02:43:21.000 --> 02:43:25.040
[Guest]: Initially humne aise suchta ki 4-5 log rukh jayenge, toh depressed nahi honge.

02:43:25.040 --> 02:43:28.160
[Guest]: We will have a reason to come back to office, we'll do something and all.

02:43:28.160 --> 02:43:30.400
[Guest]: 55 logon ke saath, chogan logon ke saath, ab kya karoge basically?

02:43:30.400 --> 02:43:33.520
[Guest]: There's a lot of people and I don't have a product, I don't even have an idea what

02:43:33.520 --> 02:43:35.520
[Guest]: to do from here, basically.

02:43:35.520 --> 02:43:38.480
[Guest]: Toh, but yeah, I think that is what saved the company.

02:43:38.480 --> 02:43:43.280
[Guest]: Even those who stayed, they were like, sir, aap chhodo, 25% chhodo, meri paas ek lakh

02:43:43.280 --> 02:43:47.000
[Guest]: rupee ki saving hai, meri paas do lakh rupee ki saving hai, main deta hu, hum marne nahi

02:43:47.000 --> 02:43:48.000
[Guest]: denge company ko.

02:43:48.000 --> 02:43:57.360
[Guest]: One of our guys, I remember this very distinctly, that he had a kid very recently, malar us

02:43:57.360 --> 02:44:03.480
[Guest]: time pe and he said, sir, theek hai, hum inna ek kaam karenge, yeh meri salary ka jo

02:44:03.480 --> 02:44:04.480
[Guest]: hai.

02:44:04.480 --> 02:44:09.960
[Guest]: And, yaar, yeh Indore ki salaries kya hongi, between, malar yeh 20,000 se start hoke, 60-70

02:44:09.960 --> 02:44:13.640
[Guest]: thousand upar mein, basically, uske beech ki salaries hai, yeh saari.

02:44:13.640 --> 02:44:19.600
[Guest]: Toh, said ki, sir, main ek kaam karenge, hum dood kebal mere bachche ke liye manga lenge

02:44:19.600 --> 02:44:23.760
[Guest]: ghar mein, baaki hum cut down kar denge, aur aisi ek doon cheeze usne boli, and like, but

02:44:23.760 --> 02:44:29.520
[Guest]: I will stay with you, no matter what, main 25% pe rukunga aapke saath.

02:44:29.520 --> 02:44:33.440
[Guest]: I mean, what do you, like, kaise, it was such.

02:44:33.440 --> 02:44:40.920
[Guest]: A huge weight, ki yaar, inn logon ke saath main galat hone nahi de sakta kabhi bhi, right?

02:44:40.920 --> 02:44:46.800
[Guest]: And I think that became one of the reasons why we survived.

02:44:46.800 --> 02:44:53.560
[Guest]: Because it changes the entire vibe, the energy, tells you ki boss, pachpan log aise hain jo

02:44:53.560 --> 02:44:56.640
[Guest]: aap pe aap se zyada barusa karte hain.

02:44:56.640 --> 02:45:00.360
[Guest]: They believe ki you will not fail, you will do something with your life, toh ab toh karna

02:45:00.360 --> 02:45:04.840
[Guest]: toh padhega hi basically yahan se, right, so that, wo sab hua, chalo phir jaise-daise

02:45:04.840 --> 02:45:10.800
[Guest]: karke stage ki company mani hai, and one more thing, I am very proud to tell you ki pichle

02:45:10.800 --> 02:45:15.880
[Guest]: saal June mein humne un saare employees ko exit diya, as they made some 2x of their investment,

02:45:15.880 --> 02:45:16.880
[Guest]: etc.

02:45:16.880 --> 02:45:22.480
[Guest]: Main kisi, jab Unicorn bhi banega, aur humare investors 50x bhi banayenge, I don't think

02:45:22.480 --> 02:45:27.360
[Guest]: it will ever give me more satisfaction than giving exit to those people, right?

02:45:27.360 --> 02:45:34.720
[Guest]: Because hua aise boj utar gaya ki yaar, you know, the grief continued with us I think

02:45:34.720 --> 02:45:35.720
[Guest]: throughout.

02:45:35.720 --> 02:45:42.160
[Guest]: Bohot saara unprocessed hai abhi bhi, to be honest, you know, December last year, we were

02:45:42.160 --> 02:45:46.400
[Guest]: trying to raise a round, last to last year, December 2020, we were trying to raise a series

02:45:46.400 --> 02:45:50.480
[Guest]: a round, stage mein us time chal raha tha, sab sahi chal raha tha, humne monetize kiya

02:45:50.480 --> 02:45:55.200
[Guest]: nahi tha us time tha, people, every VC that we spoke to said ki Bharat doesn't pay, subscription

02:45:55.200 --> 02:45:59.000
[Guest]: chalega hi nahi, possible hi nahi hai, we were just not able to raise.

02:45:59.000 --> 02:46:06.200
[Guest]: Humare paas karib 5-6 maine ka paisa bacha tha, and hota gaya na ki 2-4-5-10 log jab

02:46:06.200 --> 02:46:11.360
[Guest]: same baat bolte hain, to ek point pe baad it gets into your head, it starts to impact

02:46:11.360 --> 02:46:12.360
[Guest]: you, right?

02:46:12.360 --> 02:46:19.360
[Guest]: And you start to believe ki yaar, itne smart log, itni baate bol rahe hain, to yaar, kuch

02:46:19.360 --> 02:46:24.240
[Guest]: sahi bol rahe honge, you know, they know, they do this for their daily job, to inko

02:46:24.240 --> 02:46:30.200
[Guest]: kuch aata hi hoga, and you start to doubt yourself, and that is when all the shit that

02:46:30.200 --> 02:46:32.320
[Guest]: you had buried, it all comes out, right?

02:46:32.320 --> 02:46:42.400
[Guest]: So hua gaya ki, mere dimaag mein ghus gaya ki yaar, we are, I am not a good entrepreneur,

02:46:42.400 --> 02:46:47.680
[Guest]: witty feed band hua, everybody said ki yaar, us samayal, there were a lot of people, people,

02:46:47.680 --> 02:46:49.120
[Guest]: there are all kinds of people, right?

02:46:49.120 --> 02:46:52.880
[Guest]: So there were a lot of people who said ki, arey toh humein toh pata hi tha, hai toh fluke

02:46:52.880 --> 02:46:56.600
[Guest]: hai, hum toh pehli bolte the, kuch boat hoga, kuch ghochi hoga, when Facebook does something,

02:46:56.600 --> 02:47:00.840
[Guest]: everybody say that Facebook probably, facebook aise kyun hi karega, chote wale ki kisi ko

02:47:00.840 --> 02:47:05.520
[Guest]: nahi, nobody would say ki, my story is the right story, until unless I prove it at some

02:47:05.520 --> 02:47:06.520
[Guest]: point, right?

02:47:06.520 --> 02:47:10.920
[Guest]: Everybody would say ki, Facebook aise kisi ka kyun band karega, inkar kiya, toh I was

02:47:10.920 --> 02:47:12.560
[Amit Varma]: the culprit basically in everybody's mind.

02:47:12.560 --> 02:47:15.720
[Amit Varma]: Kiya ki, lekin by the way, why did they shut you down?

02:47:15.720 --> 02:47:18.760
[Guest]: Yeah, I'll probably come to that as a follow up, right?

02:47:18.760 --> 02:47:25.520
[Guest]: So everybody thought ki yaar yeh toh, and some people said it was a fluke, anyways dekho

02:47:25.520 --> 02:47:27.160
[Guest]: hum toh bolte the, inkar kuch nahi hoga.

02:47:27.160 --> 02:47:32.040
[Guest]: Ab jab wo 6 maine ka paisa bacha aur paisa raise nahi ho para tha, toh dimaag mein kya

02:47:32.040 --> 02:47:37.080
[Guest]: thoughts aane lage, ki yaar toh stage bhi band hoega, and then everybody who said so will

02:47:37.080 --> 02:47:40.520
[Guest]: basically be right, and they'll say humne toh bola hi tha, yeh inko toh aata hi nahi

02:47:40.520 --> 02:47:41.520
[Guest]: hai kuch basically, right?

02:47:41.520 --> 02:47:46.160
[Guest]: And it got into my head, it got into my head so much, aise poore poore din, dupair mein

02:47:46.160 --> 02:47:50.720
[Guest]: 2 baje, 3 baje, neech aise ghoomta rahata tha garden mein, like a crazy guy who doesn't

02:47:50.720 --> 02:47:54.120
[Guest]: know, main kuch samajh mein aata tha kya soch raha hoon, aur saare din main ek se sochta

02:47:54.120 --> 02:47:58.320
[Guest]: rahata tha ki yaar accha toh band hoegi, yeh toh confirm ho gaya hai, mujhe kaun se job

02:47:58.320 --> 02:47:59.320
[Guest]: milegi?

02:47:59.320 --> 02:48:00.880
[Guest]: Who will give me a job?

02:48:00.880 --> 02:48:07.680
[Guest]: The sense of worthlessness for self was so high, that I used to feel ki, yaar mujhe nokri

02:48:07.680 --> 02:48:08.680
[Guest]: kaun dega?

02:48:08.680 --> 02:48:12.600
[Guest]: Aur main kya nokri karunga, mujhe toh kuch aati hi nahi hai, mujhe kaun se cheez, main

02:48:12.600 --> 02:48:15.040
[Guest]: expert kis cheez ka hoon, main se kuch bhi nahi aata hai.

02:48:15.040 --> 02:48:18.960
[Guest]: You are basically jack of all trades as an entrepreneur and you are master of none, toh

02:48:18.960 --> 02:48:23.720
[Guest]: tumhe koi PM ki job bhi tumhe koi entry level milegi, milegi toh product manager ki, tumhe

02:48:23.720 --> 02:48:29.120
[Guest]: koi developer tum ho nahi, CEO tumhe koi banayega nahi, toh tum what will you do basically?

02:48:29.120 --> 02:48:36.680
[Guest]: I just couldn't think of a single job that I could get and poore din main yeh sochta

02:48:36.680 --> 02:48:41.880
[Guest]: rahata tha, poore din, all the unprocessed grief of witty feed not making it came out

02:48:41.880 --> 02:48:44.280
[Guest]: basically.

02:48:44.280 --> 02:48:50.040
[Guest]: And it took a lot to come out of this, thankfully we shifted from Indore to Noida around that

02:48:50.040 --> 02:48:54.560
[Guest]: time, 1st of April last year I shifted here, changed the energy, changed the vibe and we

02:48:54.560 --> 02:49:01.320
[Guest]: launched subscriptions 10th of April, thank god it worked out and that gave me the energy

02:49:01.320 --> 02:49:07.280
[Guest]: to be able to raise the round in next, within next 2 months I raised some million dollars

02:49:07.280 --> 02:49:12.120
[Guest]: or so and then we survived and like it all is going great now and all, touch wood.

02:49:12.120 --> 02:49:19.080
[Guest]: Point is yaar, aise like you said ki aisa aisa where do you even bring the motivation

02:49:19.080 --> 02:49:21.560
[Guest]: from etc.

02:49:21.560 --> 02:49:27.520
[Guest]: The truth is that I am not always motivated, truth is that there are times when I feel

02:49:27.520 --> 02:49:34.120
[Guest]: like worthless piece of shit, there are times when I feel like giving up and I am like what

02:49:34.120 --> 02:49:40.080
[Guest]: the hell, why don't I even do a job itself and all right.

02:49:40.080 --> 02:49:49.280
[Guest]: But then what motivates you and what brings you back to doing it all over again is the

02:49:49.280 --> 02:49:57.120
[Guest]: reminder of why did you start in the 1st place right and you remember that did you start

02:49:57.120 --> 02:50:01.640
[Guest]: it for the money, did you start it for, why did you start it right and you started because

02:50:01.640 --> 02:50:06.640
[Guest]: you want to do something good for people, you are able to do that basically.

02:50:06.640 --> 02:50:12.360
[Guest]: There are, there is an entire state which is coming out of inferiority complex based

02:50:12.360 --> 02:50:16.320
[Guest]: on their language because you created a platform in Haryanvi.

02:50:16.320 --> 02:50:22.640
[Guest]: The youth, entire Haryanvi youth today are you just call and tell us that you know that

02:50:22.640 --> 02:50:28.520
[Guest]: because there is stage today I don't feel bad in speaking in Haryanvi and I think about

02:50:28.520 --> 02:50:33.840
[Guest]: that and I am like what the hell, we have to do this, you know if not who, if not us

02:50:33.840 --> 02:50:38.920
[Guest]: who, who will do it, no one is doing it, so we have to do it basically and I think just

02:50:38.920 --> 02:50:45.120
[Guest]: thinking like this, all this motivation porn, success porn comes to mind from here and there,

02:50:45.120 --> 02:50:52.240
[Guest]: do something and then start and I think success is the biggest motivator, in entrepreneurship

02:50:52.240 --> 02:50:57.960
[Guest]: you have to look for the ropes right.

02:50:57.960 --> 02:51:03.280
[Guest]: I always say that sorrows come in a truck and happiness comes in small quantities always.

02:51:03.280 --> 02:51:07.000
[Guest]: Success is also like that, failure happens in one year, it is clear, it is over, VT feed

02:51:07.000 --> 02:51:10.600
[Guest]: is there one day in the morning and it is not existing, but success is never like that,

02:51:10.600 --> 02:51:13.960
[Guest]: success does not happen overnight, success does not happen at once, success comes in

02:51:13.960 --> 02:51:20.240
[Guest]: small quantities, right, so you need to be able to learn to identify those ropes, hold

02:51:20.240 --> 02:51:25.160
[Guest]: on to them and like catch the other, one after the other, one after the other and like keep

02:51:25.160 --> 02:51:26.760
[Guest]: climbing up.

02:51:26.760 --> 02:51:34.920
[Guest]: So when there is a spiral down, now at least the way I, the way I have learned to handle

02:51:34.920 --> 02:51:40.400
[Guest]: it is that I acknowledge it, I do not fight it, I have realized that motivation is not

02:51:40.400 --> 02:51:45.920
[Guest]: a linear thing, there are days when you feel amazingly motivated and you should use that

02:51:45.920 --> 02:51:51.600
[Guest]: to do everything and then there are weeks when you will feel really low and it is okay.

02:51:51.600 --> 02:51:57.320
[Guest]: So I do not fight too much with myself on the days when I am feeling low and I tell

02:51:57.320 --> 02:52:03.760
[Guest]: myself that it is okay, it will also pass and basically it has happened so many times,

02:52:03.760 --> 02:52:08.680
[Guest]: so now it does not feel like, now it feels okay, I know you are feeling very bad right

02:52:08.680 --> 02:52:14.240
[Guest]: now, but you have to do a little self-soothing that it has happened many times, we will feel

02:52:14.240 --> 02:52:15.240
[Guest]: better tomorrow.

02:52:15.240 --> 02:52:19.800
[Guest]: So you look forward to tomorrow and one of those days turns out to be a good day, something

02:52:19.800 --> 02:52:26.960
[Guest]: good happens and one good thing leads to another, I have told my team that one good thing leads

02:52:26.960 --> 02:52:27.960
[Guest]: to another.

02:52:27.960 --> 02:52:31.400
[Guest]: Look for one thing, when something is not going well, just look for one thing that is

02:52:31.400 --> 02:52:35.800
[Guest]: going good and build on that, so everything happens slowly.

02:52:35.800 --> 02:52:40.680
[Amit Varma]: And from where I am sitting, it seems to me that what you described with your 54 employees

02:52:40.680 --> 02:52:45.600
[Amit Varma]: is such a big success, I mean you were earlier talking about your anger issues and whatever,

02:52:45.600 --> 02:52:50.320
[Amit Varma]: but you know, 54 people making that kind of a choice just shows that it did not matter,

02:52:50.320 --> 02:52:53.120
[Amit Varma]: that overall there was something else that you did right.

02:52:53.120 --> 02:52:55.440
[Amit Varma]: So that is quite amazing.

02:52:55.440 --> 02:52:59.520
[Amit Varma]: Just to go back to the smaller question of why did Facebook do what they did and also

02:52:59.520 --> 02:53:04.800
[Amit Varma]: the larger question that brings about is the power that platforms have, like as someone

02:53:04.800 --> 02:53:10.160
[Amit Varma]: who cares deeply about the creator economy, this also worries me, that the way the tech

02:53:10.160 --> 02:53:15.640
[Amit Varma]: ecosystem has evolved is that you practically have, you know, monopolies in their domains

02:53:15.640 --> 02:53:19.560
[Amit Varma]: of Facebook, Twitter, Twitch and so on and so forth.

02:53:19.560 --> 02:53:24.880
[Amit Varma]: And if a platform tomorrow makes a small change in an algorithm, a creator's entire, you know,

02:53:24.880 --> 02:53:31.360
[Amit Varma]: revenue model could fall apart or a business's model could fall apart as happened to you.

02:53:31.360 --> 02:53:35.880
[Amit Varma]: So is this something you think about, given that earlier you said if, you know, content

02:53:35.880 --> 02:53:39.560
[Amit Varma]: is king, distribution is God, distribution to platforms key through.

02:53:39.560 --> 02:53:41.240
[Guest]: So what are your thoughts?

02:53:41.240 --> 02:53:44.680
[Guest]: So let me answer the what happened to Witty Feed first and then I'll tell you my views

02:53:44.680 --> 02:53:45.680
[Guest]: on it.

02:53:45.680 --> 02:53:46.680
[Guest]: Right.

02:53:46.680 --> 02:53:50.680
[Guest]: So not that these companies tell you what they do, why they do, how they do it, etc.

02:53:50.680 --> 02:53:56.880
[Guest]: These companies operate as a dictatorship type, because they have monopolies, they can

02:53:56.880 --> 02:53:58.720
[Guest]: do what they're doing.

02:53:58.720 --> 02:54:04.200
[Guest]: So these people pass orders and you live in their world and you just have to accept it.

02:54:04.200 --> 02:54:05.200
[Guest]: You can't do much about it.

02:54:05.200 --> 02:54:06.200
[Guest]: You can't really fight them.

02:54:06.200 --> 02:54:07.800
[Guest]: And that's the reality of the world, right?

02:54:07.800 --> 02:54:12.000
[Guest]: So just like that, one fine day we got this notice in our inbox.

02:54:12.000 --> 02:54:18.060
[Guest]: And before even we read that, we discovered the notice later, before that, all our properties

02:54:18.060 --> 02:54:22.040
[Guest]: basically started getting deleted from the platform, including my own, like founder's

02:54:22.040 --> 02:54:26.480
[Guest]: profile, even our wife's profile got deleted, all employees, basically everything about

02:54:26.480 --> 02:54:29.920
[Guest]: Witty Feed was removed and so on and so forth, right?

02:54:29.920 --> 02:54:31.360
[Guest]: We never got an official reason.

02:54:31.360 --> 02:54:37.320
[Guest]: Official reason was that you violated some of our platform policies, which is a black

02:54:37.320 --> 02:54:38.320
[Guest]: hole, right?

02:54:38.320 --> 02:54:40.720
[Guest]: You don't know what policies, how do I even know, right?

02:54:40.720 --> 02:54:45.600
[Guest]: And I'm a large company, I'm giving you so much business, there are 150 people, it's

02:54:45.600 --> 02:54:49.560
[Guest]: a business, real business, lives are on the other side of that email, right?

02:54:49.560 --> 02:54:50.960
[Guest]: So you need to talk to me.

02:54:50.960 --> 02:54:55.520
[Guest]: If I'm violating, I'm not a criminal, you need to talk to me, you need to tell me, these

02:54:55.520 --> 02:54:58.880
[Guest]: are the problems, I will fix them, right?

02:54:58.880 --> 02:55:04.560
[Guest]: So but then again, over time, what we discovered, the actual issue was that 2018 was also the

02:55:04.560 --> 02:55:07.320
[Guest]: year of Cambridge Analytica in US.

02:55:07.320 --> 02:55:12.560
[Guest]: And from a very American point of view, the entire issue was non-American companies influencing

02:55:12.560 --> 02:55:17.520
[Guest]: American voters using Facebook as a platform, right?

02:55:17.520 --> 02:55:22.020
[Guest]: We were a non-American company, we were reaching out to every third American voter every month,

02:55:22.020 --> 02:55:26.240
[Guest]: that was the scale that we had 60 million American users, right?

02:55:26.240 --> 02:55:30.080
[Guest]: And we were using Facebook as the primary source of distribution, right?

02:55:30.080 --> 02:55:33.240
[Guest]: Now Facebook was under a lot of pressure, Mark was going through Senate hearings, all

02:55:33.240 --> 02:55:34.240
[Guest]: of that stuff, right?

02:55:34.240 --> 02:55:37.960
[Guest]: We wanted to show some action, we wanted to show them that we are doing something, basically,

02:55:37.960 --> 02:55:38.960
[Guest]: right?

02:55:38.960 --> 02:55:42.920
[Guest]: Now you can't do anything about BuzzFeed, you can't do anything about the other companies

02:55:42.920 --> 02:55:45.200
[Guest]: from New York.

02:55:45.200 --> 02:55:49.520
[Guest]: If you kill a company which is based out of Indore and nobody has even heard of, who cares?

02:55:49.520 --> 02:55:57.600
[Guest]: And the action, however, is 120 million users, 65,000 influencers, you show like a huge

02:55:57.600 --> 02:56:00.840
[Guest]: action, right?

02:56:00.840 --> 02:56:03.480
[Guest]: And no one will care, basically.

02:56:03.480 --> 02:56:08.800
[Guest]: Same company, if owned by some American, based out of New York, the outcome would have been

02:56:08.800 --> 02:56:10.960
[Guest]: very, very different, basically, right?

02:56:10.960 --> 02:56:14.920
[Guest]: So that is what happened, actually.

02:56:14.920 --> 02:56:27.040
[Guest]: I think it also has a lot of unspoken racism, unspoken, how these large companies, especially

02:56:27.040 --> 02:56:32.400
[Guest]: US companies, look at Asian companies and Indian companies, especially Indian entrepreneurs

02:56:32.400 --> 02:56:41.480
[Guest]: and there's a lot of inbuilt discrimination that exists over there, the superiority complex

02:56:41.480 --> 02:56:50.760
[Guest]: and underlying issues, basically, when you peel the onion, you will find that there are

02:56:50.760 --> 02:56:53.720
[Guest]: so many layers to the entire issue.

02:56:53.720 --> 02:56:57.080
[Guest]: It was just convenient for them to kill us.

02:56:57.080 --> 02:57:02.080
[Guest]: And that is why we got killed, not because we deserved or we did something wrong or anything

02:57:02.080 --> 02:57:03.080
[Guest]: like that.

02:57:03.080 --> 02:57:07.680
[Guest]: It's just that because it was convenient for Facebook to kill us, they killed it.

02:57:07.680 --> 02:57:13.080
[Guest]: And there were zero consequences that they had to face, right?

02:57:13.080 --> 02:57:14.840
[Guest]: So it's as simple as that.

02:57:14.840 --> 02:57:18.680
[Guest]: Now, my views on distribution and platforms and all, right?

02:57:18.680 --> 02:57:24.480
[Guest]: So one of the reasons we decided to build Stage as an OTT platform, an app-based platform

02:57:24.480 --> 02:57:30.800
[Guest]: is that at least to some extent, we remove that dependency, that once you have a user

02:57:30.800 --> 02:57:37.360
[Guest]: on your app, at least now they're your user, there is still dependency of play store distributions

02:57:37.360 --> 02:57:44.400
[Guest]: and all policies like you have to pay 30% on cart and all that stuff, right?

02:57:44.400 --> 02:57:53.720
[Guest]: But and which are very, I don't know what's the right word, but wrong policies, right?

02:57:53.720 --> 02:57:58.560
[Guest]: I think, so we reduced that to a large extent by being an app-based player this time, like

02:57:58.560 --> 02:58:02.080
[Guest]: having our own and companies like Dream 11, etc.

02:58:02.080 --> 02:58:06.640
[Guest]: Because of policies, you have shown that you can build a user base without having to distribute

02:58:06.640 --> 02:58:09.160
[Guest]: on play stores and so on and so forth, right?

02:58:09.160 --> 02:58:11.240
[Guest]: So which is why we choose to build this.

02:58:11.240 --> 02:58:14.800
[Guest]: There is a saying, that even if you drink milk, you will still have to swallow it.

02:58:14.800 --> 02:58:19.000
[Guest]: So it happened with us, at least I am never going to trust these platforms for distribution

02:58:19.000 --> 02:58:26.000
[Guest]: because even today, I feel that Google will wake up one day and say, no, we have banned

02:58:26.000 --> 02:58:28.840
[Guest]: you from play stores, we can't do anything.

02:58:28.840 --> 02:58:31.240
[Guest]: And it has happened to so many companies.

02:58:31.240 --> 02:58:34.840
[Guest]: Even companies like PTM, such a large company, it happened to them, right?

02:58:34.840 --> 02:58:37.920
[Guest]: It's probably the influence of VSS in some way, etc.

02:58:37.920 --> 02:58:40.480
[Guest]: And like a lot of media buzz around it, etc.

02:58:40.480 --> 02:58:45.520
[Guest]: And like a certain narrative that got pulled in, which is why Google came on the back foot

02:58:45.520 --> 02:58:47.040
[Guest]: and they restored it.

02:58:47.040 --> 02:58:52.600
[Guest]: If it can happen to them, as long as I am small, it can happen to me anytime and anything.

02:58:52.600 --> 02:58:58.360
[Guest]: So I think these platforms need to re-look into these things.

02:58:58.360 --> 02:59:05.120
[Guest]: And if they will not, we are already seeing the winds of change and these guys will lose.

02:59:05.120 --> 02:59:09.400
[Guest]: There has to be a point where creators will realize that and creators will start to figure

02:59:09.400 --> 02:59:13.600
[Guest]: out their own, this thing and they will lose on that over time, right?

02:59:13.600 --> 02:59:21.000
[Guest]: So anyone, all creators, I still tell everyone, you are a YouTuber, you are all this, but

02:59:21.000 --> 02:59:26.480
[Guest]: the problem is that you are on the mercy of these platforms, they can kill you whenever

02:59:26.480 --> 02:59:27.480
[Guest]: they want.

02:59:27.480 --> 02:59:30.320
[Guest]: Google kills SEO people every third month, right?

02:59:30.320 --> 02:59:31.320
[Guest]: We know that.

02:59:31.320 --> 02:59:36.720
[Guest]: And it's like a known industry accepted fact that traffic will go bad every third month

02:59:36.720 --> 02:59:40.680
[Guest]: and then you have to figure out again what is new, basically, right?

02:59:40.680 --> 02:59:44.880
[Guest]: Similarly, there were so many entrepreneurs on Facebook, so many companies like ours,

02:59:44.880 --> 02:59:45.880
[Guest]: all died.

02:59:45.880 --> 02:59:50.520
[Guest]: There was a very viral thread recently by the founder of Little Things, which was also

02:59:50.520 --> 02:59:53.000
[Guest]: killed in a similar manner.

02:59:53.000 --> 02:59:58.920
[Guest]: BuzzFeed, which was more than a billion dollar company at one point in time, their total

02:59:58.920 --> 03:00:02.600
[Guest]: valuation of the company is less than the money that they raised for simple reason because

03:00:02.600 --> 03:00:03.600
[Guest]: Facebook killed them.

03:00:03.600 --> 03:00:10.520
[Guest]: Reach is gone, basically, traffic is gone, everything is gone, essentially.

03:00:10.520 --> 03:00:15.040
[Guest]: So I still don't know the answer to what to do from here.

03:00:15.040 --> 03:00:20.160
[Guest]: I am trying my best to ensure that my dependency on them is bare minimum.

03:00:20.160 --> 03:00:27.120
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about stage now, like, how did you think of stage and what I find so interesting

03:00:27.120 --> 03:00:31.160
[Amit Varma]: and also impressive that you could then have the courage to follow through on it, is that

03:00:31.160 --> 03:00:36.240
[Amit Varma]: it's going against so many of so much of what the industry is doing in terms of being as

03:00:36.240 --> 03:00:40.920
[Amit Varma]: hyper local as you are, that there is Haryanvi, there is Rajasthani, you know, where people

03:00:40.920 --> 03:00:45.400
[Amit Varma]: could even argue that there is no ecosystem, what will you do in this, you know, and even

03:00:45.400 --> 03:00:51.320
[Amit Varma]: against the conventional knowledge of India versus Bharat, where, you know, the assumption

03:00:51.320 --> 03:00:57.360
[Amit Varma]: is that it's only the very top, which I also believed until I, you know, heard otherwise,

03:00:57.360 --> 03:01:02.080
[Amit Varma]: while researching you, that, you know, it's a very top layer of elites like us who can

03:01:02.080 --> 03:01:04.480
[Amit Varma]: actually spend money via the market.

03:01:04.480 --> 03:01:09.360
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, Sajid Bhai of Bloom Ventures is one of your funders, Sajid had come on

03:01:09.360 --> 03:01:14.080
[Amit Varma]: the show, and he had once written an influential article on this, I think, and had broken it

03:01:14.080 --> 03:01:22.760
[Amit Varma]: down that most of India is basically like sub-Saharan Africa, but what your venture

03:01:22.760 --> 03:01:27.440
[Amit Varma]: seems to say, and what you're saying, not by words, but by actions, is that no, Bharat

03:01:27.440 --> 03:01:31.560
[Amit Varma]: has money as well, if you give value, people will give money, just in the same way that

03:01:31.560 --> 03:01:35.080
[Amit Varma]: your parents, even though they were in a village, sent you to a private school, because there

03:01:35.080 --> 03:01:36.960
[Amit Varma]: was value, they gave money.

03:01:36.960 --> 03:01:41.760
[Amit Varma]: So you know, so tell me a little bit about, you know, how did you conceive of stage?

03:01:41.760 --> 03:01:46.600
[Amit Varma]: And how did all these beliefs, ki Bharat will pay, that we should be hyperlocal, how did

03:01:46.600 --> 03:01:48.160
[Amit Varma]: all this come about?

03:01:48.160 --> 03:01:57.840
[Guest]: Yeah, see, the idea of stage came from, it is rooted into those two same common beliefs

03:01:57.840 --> 03:02:02.920
[Guest]: that the power of content as a medium of mass influence and distribution as the real game.

03:02:02.920 --> 03:02:07.280
[Guest]: So we knew that we want to build a content company again, and we knew that we are going

03:02:07.280 --> 03:02:11.000
[Guest]: to do things differently in terms of distribution this time, right, and whatever we did wrong

03:02:11.000 --> 03:02:17.120
[Guest]: with Witty Feed, basically, one thing that we this time wanted to change was the fact

03:02:17.120 --> 03:02:22.560
[Guest]: that we wanted to build it for Bharat, we made it for Americans, the extreme one end

03:02:22.560 --> 03:02:23.960
[Guest]: of the spectrum.

03:02:23.960 --> 03:02:27.640
[Guest]: And now we want to do the other end of the spectrum on internet, which is the Bharat

03:02:27.640 --> 03:02:29.400
[Guest]: audience, right?

03:02:29.400 --> 03:02:34.480
[Guest]: Reason being because when we were making Witty Feed, and this entire Jio story was unfolding

03:02:34.480 --> 03:02:42.040
[Guest]: in India, we always felt very frustrated and jealousy with the kind of companies that were

03:02:42.040 --> 03:02:46.600
[Guest]: coming up and building for Bharat and we felt that what are they doing, what are they making,

03:02:46.600 --> 03:02:48.560
[Guest]: we can do a much better job.

03:02:48.560 --> 03:02:50.520
[Guest]: And they're not doing it the right way.

03:02:50.520 --> 03:02:58.680
[Guest]: And so we should do it, basically, but no one pivots the 40 crore revenue of a company

03:02:58.680 --> 03:02:59.680
[Guest]: basically.

03:02:59.680 --> 03:03:05.000
[Guest]: They are making it, let them make it, what can I do, I am doing it, so I will keep running

03:03:05.000 --> 03:03:06.000
[Guest]: my company.

03:03:06.000 --> 03:03:07.680
[Guest]: Now we had a chance, basically, right?

03:03:07.680 --> 03:03:11.520
[Guest]: And so we decided to go back and build it for Bharat.

03:03:11.520 --> 03:03:14.720
[Guest]: We were thinking about, okay, what are the problems in content in Bharat, right?

03:03:14.720 --> 03:03:19.200
[Guest]: And the top five content companies, back in the day, which were solving for Bharat were

03:03:19.200 --> 03:03:26.360
[Guest]: all Chinese, all UGC content companies, and all of them used a huge amount of sexually

03:03:26.360 --> 03:03:29.360
[Guest]: explicit content as their actual growth hack, right?

03:03:29.360 --> 03:03:34.760
[Guest]: So TikTok, Likey, Hello, Bego, these types of companies were basically going on at that

03:03:34.760 --> 03:03:35.760
[Guest]: time, right?

03:03:35.760 --> 03:03:38.200
[Guest]: All of them were Chinese and UGC and sexual content.

03:03:38.200 --> 03:03:46.200
[Guest]: I said, if I am saying that I am Bharat, my family is Bharat, then how is that, do they

03:03:46.200 --> 03:03:48.560
[Guest]: want to consume only this kind of content?

03:03:48.560 --> 03:03:51.960
[Guest]: The question was, what do I want to see for my family?

03:03:51.960 --> 03:03:57.520
[Guest]: And the answer to that was, obviously, no, they want to consume better content, premium

03:03:57.520 --> 03:04:02.680
[Guest]: content, sensible content, but unfortunately, it does not exist, nobody is creating that

03:04:02.680 --> 03:04:03.680
[Guest]: for Bharat.

03:04:03.680 --> 03:04:08.760
[Guest]: And that is where we figured out this problem statement that, that if we could build a premium

03:04:08.760 --> 03:04:13.600
[Guest]: and sensible content company for Bharat, it is a complete white space, it is a very large

03:04:13.600 --> 03:04:17.040
[Guest]: opportunity and you can build a very large company here.

03:04:17.040 --> 03:04:21.320
[Guest]: Now, the moment you say premium, you cannot say UGC.

03:04:21.320 --> 03:04:27.640
[Guest]: So if you make UGC, then basically the same nonsense content will come, so we said, okay,

03:04:27.640 --> 03:04:28.640
[Guest]: remove UGC.

03:04:28.640 --> 03:04:29.640
[Guest]: There are very few options in PGC.

03:04:29.640 --> 03:04:34.120
[Guest]: You can build a news company or make something like VTV or make something like a news channel

03:04:34.120 --> 03:04:40.800
[Guest]: and then make OTT, basically, VTV got eliminated because of whatever reasons, news, because

03:04:40.800 --> 03:04:44.920
[Guest]: again, where will you do its distribution, Facebook, Google, it will be on all of this.

03:04:44.920 --> 03:04:54.960
[Guest]: OTT made more sense because one, it was as much a tech play as content, so it connected

03:04:54.960 --> 03:04:55.960
[Guest]: to us.

03:04:55.960 --> 03:04:59.640
[Guest]: If we make app-based, then the distribution will be ours this time, we will own the user,

03:04:59.640 --> 03:05:01.600
[Guest]: whatever we acquire, it will be ours.

03:05:01.600 --> 03:05:05.640
[Guest]: The problem with Fitivit was that we used to acquire 120 million every month and none

03:05:05.640 --> 03:05:06.640
[Guest]: of it was ours.

03:05:06.640 --> 03:05:12.280
[Guest]: All of them were the same, our returning user was 60-70%, but we had to acquire it every

03:05:12.280 --> 03:05:13.280
[Guest]: month, basically.

03:05:13.280 --> 03:05:21.400
[Guest]: So here, if we acquire it once, they are ours, basically, if we can retain them, so we said,

03:05:21.400 --> 03:05:26.840
[Guest]: let's build an OTT for India, so Netflix for India solution came out, but the problem,

03:05:26.840 --> 03:05:32.640
[Guest]: the moment we said it, we kind of got scared a little, because that means there are about

03:05:32.640 --> 03:05:39.600
[Guest]: 20-25 active OTT platforms in India, small and big, you can mix them all, if you go to

03:05:39.600 --> 03:05:43.960
[Guest]: sleep at night and ask, they will say, we are building Netflix for India.

03:05:43.960 --> 03:05:51.120
[Guest]: Everybody claims that only, you can ask SonyLibs, Hotstar, G5, All Balaji, anyone, everybody

03:05:51.120 --> 03:05:53.160
[Guest]: will claim the same thing.

03:05:53.160 --> 03:06:00.640
[Guest]: So we said, what are we making here, in such a crowded market, and every single player

03:06:00.640 --> 03:06:08.840
[Guest]: literally is owned by an incumbent, is a large production house, a large company backed by

03:06:08.840 --> 03:06:13.240
[Guest]: some media, so what are we going to do here?

03:06:13.240 --> 03:06:20.880
[Guest]: We went back to our village, literally, and one of the things that has helped me throughout

03:06:20.880 --> 03:06:29.120
[Guest]: our story, all three founders, that we always remained an outsider, in WittyFeed also, we

03:06:29.120 --> 03:06:33.360
[Guest]: were able to do whatever we could, because we did not know that it was not possible,

03:06:33.360 --> 03:06:36.600
[Guest]: we did not know that a company is not made in Indore, for that you have to go to Bangalore,

03:06:36.600 --> 03:06:40.040
[Guest]: you have to do a startup, so we did not know that we should not do revenue, we did not

03:06:40.040 --> 03:06:45.080
[Guest]: know that profitability is not looked at as a good thing in the VC circles, we did not

03:06:45.080 --> 03:06:49.960
[Guest]: know that we cannot make global media from India, we did not know all this, so we did

03:06:49.960 --> 03:06:57.960
[Guest]: it, then it happened, now in the same way, in OTT, we were still an outsider, basically,

03:06:57.960 --> 03:07:02.960
[Guest]: we did not know what all could not be done, which is said by the book, that all this is

03:07:02.960 --> 03:07:03.960
[Guest]: not possible, right?

03:07:03.960 --> 03:07:14.720
[Guest]: So, our entire life, our entrepreneurial journey has been all about common sense, what does

03:07:14.720 --> 03:07:19.960
[Guest]: make sense here, so we said, on one hand, I am saying that my family needs premium sensible

03:07:19.960 --> 03:07:25.360
[Guest]: content and not, on the other hand, I am saying that there are 27 OTT, so where is the problem?

03:07:25.360 --> 03:07:26.800
[Guest]: What is the unsolved part?

03:07:26.800 --> 03:07:33.080
[Guest]: We went back to our village, literally, and there we did some research, understood, what

03:07:33.080 --> 03:07:38.160
[Guest]: we discovered became the unique insight on which we built this company, which is that

03:07:38.160 --> 03:07:42.760
[Guest]: you look at all the OTTs in India, in the name of vernacular content, all of them do

03:07:42.760 --> 03:07:47.800
[Guest]: language-based content, Hindi, Tamil, Telugu, Marathi, Punjabi, Bangla, Gujarati, Kannada,

03:07:47.800 --> 03:07:53.840
[Guest]: Malayalam, you will get all this, I grew up speaking Haryanvi, Haryanvi is not a language

03:07:53.840 --> 03:07:58.720
[Guest]: and there was no content in Haryanvi, there was no app in Haryanvi, nothing, so I said,

03:07:58.720 --> 03:08:03.480
[Guest]: this is it, this is not happening, both are right, there are 27 OTTs, but nobody is doing

03:08:03.480 --> 03:08:04.480
[Guest]: Haryanvi.

03:08:04.480 --> 03:08:05.480
[Guest]: Why is no one doing it?

03:08:05.480 --> 03:08:08.480
[Guest]: Which is the pursuit of trying to figure this out, we found that Haryanvi is a dialect and

03:08:08.480 --> 03:08:12.880
[Guest]: not a language, before that I did not know all this, I spoke in the vernacular and I

03:08:12.880 --> 03:08:19.440
[Guest]: read the language, but never thought of it in a practical sense, right, and this discrimination

03:08:19.440 --> 03:08:25.120
[Guest]: by our constitution between a dialect and a language leads to a lot of things.

03:08:25.120 --> 03:08:28.120
[Guest]: Dialects don't have their own scripts, so they don't have their own literature, so they

03:08:28.120 --> 03:08:32.520
[Guest]: don't have their own cinema, so they don't have their own industry, Boliyaan literally

03:08:32.520 --> 03:08:39.480
[Guest]: Boli jatiye, likhi nahi jatiye, basically, lipi nahi hoti hunki apni, toh we said ki

03:08:39.480 --> 03:08:43.760
[Guest]: boss Haryana mein toh hai, is it a Haryana only problem?

03:08:43.760 --> 03:08:48.880
[Guest]: So you go to Rajasthan, people speak Marwadi, Sikhavati, Haruti, Mewati, depending on the

03:08:48.880 --> 03:08:54.280
[Guest]: region that you come from, UP speaks Braj, Bundeli, Avdi, Bhojpuri, Kannoji, Bihar speaks

03:08:54.280 --> 03:09:02.240
[Guest]: Mathli, Maghai, Bhojpuri, Angika and Bajjika, then North toh pura cover hogaya, North mein

03:09:02.240 --> 03:09:06.320
[Guest]: toh Boliyaan hai, then we said, kya yeh North only problem hai?

03:09:06.320 --> 03:09:12.000
[Guest]: You go to the entire coastal region of Maharashtra, Karnataka and Goa speaks Konkani, Konkani

03:09:12.000 --> 03:09:16.760
[Guest]: is a language recognised as a language because of Goa, but still there is hardly any content

03:09:16.760 --> 03:09:21.520
[Guest]: in Konkani and there is a very large population that speaks it, Gujarat mein Gujrati hai lekin

03:09:21.520 --> 03:09:29.200
[Guest]: Gujrati ke andar Kathiawadi aur Kachi hai, Maharashtra has Kulapuri, Malwani, Telangana

03:09:29.200 --> 03:09:32.760
[Guest]: and Andhra were divided, one of the big reason was that they speak two different versions

03:09:32.760 --> 03:09:37.880
[Guest]: of Telugu, there is Tullu and there are different Sindhi and bohot saari aisi phir chhoti languages

03:09:37.880 --> 03:09:42.680
[Guest]: hain jaise Assamese, Oriya, the entire North East, Nepali and yeh sab basic, point being

03:09:42.680 --> 03:09:49.200
[Guest]: that humne yeh discover kiya that in India, language is an urban concept, seher mein kya

03:09:49.200 --> 03:09:52.840
[Guest]: hai na, aap kahin se ho, main kahin se ho, hume Hindi aur English samajh mein aati hai

03:09:52.840 --> 03:09:56.080
[Guest]: toh hum yeh use kar rahe hain, main Haryanvi mein nahi bol sakta hai kyunki aapko samajh

03:09:56.080 --> 03:09:59.280
[Guest]: mein nahi aayega aur aap whatever dialect you may speak, you can't speak in that because

03:09:59.280 --> 03:10:05.320
[Guest]: I will not understand right, so we need common ground and so urban places, cities are about

03:10:05.320 --> 03:10:11.520
[Guest]: languages, but the moment you go beyond urban settlements, everyone speaks in dialects,

03:10:11.520 --> 03:10:18.440
[Guest]: aap Gurgaon se 20 km andar chale jao, aapko Hindi bolne wala vekti milega nahi, for me

03:10:18.440 --> 03:10:24.760
[Guest]: to learn Hindi, to speak clean Hindi was as big a task as it was to learn English, jaise

03:10:24.760 --> 03:10:31.200
[Guest]: hum Neeraj Chopra ki hi baat kar rahe the right, he speaks his Hindi with a very Haryanvi

03:10:31.200 --> 03:10:37.040
[Guest]: accent and I am so glad that he embraces his own identity so well because I didn't, growing

03:10:37.040 --> 03:10:43.760
[Guest]: up hume lagta tha ki hume Haryanvi was supposed to be a bad thing, I used to literally scold

03:10:43.760 --> 03:10:50.280
[Guest]: and beat my siblings for speaking in Haryanvi, toh hum hamare dimaag me itna inferiority

03:10:50.280 --> 03:10:55.960
[Guest]: bhara jaata hai na iske upar, point being that the insight yeh mila ki in India language

03:10:55.960 --> 03:11:01.120
[Guest]: is an urban concept, the moment you go beyond urban settlements, everybody speaks in dialects

03:11:01.120 --> 03:11:06.680
[Guest]: and so if there is a true hyper local content company to be built for Bharat, for the next

03:11:06.680 --> 03:11:11.720
[Guest]: billion people, something that will disrupt Bollywood, something that will be built bottom

03:11:11.720 --> 03:11:16.400
[Guest]: up for them and not with a top-down approach ki ek film banayega Bombay aur poori desh

03:11:16.400 --> 03:11:24.080
[Guest]: ko vahi dekhna hai, something that will not bastardize the Haryanvi spoken by the characters

03:11:24.080 --> 03:11:30.280
[Guest]: in Dangal because it has to be relevant to somebody in Maharashtra also and so it has

03:11:30.280 --> 03:11:34.400
[Guest]: to be a dialect-based content company and not a language-based sort of a platform.

03:11:34.400 --> 03:11:38.880
[Guest]: So we decided to build the most hyper local content company ever built, a dialect-based

03:11:38.880 --> 03:11:44.960
[Guest]: OTT for Bharat basically, again humein nahi pata tha ki aisa nahi ho sakta hai, so bas

03:11:44.960 --> 03:11:50.760
[Guest]: chale banane aur ho gaya over time, challenges uske apne rahe, maybe I can talk about that

03:11:50.760 --> 03:11:56.720
[Guest]: also a little bit, teen parts mein challenges the, everyone said that ki kaun download garega

03:11:56.720 --> 03:12:01.200
[Guest]: Haryanvi ke liye app, aur kar bhi lega toh kitne logonge, so demand and depth as one

03:12:01.200 --> 03:12:06.400
[Guest]: problem, second people said there is no existing supply and which means there are no existing

03:12:06.400 --> 03:12:11.160
[Guest]: creators, so how will you build the supply basically, so supply as an issue and third

03:12:11.160 --> 03:12:16.440
[Guest]: monetization, Bharat paise nahi deta hai basically, ek ek karke humne teenon ko solve kiya, sabse

03:12:16.440 --> 03:12:23.320
[Guest]: pehle demand ko solve kiya, so we launched with a free app in the first 18 months, toh

03:12:23.320 --> 03:12:27.000
[Guest]: paise the nahi, content banane ke liye, PGC content banane ke liye, pre-request hai ki

03:12:27.000 --> 03:12:31.440
[Guest]: aapko paise invest karne padheni hai, right, so you have to figure out ki kaunsa content

03:12:31.440 --> 03:12:37.160
[Guest]: mein jo saste mein banega, toh artist based content, comedy, poetry, storytelling, folk,

03:12:37.160 --> 03:12:43.840
[Guest]: nokkar naatak, yeh ek toh dialects mein naturally exist karta hai, doosra bahut sasta hota hai,

03:12:43.840 --> 03:12:48.480
[Guest]: teesra hamara original idea hi keval artist based content banane ka tha, which is why

03:12:48.480 --> 03:12:55.560
[Guest]: the name is stage of the platform, because humein lagta tha ki, dekho jo mainstream media

03:12:55.560 --> 03:13:01.520
[Guest]: hai, wo toh khareeda jaata hai, bechara jaata hai, uski apni ek alag samasyaayin hain, uske

03:13:01.520 --> 03:13:06.120
[Guest]: upar pressure aata hai, yeh aata hai, wo aata hai, toh phir historically, matlab Raja Maharaja

03:13:06.120 --> 03:13:12.720
[Guest]: ho ke time se leke abhi tak, who are the, kaunse type ka content hai, jo krantiyan khari karta

03:13:12.720 --> 03:13:17.720
[Guest]: hai, revolution kahaan se aata hai, change kahaan se, chingariyan kahaan se banti hai,

03:13:17.720 --> 03:13:24.160
[Guest]: and it has always been the artists, you know, chahe wo comedy, poetry karke karte hain,

03:13:24.160 --> 03:13:28.240
[Guest]: wo folk ki form mein karte hain, matlab jeetne wale ki kahaniyaan toh itihaas batata hai,

03:13:28.240 --> 03:13:32.920
[Guest]: par haarne wale ki kahani kaun batata hai, itihaas amesa jeetne wale ki kahani batata

03:13:32.920 --> 03:13:36.560
[Guest]: hai, haarne wale ki kahani kisne batayi hai, wo folk ki form mein bahar aati hai, geet

03:13:36.560 --> 03:13:42.240
[Guest]: bante hain uske, uske upar koi kavita likhi jaati hai, uske upar koi kuch aur hota hai,

03:13:42.240 --> 03:13:47.800
[Guest]: aisi cheejein hoti hain, art bante hain, art has always preserved our history in the most,

03:13:47.800 --> 03:13:57.600
[Guest]: this thing, so we said ki yaar, agar dialects ka Netflix banega, toh wo artist based hoga,

03:13:57.600 --> 03:14:02.560
[Guest]: basically, ye artist log hain jo zinda rakhte hain, toh hum agar genuinely ek aisa platform

03:14:02.560 --> 03:14:08.600
[Guest]: banana jaate hain, jo revolution khada kare, jo ek surrogate tariqa ho sake, poori janta

03:14:08.600 --> 03:14:12.440
[Guest]: ko jagane ka, toh it has to be ek artist ka Netflix hona chahiye basically, so which is

03:14:12.440 --> 03:14:17.880
[Guest]: how the stage, which was the original idea of stage, so we started with that content,

03:14:17.880 --> 03:14:22.840
[Guest]: within the first 18 months, 18 months the app was free, we had 1.5 million downloads

03:14:22.840 --> 03:14:27.000
[Guest]: just from Haryana, Haryana se start kiya because of course my home dialect yeh, wo sab right,

03:14:27.000 --> 03:14:32.600
[Guest]: 1.5 million downloads the, 15 lakh download, toh demand, depth, yeh sab toh solve hogaya,

03:14:32.600 --> 03:14:38.120
[Guest]: but we also realized ki log is content ka paisa nahi denge, kyunki and see this is where

03:14:38.120 --> 03:14:42.440
[Guest]: going back to what you said, ki ye contradictions hain life ke right, you start with something

03:14:42.440 --> 03:14:46.120
[Guest]: and then you realize ki bhai, isko sustain karna hai toh kuch aur karna padega right,

03:14:46.120 --> 03:14:50.840
[Guest]: I started with an NGO and then I started a business, I started with the idea of building

03:14:50.840 --> 03:14:55.400
[Guest]: a surrogate media, like a platform for artists, etc, patna realized ki boss iska paisa nahi

03:14:55.400 --> 03:14:59.960
[Guest]: denge log, kyunki ye na, sabko lagta hai ki ye content YouTube pe mil jayega aage peechay,

03:14:59.960 --> 03:15:03.720
[Guest]: even when it was exclusive, artist based content ki samjhya ye hai ki logon ko lagta hai ki

03:15:03.720 --> 03:15:09.800
[Guest]: YouTube pe aajata hai, doosri uske samjhya ye hai ki aap kuch bhi koshish kar lo, comedian

03:15:09.800 --> 03:15:15.320
[Guest]: aapka perform kar raha hai, aap kya paanch camera laga loge, phir uske aage ek jaga khada

03:15:15.320 --> 03:15:20.360
[Guest]: ho ki perform karega, toh uski perceived production value jo hai na, wo bahut low hoti hai, uske

03:15:20.360 --> 03:15:25.240
[Guest]: liye paisa lena bahut muskil kaam hai, which is when we realized that ki people will pay

03:15:25.240 --> 03:15:29.320
[Guest]: only for the established content formats which are, and longer content formats like movies

03:15:29.320 --> 03:15:36.200
[Guest]: and web series and so on and so forth, and so came the part of solving for the supply,

03:15:36.200 --> 03:15:41.640
[Guest]: ki jo supply humne banayi hai, usse liye paisa nahi milega, supply ke liye aapko jo typical

03:15:41.640 --> 03:15:43.400
[Guest]: entertainment ke supply hoti hai, wo banaani padegi.

03:15:44.680 --> 03:15:49.560
[Guest]: So we literally jumpstarted a local Bollywood in Haryana, we literally created a poori industry

03:15:49.560 --> 03:15:54.280
[Guest]: banayi iskrayat se, one of the cliche insights that you, when you work there, you realize

03:15:54.280 --> 03:15:59.720
[Guest]: is that talent is universal, but opportunity is not. There are so many people who want

03:15:59.720 --> 03:16:05.080
[Guest]: to create great content, who wanted to make movies and so on, like Haryanvi mein unko

03:16:05.080 --> 03:16:09.800
[Guest]: kaam karna hai, script likhi hui hai, ya kuch kiya hua hai, lekin platform nahi, Haryanvi

03:16:09.800 --> 03:16:13.800
[Guest]: mein film banali toh release kaun karega, paisa laga diya toh recover kahan se hoga.

03:16:13.800 --> 03:16:18.680
[Guest]: Right, so we basically went on the ground, worked with these people, incubated them,

03:16:18.680 --> 03:16:23.160
[Guest]: helped them become creators and producers, and pehli web series humne sanction ki Haryana

03:16:23.160 --> 03:16:28.520
[Guest]: ki, jaise hi humne pehli web series app pe dali, the engagements skyrocketed.

03:16:28.520 --> 03:16:35.000
[Guest]: Even by the way, aaj, something that I am most proud to tell is that Haryana today has

03:16:35.000 --> 03:16:42.200
[Guest]: a very flourishing industry, locally, we very fondly call it Harrywood, aur 25 production

03:16:42.200 --> 03:16:46.520
[Guest]: houses hunge kam se kam bhi yahan pe, more than 1500 people have jobs directly and indirectly

03:16:46.520 --> 03:16:50.360
[Guest]: because of what we have been able to create, and reverse migration ho raha hai.

03:16:50.360 --> 03:16:54.360
[Guest]: Abhi pehle kya hota tha, kisi Haryanvi ko agar entertainment mein kuch karna hai, toh

03:16:54.360 --> 03:16:58.040
[Guest]: woh basically Bombay jaata tha, wahan Bollywood mein struggle karta tha, ab kya ho raha hai,

03:16:58.040 --> 03:17:02.280
[Guest]: they are like, yaar, humare gaon mein filme ban rahi hain, aur hum yahaan struggle kar

03:17:02.280 --> 03:17:06.040
[Guest]: rahe hain, they are coming back, plus Bombay se aadmi wapas aata toh usko ijjat bhi zyada

03:17:06.040 --> 03:17:11.240
[Guest]: milti hai, ki bhai usko aata hai, Bombay se aaya hai, seekh ke aaya hai, right, so kaafi

03:17:11.240 --> 03:17:14.840
[Guest]: amazing ye ho raha hai, jaise hi humne web series dali, engagements skyrocketed, which

03:17:14.840 --> 03:17:16.840
[Guest]: is when we knew that people will pay.

03:17:16.840 --> 03:17:20.360
[Guest]: Answering your last part of the question, which is that, how did I know that people

03:17:20.360 --> 03:17:23.720
[Guest]: will pay, and why did I believe in that and all, see, gaon mein jab aap bade ho toh, toh

03:17:23.720 --> 03:17:26.760
[Guest]: un logon ko aap samashte ho, wohin bade ho, yeh sab hua, right, so like you said, my

03:17:26.760 --> 03:17:31.640
[Guest]: father sent me to a private school, yaar, papa jo grocery store chalate the, kirane

03:17:31.640 --> 03:17:37.080
[Guest]: ki dukaan, we used to sell Pepsi, Coke, Darbar, Lifebuoy, Lux, sab hum beshte the yeh sab,

03:17:37.080 --> 03:17:42.200
[Guest]: aur bhi lot more other brands, it has never been about that they don't want to pay, it

03:17:42.200 --> 03:17:46.440
[Guest]: has always been about that, have you created enough value for them, aur entrepreneurs

03:17:46.440 --> 03:17:50.440
[Guest]: ko sath, problem kya unfortunately, sabko lagta hai ki Bharat pay nahi karega, toh

03:17:50.440 --> 03:17:55.400
[Guest]: ek urban, aur entrepreneur banta hai kaun hai normally, thode se sehri log bante hain,

03:17:55.400 --> 03:17:58.520
[Guest]: yaar at least sehr mein aane ke baad insan bante hain, gaon mein baith ke toh koi bana

03:17:58.520 --> 03:18:03.080
[Guest]: nahi raha hai company hain normally, toh ek urban bias ban jaata hai, and easy way out

03:18:03.080 --> 03:18:07.640
[Guest]: is, ki sehr ke liye banao, log paisa dete hain yahan pe, toh everybody ends up creating

03:18:07.640 --> 03:18:13.720
[Guest]: for the cities, for the urban audience, and then they feel entitled ke, arre app hi toh

03:18:13.720 --> 03:18:18.680
[Guest]: hai kya, phir aap bhi use kar lo, aur Bharat ko phir milti utran, Bharat ko milta second

03:18:18.680 --> 03:18:24.280
[Guest]: class experience, and which is why they have not been successful in monetizing Bharat user,

03:18:24.280 --> 03:18:30.360
[Guest]: and humne day zero pe bola ki yaar, we will build for everyone minus the top 10%, top

03:18:30.360 --> 03:18:35.160
[Guest]: 10% Delhi ka ho, Bombay ka ho, ya mere gaon ka ho, uske liye nahi banana hai, which is

03:18:35.160 --> 03:18:40.440
[Guest]: why we had the courage to build it in dialects, right, toh humein lagta tha yaar log karenge

03:18:40.440 --> 03:18:46.280
[Guest]: paisa pay, humne unke liye truly value create ki hai, and April 2021 mein, from a fully

03:18:46.280 --> 03:18:52.120
[Guest]: free app, we became a fully paid app, and the response has been phenomenal, abhi 1,10,000,

03:18:52.120 --> 03:18:56.920
[Guest]: 1,15,000 paying subscribers hain, just from Haryana, 400 rupiah dete hain saal ka, which

03:18:56.920 --> 03:19:01.880
[Guest]: is also typically the rate at any other OTT, even humara minimum 200 rupiah, typically

03:19:01.880 --> 03:19:06.040
[Guest]: 30-40 rupiah, 50 rupiah hota hai maine ka, OTT's ka, baaki OTT's ka, humara minimum

03:19:06.040 --> 03:19:11.000
[Guest]: 200 rupiah hai, 3 maine ke liye, and we got phenomenal response, 8-10,000 naye subscriber

03:19:11.000 --> 03:19:16.680
[Guest]: har maine aate hain Haryana se, and, matlab people love the fact that we've been able

03:19:16.680 --> 03:19:22.040
[Guest]: to do what we've been able to do, and we've found a meaning, larger meaning when the youth

03:19:22.040 --> 03:19:27.160
[Guest]: came and told us, and that became the mission of the company today, is that, logon ne mein

03:19:27.160 --> 03:19:32.920
[Guest]: bataya ki yaar, Haryanvi bolne mein sharam aati thi pehle, itna inferiority complex,

03:19:32.920 --> 03:19:39.160
[Guest]: itna logon ko, logon na, agar mai abhi Haryanvi mein podcast karunga toh logon ko lagta ki

03:19:39.160 --> 03:19:43.160
[Guest]: anpad hai, gamaar hai, gaon ka hai, isko aata nahi hai, kahin sahar mein aap bol nahi sakte,

03:19:43.160 --> 03:19:48.760
[Guest]: right, and so imagine what it does to people jo jindagi mein kebhal Haryanvi bolte hain,

03:19:48.760 --> 03:19:54.200
[Guest]: kaise aap agar mere ghar aoge na Amit, and you're sitting in the living room on, in my

03:19:54.200 --> 03:20:00.520
[Guest]: own house, on my sofa, my father will not sit there, just he will not sit there, he

03:20:00.520 --> 03:20:04.040
[Guest]: will say, arre nahi nahi, aap log bade legal hoga, aap log baithiye, mai kya karunga yaan,

03:20:04.040 --> 03:20:08.280
[Guest]: he will just feel so inferior by the fact that you will, you and me will end up talking in

03:20:08.280 --> 03:20:11.000
[Guest]: Hindi or English, and he will just not feel comfortable there.

03:20:12.840 --> 03:20:17.560
[Guest]: Imagine what it does to this entire set of people who only grow up speaking in their

03:20:17.560 --> 03:20:23.480
[Guest]: dialects, and they're felt inferior, they're made to feel inferior because they speak in

03:20:23.480 --> 03:20:30.520
[Guest]: a certain way, which is borderline criminal, in my understanding, right, and these people

03:20:30.520 --> 03:20:34.440
[Guest]: came and told us that, kya hota tha na ki app pe log aate, 5 star reviews dekhe likhte,

03:20:34.440 --> 03:20:39.080
[Guest]: Jai Haryana, Jai Haryanvi, aapne maari culture ko bacha liya, aapne maari boli ko bacha liya,

03:20:39.080 --> 03:20:43.880
[Guest]: and which is when by talking to them we understood ki yaar, our true mission is actually to restore

03:20:44.600 --> 03:20:51.400
[Guest]: the pride and the dignity of the dialects, their, the respect, the pride and the dignity

03:20:51.400 --> 03:20:56.680
[Guest]: of the dialects and cultures back into them, basically. That's the real product that is

03:20:56.680 --> 03:21:00.760
[Amit Varma]: happening because of what we're able to do. No, this is, I can't tell you how inspiring

03:21:00.760 --> 03:21:04.840
[Amit Varma]: this is. I hope many, many people are listening to this and, you know, feeling like they should

03:21:04.840 --> 03:21:10.440
[Amit Varma]: do the same for their dialects. Like I, you know, when, when we fixed our episode, I sent

03:21:10.440 --> 03:21:13.880
[Amit Varma]: the link to download the app to a bunch of my friends, and I said, please download, tell me

03:21:13.880 --> 03:21:19.160
[Amit Varma]: what your experience is. And one of them, shout out to Kumar, just sort of wrote back today to

03:21:19.160 --> 03:21:24.680
[Amit Varma]: say he was so blown away. And one of the things he was blown away by is ki ye jo saare artist hai,

03:21:24.680 --> 03:21:28.360
[Amit Varma]: he said ki maine inka kabhi naam nahi suna hai, maine inka kaam kabhi nahi dekha hai,

03:21:28.360 --> 03:21:32.840
[Amit Varma]: Bollywood mein, you know, nobody is familiar to me. So all of these people, the fact that

03:21:32.840 --> 03:21:39.160
[Amit Varma]: they have a platform, the fact that they have a stage to, you know, so you've created a new

03:21:39.160 --> 03:21:44.600
[Amit Varma]: ecosystem. And when you create a new ecosystem, you expand the culture. Like one of my worries

03:21:44.600 --> 03:21:49.560
[Amit Varma]: that I've discussed on the show, and I feel I've spoken with various people about whether it is

03:21:49.560 --> 03:21:54.920
[Amit Varma]: happening to languages, is homogenization. Because kya ho daana ki Hindi hai, Hindi ke itne saare

03:21:54.920 --> 03:22:00.120
[Amit Varma]: dialects hai, lekin gradually, the smaller ones start disappearing and Hindi becomes everything,

03:22:00.120 --> 03:22:05.640
[Amit Varma]: especially because India is a rapidly urbanizing country. And, and it's such a loss because there

03:22:05.640 --> 03:22:12.280
[Amit Varma]: is such a rich heritage there, that is kind of gone. So I'm just sort of blown away by what you're

03:22:12.280 --> 03:22:19.320
[Amit Varma]: doing. My next question is this, that at one level, like I completely agree with your disdain

03:22:19.320 --> 03:22:23.960
[Amit Varma]: of the top down way of thinking and the top down content creation jaise Bollywood se hota hai ki

03:22:23.960 --> 03:22:29.080
[Amit Varma]: Bombay se banayenge, poora desh dekhega and all of that. And that was actually one of the reasons I

03:22:29.080 --> 03:22:34.280
[Amit Varma]: love TikTok when it came out, like Chinese company, it was a huge leveler, it was a huge leveler,

03:22:34.280 --> 03:22:39.800
[Amit Varma]: because any people across the country in villages, people of alternate sexualities, people who were

03:22:39.800 --> 03:22:45.240
[Amit Varma]: otherwise oppressed and marginal, who could never have access to a platform, could suddenly just

03:22:45.240 --> 03:22:49.640
[Amit Varma]: turn their phone around and shoot a video of themselves and put it up. And I thought that

03:22:49.640 --> 03:22:55.000
[Amit Varma]: was incredibly empowering. So at one level, I understand where you come from when you say ki

03:22:55.000 --> 03:23:01.400
[Amit Varma]: user generated content can only go so far. But at another level, I feel that that is also a kind of

03:23:01.400 --> 03:23:09.880
[Amit Varma]: bottom up. You know, your artists that you have access to also is still a limited pool. And,

03:23:10.600 --> 03:23:17.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, user generated, maybe I see sort of a lot of hope there, like most of the content I

03:23:17.080 --> 03:23:21.800
[Amit Varma]: consume on YouTube is actually user generated. Absolutely, you know, so I so I agree with you

03:23:21.800 --> 03:23:27.400
[Guest]: on that. And I have nothing against UGC, by the way, there. We've been debating an idea

03:23:27.400 --> 03:23:33.880
[Guest]: internally of having a UGC section on our own app also, by the way. And, and so what I meant

03:23:33.880 --> 03:23:40.440
[Guest]: when I was explaining why not UGC, because the the way these, especially the Chinese apps were

03:23:40.440 --> 03:23:46.920
[Guest]: using UGC was in the name of UGC, they were essentially seeding a huge amount of sexually

03:23:46.920 --> 03:23:53.800
[Guest]: explicit content and calling it UGC and using that as the actual growth hack, right. So there were a

03:23:53.800 --> 03:24:00.200
[Guest]: lot of amazing things about TikTok and it brought out a amazing set of influencers and creators and

03:24:00.200 --> 03:24:05.160
[Guest]: so many talented people out, right. And we heard such amazing stories because of TikTok and short

03:24:05.160 --> 03:24:11.640
[Guest]: video apps, right. So I agree with you on that. Absolutely. And just that they this needs to be

03:24:11.640 --> 03:24:17.800
[Guest]: done with the right intent. UGC platforms are amazing, but need to be done with the right

03:24:17.800 --> 03:24:22.520
[Guest]: intent. YouTube has done a fairly good job. There are so many creators, UGC creators would

03:24:22.520 --> 03:24:29.080
[Guest]: who become big creators because of YouTube. Even there are some newer kind of platforms which are

03:24:29.080 --> 03:24:36.360
[Guest]: doing a good job. Just say the Indian versions, for example, are not so bad to be honest. See

03:24:36.360 --> 03:24:41.240
[Guest]: Chinese apps, the problem was that they basically had zero accountability, right. There was no fear

03:24:41.240 --> 03:24:47.960
[Guest]: of anything. They could cross any limit and get away with it, right. And which is what was

03:24:47.960 --> 03:24:55.640
[Guest]: bringing up a huge, an entire generation online, believing that this is what internet is.

03:24:56.520 --> 03:25:05.000
[Guest]: And which is why I said, we chose a certain white space that there are every Tom, Dick and Harry says

03:25:05.000 --> 03:25:10.120
[Guest]: that UGC app banate hain. Ye hi to banare, specially TikTok jaane ke baad toh baris type aa gayi thi

03:25:10.120 --> 03:25:15.320
[Guest]: hink, right. All my investors message me, apna time aa gaya, aap toh UGC banate hain. Like, why?

03:25:15.320 --> 03:25:23.240
[Guest]: Kyunki so many log banaye rahe hain, toh main usme kya karunga, right. The empty space, the fact

03:25:23.240 --> 03:25:30.920
[Guest]: that most people thought ki Bharat premium deserve nahi karta hai is what was a problem for me.

03:25:30.920 --> 03:25:36.440
[Guest]: Mujhe aisa lagta hai ki Bharat ko bhi premium content deserve, aisa aap, sabko aisa kyu lagta

03:25:36.440 --> 03:25:42.120
[Guest]: hai ki Netflix jaisa premium content keval Delhi-Bombay walon ke liye hi hai. Mera gaon

03:25:42.120 --> 03:25:47.160
[Guest]: ka aadmi ko wo premium content kyun nahi mil sakta? Woh phir bolte hain, acha Delhi shop hai,

03:25:47.160 --> 03:25:52.120
[Guest]: Delhi shop hum sabko pata hai, it's a brainwashing, it's bullshit content essentially. I know it

03:25:52.120 --> 03:25:58.440
[Guest]: works, it does amazing TRPs and all, but point is, can I not deliver great quality content?

03:25:59.080 --> 03:26:03.080
[Guest]: Do you think that they don't want to consume quality content? And my entire fight has been

03:26:03.080 --> 03:26:12.040
[Guest]: that they want to. Humne bahut hi hard stance liya ispe that we will not do any sex, violence and

03:26:12.040 --> 03:26:19.480
[Guest]: abusive content on our app. Everything that we do has to be very family friendly. Imagine a Delhi

03:26:19.480 --> 03:26:26.200
[Guest]: shop, but the stories will be very high quality, very high quality acting and something that will

03:26:26.200 --> 03:26:32.920
[Guest]: leave them thinking that will, that will not be mindless basically, right? And that's the,

03:26:34.040 --> 03:26:39.320
[Guest]: agar koi actual mein stage ko dhang se samjhe na, so that is the proof that we have been able

03:26:39.320 --> 03:26:44.840
[Guest]: to create. The real POC stage is of the fact that Bharat wants to, if you provide, Bharat can

03:26:44.840 --> 03:26:51.720
[Guest]: consume premium content, wants to consume premium content, sensible stuff and stories which are not

03:26:51.720 --> 03:26:58.120
[Guest]: mindless. Kewal senseless sexual comedy nahi chalti hai Bharat mein, uske suvay bhi bahut

03:26:58.120 --> 03:27:03.080
[Guest]: kuch chalta hai, is the entire revolution that we're trying to basically build up here.

03:27:03.800 --> 03:27:07.560
[Amit Varma]: No, it's, it's incredible and another thing I was struck by is that you said that

03:27:07.560 --> 03:27:13.320
[Amit Varma]: the demand is so much that you can't possibly keep up. And therefore, even when you make mistakes,

03:27:13.320 --> 03:27:18.200
[Amit Varma]: even when some content isn't perfect, it is still extremely popular. Yes. So you're basically,

03:27:18.200 --> 03:27:22.360
[Amit Varma]: your learning curve is coming at a profit. Yes, yes. They're very forgiving.

03:27:24.440 --> 03:27:28.120
[Guest]: This user also realizes ki yaar iske pehle toh koi kuch dehi nahi raha tha. Koi toh hai.

03:27:28.120 --> 03:27:31.720
[Guest]: Haan, koi toh hai jo kam sakam Haryanvi mein film banara abhi, web series banara abhi.

03:27:31.720 --> 03:27:36.520
[Guest]: Toh, matlab, they are demanding also. That doesn't mean they're not demanding. They will,

03:27:36.520 --> 03:27:41.480
[Guest]: they will come, critique, they will tell us and they're okay. They're like, theek hai,

03:27:41.480 --> 03:27:47.400
[Guest]: as long as you're improving, they, they will come with a, jaise for example, humaari cable pehle

03:27:47.400 --> 03:27:52.760
[Guest]: phone app thi and we didn't have a Android TV app and we received huge amount of complaints

03:27:52.760 --> 03:27:57.720
[Guest]: about it. So they're demanding. They want the best of the experience. It was a revelation to me that

03:27:57.720 --> 03:28:02.840
[Guest]: the, the penetration of Android TV in India is so huge that we don't even realize it's the,

03:28:02.840 --> 03:28:07.000
[Guest]: matlab, we should build for those platforms. If there's an entrepreneur listening this,

03:28:07.000 --> 03:28:10.680
[Guest]: somewhere out there. So, they're demanding. They want the best of the experiences,

03:28:10.680 --> 03:28:15.480
[Guest]: but they're forgiving of the fact ki they realize ki yaar boss yeh aadmi kar raha hai kuch.

03:28:16.040 --> 03:28:20.920
[Guest]: Toh they want to, you know, stand by you. They want to stick with you. They want to support you.

03:28:22.120 --> 03:28:27.080
[Guest]: Jaise main logon ko bolta hai yaar, mera mote ek yeh bhi hai ki, any other OTT app, duniya mein

03:28:27.080 --> 03:28:31.000
[Guest]: log film dekhne ke liye, web series dekhne ke liye, content dekhne ke liye download karte hain.

03:28:31.000 --> 03:28:35.800
[Guest]: Humari app, woh baseline hai. Humari app, actual mein aadmi isliye download karte hain ki woh

03:28:35.800 --> 03:28:41.320
[Guest]: Haryanvi mein. Uske liye, it's a matter of pride. Jo koi bhi product manager hai na,

03:28:41.320 --> 03:28:45.080
[Guest]: kisi bhi product mein epic meaning dhundhta hai. Ki mai aisa kya bana doon ki is product

03:28:45.080 --> 03:28:48.280
[Guest]: mein epic meaning mil jaye. Because that's when you become irrational. And you, your

03:28:48.280 --> 03:28:53.880
[Guest]: retention becomes very high. Humari product mein by default hai woh. The epic meaning of the fact

03:28:53.880 --> 03:28:58.040
[Guest]: that ki, yaar aap Haryana ke liye kar rahe ho. Aap Haryanvi ke liye kar rahe ho. Thank you for

03:28:58.040 --> 03:29:02.840
[Guest]: doing this. It's a matter of pride for me. It's a very, very big deal for them. And this is a

03:29:02.840 --> 03:29:06.600
[Amit Varma]: very big reason why they buy the subscription basically. And not just pride, I would imagine

03:29:06.600 --> 03:29:12.760
[Amit Varma]: comfort zone also. Absolutely. So, I remember my father in his last years, he was brought up

03:29:12.760 --> 03:29:18.440
[Amit Varma]: in Calcutta and so very Bengali by culture and retired in Chandigarh and lived there till he

03:29:18.440 --> 03:29:22.760
[Amit Varma]: passed away. And in his last years, the only thing he would watch on television really was old

03:29:22.760 --> 03:29:28.280
[Amit Varma]: Bengali serials. Because it's that comfort zone factor, ki this is my language and that sense of,

03:29:28.280 --> 03:29:33.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, so I sort of totally get that. So, what are your sort of plans moving ahead now?

03:29:33.400 --> 03:29:38.120
[Amit Varma]: Haryanvi hai, Rajasthani hai, you know, do you see this as sort of an all India play,

03:29:38.120 --> 03:29:42.920
[Amit Varma]: ki har jagah hyper local karte hai? Because the hunger is clearly there. You have demonstrated

03:29:42.920 --> 03:29:47.880
[Amit Varma]: against all conventional wisdom that they are willing to pay. So, aage kya plans hai aapke?

03:29:47.880 --> 03:29:53.880
[Guest]: We have identified 18 such markets across the country, which have a minimum potential of 5

03:29:53.880 --> 03:29:58.840
[Guest]: million paying households. So, hum ek parivaar ko ek TG maante hain bhajaye ki individual ko,

03:29:58.840 --> 03:30:04.840
[Guest]: kyuki subscription ghar mein ek aadmi lega basically. So, 50 lakh people at least speak

03:30:05.480 --> 03:30:11.160
[Guest]: a dialect and there are 18 such dialects and small languages, which basically have a potential to

03:30:11.160 --> 03:30:15.960
[Guest]: replicate the same success all across. When we capture all these 18, we will be addressing

03:30:15.960 --> 03:30:22.520
[Guest]: 50 to 60 percent of India's population through their own local dialects, basically. 125 million

03:30:22.520 --> 03:30:28.840
[Guest]: households almost. We will most probably not do South a lot because wahan pe languages itself are

03:30:28.840 --> 03:30:33.240
[Guest]: playing that role and it's a very crowded market and like very expensive market. So,

03:30:33.240 --> 03:30:38.040
[Guest]: we probably will never do South. But everywhere else in this country, there's a huge potential.

03:30:38.840 --> 03:30:42.920
[Guest]: We're already live in Rajasthani. We're going to launch Bhojpuri,

03:30:42.920 --> 03:30:49.560
[Guest]: Maithili and Maghai within the next one year. And once we do that, then the rest of the Hindi belt,

03:30:49.560 --> 03:30:56.280
[Guest]: which is Awadhi, Bundeli and then Pahadi, Chhattisgarhi. We're already talking to a

03:30:56.280 --> 03:31:02.600
[Guest]: partner in Nepal to launch stage Nepali, something like that. Then Gujarati and basically Konkani and

03:31:02.600 --> 03:31:07.000
[Guest]: basically the entire set of these things. So, this is absolutely an all-India play.

03:31:07.000 --> 03:31:10.120
[Guest]: Isse main ek cheezo yaad aaya aapne usse main. Isse pe piche piche wale question bole jaye. I

03:31:10.120 --> 03:31:17.320
[Guest]: want to make a point there about homogeneity. India ka last linguistic survey based on

03:31:17.320 --> 03:31:21.160
[Guest]: dialects happened in 1901. Angrejo ne kiya tha. Humne uske baad kabhi nahi kiya.

03:31:22.120 --> 03:31:28.040
[Guest]: Unnis hajaar dialects identified huye the India mein usse maa pe. Unnis hajaar. Aaj kebal 700

03:31:28.040 --> 03:31:34.120
[Guest]: zinda hai usme se. Only 700 of them. Right? And it happened because of a simple reason that

03:31:34.120 --> 03:31:40.840
[Guest]: aajadi ke baad humne ek political agenda ke antaragat basically ek desh, ek bhaasha aur

03:31:40.840 --> 03:31:46.440
[Guest]: whatever bullshit basically we sold to people. And kuch toh colonial baggage tha. Kuch humne

03:31:46.440 --> 03:31:50.440
[Guest]: apne logon ko bata diya ki Angreji ye nahi bologe toh tum inferior ho. Ab chalo internet

03:31:50.440 --> 03:31:55.320
[Guest]: ke wajah se thankfully Hindi pe thoda wapis yun aagaya ki Hindi bol sakte hain aap kisi

03:31:55.320 --> 03:31:58.440
[Guest]: business meeting mein, bhaasha mein, ye podcast mein hum Hindi bol pa rahe hain.

03:31:58.440 --> 03:32:02.680
[Guest]: Nahin toh wo bhi allowed nahi tha pehle toh. Dialect pe toh bilkul na baba na type ka

03:32:02.680 --> 03:32:06.600
[Guest]: situation hai. Right? And we feel, we make those people feel very bad. There are still

03:32:06.600 --> 03:32:10.360
[Guest]: schools in this country in the rural parts where jab aap apni local language mein or

03:32:10.360 --> 03:32:15.240
[Guest]: dialect mein bolte ho toh aap pe fine lagta hai. Wow. Theek hai. It used to happen in our

03:32:15.240 --> 03:32:21.560
[Guest]: school and there are many friends that I have heard saying the same thing. Right? Toh bas

03:32:21.560 --> 03:32:29.880
[Guest]: ye itna sa hi sapna hai ki across the country isko karein aur so that people can feel their

03:32:29.880 --> 03:32:36.920
